<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Investigating Sudan Bomb Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- The United Nations is sending a medical  
team to Sudan to check out rebel claims that the government dropped 
chemical or biological bombs on two towns held by southern rebels, 
a senior U.N. official said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The team will leave tomorrow and will camp outside the towns of  
Kaaya and Lainya in Western Equatoria province, where the Sudanese 
air force allegedly dropped the bombs on July 23, said Dr. Sharad 
Sapra, a Nairobi-based coordinator for Operation Lifeline Sudan. 
</P>
<P>
	Operation Lifeline Sudan is an umbrella group of U.N. and  
private relief agencies working in Sudan. 
</P>
<P>
	Sapra said two employees of the World Food Program and one from  
the Sudan Relief and Rehabilitation Association, the rebel's relief 
agency, were affected by the unidentified substance while passing 
through Lainya. 
</P>
<P>
	One of them underwent tests at a Nairobi hospital, but the  
results were not ready Tuesday, Sapra said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said investigators will also provide medical treatment to  
villagers, if needed. Team members plan to take medical samples to 
determine what chemical substances, if any, were involved. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the rebel Sudanese People's Liberation Army said a  
government plane dropped 16 bombs in Lainya and six in Kaaya on 
July 23, the day unsuccessful peace talks to end the war concluded 
in Kenya. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is reported that a day after the bombing of these towns,  
children and men and women started to vomit blood,'' Samson Kwanje, 
a rebel spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said since the bombing ``almost all pregnant women have  
aborted or are gravely ill'' and goats, sheep, cats, dogs and birds 
are dying in large numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	The pro-government Akhbar Al-Youm newspaper quoted army  
spokesman Gen. Mohamed Osman as saying that such reports are a 
smear campaign against the Sudanese government. 
</P>
<P>
	``These rebel allegations are mere lies and fabrications,''  
Yassin was quoted as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1.9 million people have been killed in Sudan's civil  
war and war-related famines since the war began in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels are fighting Sudan's central Muslim-dominated  
government, seeking autonomy and a greater share in the country's 
wealth for the south, where people are predominantly Christian or 
animists. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
