<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pan Am Games Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Charles Levarity Smith, a member of  
the Bahamas softball team at the Pan American Games, has been 
charged with sexual assault. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, 36, has been released on $500 ($340 U.S.) bail and told  
to appear in court Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The alleged victim is a member of the cleaning staff at the  
athletes village just outside Portage la Prairie, Manitoba. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was alleged to have occurred on Monday, it was reported on  
Monday and investigated and in consultation with a crown attorney 
the criminal charge of sexual assault was laid,'' Royal Canadian 
Mounted Police spokesman Steve Saunders said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Saunders said it will be up to the courts to decide whether  
Smith can return home with the rest of his team. The games end 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith is a third baseman for the Bahamas.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *RECOVERING MASCOT:* Brenda Reinhardt, a Pan Am Games volunteer,  
hopes to be back at work soon as Pato, the wood duck who serves as 
a mascot for the event. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday night, she suffered neck injuries when she was rammed  
in the head from behind while walking to the baseball stadium. She 
said the force of the blow rocked her head inside the heavy helmet. 
</P>
<P>
	A man is in custody and is expected to be charged with assault.  
</P>
<P>
	``This doesn't detroy any of the pure joy I've experienced doing  
this,, Reinhardt said. ``It's just one silly person, that's all it 
is.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SHOOTOUT SORROW:* Canada's shot at the gold medal in women's  
soccer disappeared with a penalty shot off the goalpost. A second 
opportunity, no less, for 16-year-old Claire Rustad. 
</P>
<P>
	With the game tied 2-2 against Mexico, a shootout was held.  
Mexico's first three shooters all connected, then midfielder Rustad 
shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Her kick was directly into goalkeeper Linny Quinones, but  
American referee Kari Seitz said the keeper moved forward before 
the ball was struck. 
</P>
<P>
	That gave Rustad another kick, which she sent off the post to  
her right. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a horrible way to lose, but we have to deal with it,''  
the teen-ager said. ``I was happy when I let it go. I had it in my 
mind that it was going in the net. And it didn't. It was an inch 
off. 
</P>
<P>
	``Second chances can be good and they can be bad. You can see  
how they can be bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mexico made its next two attempts to move into the gold medal  
game against the United States. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WOUNDED KNEE:* Jordie McTavish, who replaced Steve Nash of the  
Dallas Mavericks on Canada's Pan Ams basketball team, dislocated 
his right knee in a game with Argentina. McTavish had 11 points and 
nine assists heading into the final minute of the game. He drove to 
the basket and tumbled to the ground in pain. 
</P>
<P>
	With McTavish gone, the Canadians are down to their third-string  
point guard, Sherman Hamilton. 
</P>
<P>
	``He played really well tonight,'' Hamilton said of McTavish.  
``We've seen him progress all summer. This is a real sad 
situation.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
