<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Trumpets Welfare Changes  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- President Clinton gave his welfare reform plan a  
boost today, saying the nation now has the smallest percentage of 
people on public assistance rolls since 1967. Clinton called 
welfare recipients ``people who are good for the bottom line,'' and 
urged business leaders to hire more of them. Clinton also urged 
Republican leaders in Congress to resist using $4.2 billion in 
unspent federal welfare funds for other purposes, saying the money 
could go toward reducing welfare rolls even further. 

</P>
<P>
	Utah Man Pleads Guilty in Olympics Case  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Salt Lake City businessman agreed today to  
plead guilty to a misdemeanor tax violation in connection with the 
2002 Olympic Games, the first criminal case in the federal probe of 
a bribery scandal. The Justice Department said the plea stemmed 
from a scheme in which David E. Simmons helped the son of an 
International Olympic Committee member obtain lawful permanent 
resident status by offering the son a fraudulent job at his 
company, the government said. The father had a vote on which city 
would get the 2002 Winter Olympics. Salt Lake City was awarded the 
Games. 

</P>
<P>
	Pilots, NTSB Make More Rest Request  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Airline pilots made their case before Congress  
today for reduced work periods. Current federal rules say pilots 
may not fly more than eight hours and must receive at least eight 
hours of rest in a 24-hour period. The pilots want to increase the 
rest period to at least 10 hours. The Federal Aviation 
Administration agrees, but also wants to increase the pilots' 
flight time to 10 hours, and all flying would have to be done 
within a 14-hour window. The FAA argues the airlines would get more 
flight time from the pilots in any given day, and the pilots would 
get more rest. 

</P>
<P>
	Zapruder Heirs To Get $16M for Film  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Arbitrators compromised today on the  
compensation for the family of Abraham Zapruder for his home movie 
of John F. Kennedy's assassination, awarding Zapruder's heirs $16 
million, less than the $30 million they sought, but more than the 
government's $1 million offer. A government panel decided two years 
ago that the film was the property of the people of the United 
States. And under the Constitution, that meant that the Zapruder 
family had to be fairly compensated. The Justice Department says 
the resolution of this dispute will ensure that the film ``will be 
protected for scholarly and research uses.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Son of Homeless Woman Sues L.A.  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The son of a homeless woman fatally shot  
after she allegedly threatened a policeman with a screwdriver is 
suing the city and police department. Richard Mitchell's civil 
rights lawsuit contends that his frail, mentally ill mother posed 
no threat to the officers when she was killed May 21. Margaret 
Mitchell, 54, had been pushing a shopping cart down trendy La Brea 
Avenue when two officers stopped her and asked if the cart was 
stolen. Police said the woman then thrust a screwdriver at one of 
the officers, who fell to one knee and fired a shot into her chest. 

</P>
<P>
	Tim McGraw Leads CMA Nominations  
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Tim McGraw was nominated for seven  
Country Music Association awards today, and will compete with 1998 
winner Garth Brooks for the top award of best entertainer. McGraw's 
other nominations include best male vocalist, album (``A Place in 
the Sun'') and single (``Please Remember Me''). Vince Gill, the 
most awarded performer in CMA history with 17, will host the show 
for the eighth straight year. He got five nominations. Nominees for 
best entertainer along with Brooks and McGraw were George Strait, 
Shania Twain and the Dixie Chicks. 

</P>
<P>
	Casino Chips Showing Up in Church  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Hours after Detroit's first casino opened just  
steps from the Most Holy Trinity Catholic Church, gambling chips 
began clattering in the collection plate. The Rev. Russell Kohler 
wouldn't say how big the jackpot is, but he planned to cash the 
chips in and use the money to help the poor. The Michigan Gaming 
Control Board says the exchange is perfectly legal. It's done in 
other places -- in Las Vegas, many cab drivers accept chips as tips. 
The MGM Grand Detroit opened in the Motor City on Thursday. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 2  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 2.22 to 10,648.18. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,957-975. The Nasdaq was down 37.17 to 
2,586.46. 

</P>
<P>
	Isiah Thomas Purchases CBA  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- NBA great Isiah Thomas is buying a majority stake  
in the Continental Basketball Association for about $10 million and 
plans to overhaul the league. The CBA's nine teams are organized as 
an association with approximately 40 owners. The former Pistons 
star and Raptors GM said he plans to reorganize it into a single 
entity league with the nine franchises reporting to the league. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
