<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGwire's 500th Home Run Ball Eyed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The speculation has begun on how much Mark  
McGwire's 500th home run ball might be worth. 
</P>
<P>
	Going into Tuesday's game with San Diego, McGwire needed two  
homers to reach 500. He would be only the 16th player to reach the 
milestone. 
</P>
<P>
	The person who comes up with it will be holding a baseball worth  
an estimated $100,000 for starters. 
</P>
<P>
	But this figure pales in comparison to last season's  
record-setting 70th home run ball. That ball brought more than $3 
million at auction. 
</P>
<P>
	Memorabilia dealer Michael Barnes, who helped sell McGwire's  
70th home run ball last season, is working on the idea of a cash 
advance for the right to auction the 500th ball in October. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the problems last season was that we had to weigh all  
these upfront offers, money, royalties, annuities, before deciding 
on a public auction,'' Barnes said. ``One of the benefits this time 
around is, I've stayed in contact with all the underbidders from 
the 70th home run ball auction, and this is the next big thing on 
the horizon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barnes believes the baseball might bring as much as $1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	It's been almost a year since Paul Ozersky, a 26-year-old  
researcher at Washington University's Genome Sequencing Center, 
became a millionaire thanks to the 70th home run ball. Some of the 
money he made with the ball he is giving back to three charities. 
</P>
<P>
	The man who paid more than $3 million for that ball was Canadian  
comic book, toy and video tycoon, Todd McFarlane. He called the 
McGwire 70th home run ball ``the big boy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McFarlane bought nine home run baseballs from last season,  
including McGwire's first, 63rd, 67th, 68th and 69th, and Sammy 
Sosa's 33rd, which broke the record for the number of homers in a 
month. He also bought Sosa's 61st and 66th home run balls. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
