<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N. Irish Indicted for Mailing Guns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Three people from Northern Ireland  
and a another from the Irish Republic have been indicted on federal 
charges they bought guns in Florida and mailed them to Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	The four men, one of whom is allegedly connected to the Irish  
Republican Army, are accused of violating the Arms Export Control 
Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Two men bought 44 handguns from a Boynton Beach gun dealer and  
the group then mailed 15 of the weapons, without export licenses or 
proper authorization, to different addresses in Ireland, according 
to an indictment handed down Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Named in the indictment were Siobhan Browne, an Irish citizen  
living in south Florida; and Anthony Smyth, Conor Anthony Claxton 
and Martin Mullan, all citizens of the United Kingdom and Northern 
Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal prosecutor said Claxton admitted involvement with the  
IRA, but Claxton's attorney denied the claim and authorities have 
acknowledged they have not confirmed if the men are affiliated with 
IRA. 
</P>
<P>
	All four were charged with conspiracy to export firearms without  
a license or approval, exporting the guns without export licenses 
or written approval, and using the Postal Service to illegally 
export the handguns. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
