<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Richardson Calls Lee's Claims 'Bunk' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson on Tuesday  
accused Wen Ho Lee, a government scientist suspected of giving 
China details about America's nuclear arsenal, of trying to use the 
``race card'' to defend his actions. He also said Lee's claim that 
top-secret weapons code work is often done on unclassified 
computers was ``pure bunk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lee, a naturalized U.S. citizen born in Taiwan, was fired from  
his top-secret job at Los Alamos last March for security violations 
after being investigated on suspicion of providing China 
information in the 1980s about a key U.S. nuclear warhead. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing on CBS' ``60 Minutes'' on Sunday, Lee suggested he was  
targeted in a three-year espionage investigation, because he was 
the only Asian-American in the weapons design group. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities needed a scapegoat, he said. ``They think I'm  
perfect for them,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked about that claim on Tuesday, Richardson reacted  
sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	``The suspect unfairly tried to use the race card,'' Richardson  
said. ``He tried to portray himself as a victim after he massively 
violated our security system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lee has not been charged with any crime, although a federal  
grand jury in Albuquerque, N.M., reportedly is taking testimony in 
the case. His lawyer, Mark Holscher, did not return a telephone 
call to his office in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	During his interview on ``60 Minutes,'' Lee categorically denied  
giving secrets to China or anyone else. He also claimed that 
weapons designers routinely use unclassified computers to work on 
sensitive weapons codes. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee admitted he had transferred top-secret computer codes -- a  
legacy of warhead development and testing -- from the highly secured 
computer system to his personal office computer, which is an 
unclassified system and linked to the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do that routinely. ... It's a very common practice'' among  
the weapons designers, Lee insisted. He reportedly has told 
investigators that he made the transfers, dating back to 1995, to 
provide a ``backup'' for the codes. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson reacted sharply to that claim too.  
</P>
<P>
	``That is pure bunk,'' Richardson said. ``This `everybody does  
it' business is just a sorry excuse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson has called Lee's transferring of codes from a secure  
computer to his office PC -- which came to light after Lee was fired 
when his computer was searched -- a ``massive violation of our 
security system'' although it has not been determined that any of 
the files ever left the laboratory. 
</P>
<P>
	At Los Alamos, nuclear weapons scientists with super-secret  
``Q'' clearances work in two totally independent computer systems. 
One contains top-secret nuclear weapons codes and can be used only 
by a small number of scientists with no outside access. The other 
system has fewer safeguards, can be penetrated from outside the lab 
by sophisticated hackers, and is not supposed to contain top-secret 
material. Material also could have been sent outside through the 
unsecured system, although tighter controls have been installed in 
recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Los Alamos weapons scientists and managers, speaking on  
condition of not being identified, acknowledge that materials 
occasionally have been transferred from the secure system to the 
unsecured system. 
</P>
<P>
	But these transfers generally involved material that had been  
unclassified but was being used in the top-secret system. Even if 
there were no criminal intent, transferring top-secret codes to the 
unclassified system would be considered ``stupid'' and a momentous 
blunder, said one weapons scientist who has worked at Los Alamos 
for more than a dozen years. 
</P>
<P>
	The codes in question in the Lee case involved so-called  
``Legacy Codes'' that amount to an archived history of warhead 
development and testing over the years. While not a recipe for 
making nuclear bombs, the codes would provide valuable information 
about weapons development, scientists said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
