<HEADLINE> Clinton Releases $55M for Cooling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today released $55 million  
in federal aid to help residents of nine states cope with the heat. 
</P>
<P>
	The money, provided under a program that is used more often to  
help low-income people pay for heat during the winter, may be used 
to buy air conditioners, fans and other relief. 
</P>
<P>
	Illinois will get $15.9 million; Kentucky $7.7 million; Missouri  
$7.6 million; Indiana $7.1 million; Wisconsin $4.4 million; Iowa 
$3.4 million; Kansas $3.3 million; Minnesota $3 million; and 
Nebraska $2.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement was made as the president flew to Chicago,  
where he visited workers helping the elderly, lower income 
residents and other vulnerable people suffering from the heat. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been very, very tough. You've done a great job and I am  
profoundly grateful,'' he told the aides. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton especially encouraged elderly people with air  
conditioners to turn their units on and not worry about high 
electric bills because assistance is available. 
</P>
<P>
	``People should never have to worry in this country about  
risking their lives because they can't pay their power bills,'' he 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
