<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Waste Management Meets Low Estimate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Waste Management Inc., whose stock price shrunk  
in half last month in the wake of two separate warnings of reduced 
earnings, met lowered expectations Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's No. 1 trash hauler earned $371.8 million after  
special items, or 58 cents a share, compared with $243.2 million, 
or 41 cents a share, in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts initially had Houston-based Waste Management earning 78  
cents per share, then lowered their estimate to 67 cents after the 
company's July 6 warning that trash collection revenues were much 
lower than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the company issued a second warning that revised  
accounting procedures and even worse income than first thought 
would depress earnings to between 58-60 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Waste Management's share price, which had peaked at $60 in May,  
plummeted into the $25-$26 range in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Waste Management fell $1.25 to $24.18 3/4 or 4.9  
percent in trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Waste Management also said Tuesday that an internal audit might  
cause it to restate first-quarter results. The company singled out 
$95 million reported as operating income that instead should have 
been calculated as non-recurring items. 
</P>
<P>
	A revised first-quarter report could reduce earnings to 52 cents  
a share from 61 cents. Analysts at the time had expected 62 cents. 
</P>
<P>
	Second-quarter results excluded a one-time expense of $49.3  
million, or 8 cents a share, on pre-tax charges, costs related to 
merger activity and the early retirement of debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues grew 2.6 percent to $3.33 billion from $3.25 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite healthy profits, investors have punished Waste  
Management because earnings initially were expected to be at least 
$100 million better. The company has blamed poor forecasting and 
its chief financial officer took another position within the 
company last month. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first six months of the year, Waste Management earned  
$755.4 million, or $1.25 per share, compared to $442.3 million, or 
77 cents per share, in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month revenues rose to $6.41 billion from $6.22 billion in  
1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
