<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                       *Abdel Wahab al-Bayati    	
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Abdel Wahab al-Bayati, a renowned Iraqi  
writer who revolutionized Arabic poetry while spending half his 
life in exile, died Tuesday of a heart attack in Damascus. He was 
73. 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Bayati sought refuge in Jordan after quitting his diplomatic  
post in Madrid, Spain, in disgust following Iraq's 1990 invasion of 
Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Saddam Hussein's government stripped him of his  
citizenship after he visited Saudi Arabia to participate in a 
cultural festival. 
</P>
<P>
	After his graduation from Baghdad University in 1950, al-Bayati  
became a teacher, but was soon dismissed for his leftist political 
opinions. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1954, he went into exile, first to Syria and then to the  
Soviet Union and Egypt. He returned to Iraq after the 1958 anti- 
monarchy coup, but later fled again after disagreements with the 
next government. 
</P>
<P>
	He returned after the 1968 coup, but fled a few years later when  
the regime began a brutal campaign against leftists. In 1980, 
Saddam assigned him to Iraq's diplomatic mission in Madrid in an 
attempt to win him over to his side. 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Bayati was one of the first Arab poets who broke away from  
classical forms of poetry and started what later became known as 
free verse. 

</P>
<P>
                      *Russell Inslee Clark Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	WALLINGFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Russell Inslee Clark Jr., former  
president of the prestigious Horace Mann School in New York and 
Yale admissions dean, died Tuesday of a heart attack. He was 64. 
</P>
<P>
	A Yale graduate, Clark became dean of the school's Trumbell  
College in 1963. He was Yale's dean of admissions from 1965 to 
1969, successfully pushing for the admission of women. He also 
lectured in sociology. 
</P>
<P>
	He became headmaster of Horace Mann in 1970. During a period of  
rapid change, he eliminated the traditional dress code of jacket 
and tie, oversaw the prep school's merger with Barnard School in 
1973 and pushed for the admission of girls, which began in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	He was promoted to president in 1981, putting him in charge of  
Horace Mann's four campuses in New York and Connecticut. During his 
tenure, the school's enrollment increased from 600 to 1,640, its 
staff more than doubled from 125 to 300 and its annual budget grew 
from $1 million to $15 million. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Robert S. Gawthrop III    	
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- U.S. District Court Judge Robert S. Gawthrop  
III, whose cases included one involving a law firm accused of 
firing a young associate with the AIDS virus, died Sunday of 
cancer. He was 56. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the 1994 case ended in a settlement, Gawthrop wrote the  
first opinion that people who show no symptoms of AIDS can still be 
considered disabled under the Americans with Disabilities Act. 
</P>
<P>
	The case had striking similarities to the one depicted in the  
Academy Award-winning movie ``Philadelphia,'' which was released in 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other notable cases in Gawthrop's court were the 1996  
sentencing of five police officers who pleaded guilty in a 
corruption scandal; the 1996 racketeering and bribery trial of 
former Rep. Joseph McDade, R-Pa.; and the lawsuit brought by 
parents against the Chester-Upland School District, in which he 
appointed a special master to implement education reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	He was elected to the Chester County Common Pleas Court in 1978.  
Former President Reagan nominated him to the federal bench in 1987. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Alberto Gironella    	
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Alberto Gironella, a leading Mexican  
surrealist painter and promoter of literature and the arts, died 
Monday after a long illness. He was 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Details surrounding the death of Gironella, a gruff Bohemian who  
fiercely protected his privacy, were not immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper La Jornada on Tuesday, which he helped found in  
1984, published a front-page photo, but no story. The photo caption 
said he died Monday and that his body was immediately cremated 
according to his wishes. 
</P>
<P>
	A close friend, Homero Aridjis, president of the international  
writers' organization PEN International, said Gironella had been 
suffering from terminal bone cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Gironella painted his own surrealist versions of subjects as  
diverse as Emiliano Zapata, the Mexican Revolution leader, and 
Madonna, the singer, as well as his own interpretations of such 
famous classical paintings as Spaniard Diego Velazquez's ``Las 
Meninas'' and works by the Spanish painter Goya. 
</P>
<P>
	He wrote poetry for a while and a novel, ``Tiburcio Esquila,''  
which was never published. Frustrated, he turned to painting and 
was immediately successful. In 1960, he was awarded a prize at the 
Paris Biennial for Young Painters. 
</P>
<P>
	Several years later, Gironella and many younger artists broke  
away from the politically inspired surrealist masters, such as the 
Communist muralists David Alfaro Siqueiros and Diego Rivera, who 
concentrated on depicting the poverty and suffering of Mexico's 
working classes. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger artists insisted that art should not necessarily be  
political and artists should be freer to invent and fantasize and 
not be subjected to the constraints of what the older ones called 
``social conscience.'' 

</P>
<P>
                       *Sunthorn Kongsompong    	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Gen. Sunthorn Kongsompong, a  
chain-smoking general who led a coup in 1991 that toppled 
Thailand's civilian government, ushering in the country's last 
period of military rule, died Monday of lung cancer. He was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	The bloodless takeover led by Sunthorn and other senior officers  
ended a year later, shortly after troops gunned down some 50 
pro-democracy demonstrators in the streets of Bangkok. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunthorn had since lived in obscurity. Like other figures behind  
the so-called National Peacekeeping Council that embodied the coup, 
he went unpunished for deposing Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan 
and for his alleged role in the massacre known as Bloody May. 
</P>
<P>
	The takeover in 1991 was the last in a score of coups or  
attempted coups since Thailand ended absolute monarchy in 1932. The 
target was the four-year-old government led by Chatichai, which was 
notorious for corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	Pledging to clean up politics, the generals set up the National  
Peacekeeping Council with Sunthorn, supreme armed forces commander, 
as chairman. But he was generally seen as a figurehead, with real 
power in the hands of Gen. Suchinda Kraprayoon, the army commander. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Jim Kyle    	
</P>
<P>
	BAYTOWN, Texas (AP) -- Jim Kyle, a columnist for The Baytown Sun  
whose career in newspapers spanned more than a half-century, died 
Saturday of cancer. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Kyle, an award-winning journalist, wrote a humorous column that  
began in The Sun in 1966. His last column was published July 11. 
</P>
<P>
	He previously worked at newspapers in Odessa, Wichita Falls and  
Indianapolis. He had dined with President Reagan, landed on the 
aircraft carrier Lexington in the Gulf of Mexico, rode the USS San 
Jacinto from Mississippi to Houston and covered Pope John Paul II's 
visit to Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Kyle, who also had worked as a circulation manager for The Sun,  
covered the Indianapolis 500 for 38 consecutive years. 
</P>
<P>
	A collection of his columns were compiled for a book, ``Awhile  
With Kyle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, Julia; four daughters, three sons  
and 12 grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Mary Linscott    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Sister Mary Linscott, who led the Congregation of  
the Sisters of Notre Dame de Namur, an international religious 
order with 4,000 teachers on four continents, died June 14 in 
Liverpool, according to The Times of London. She was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Linscott worked in both England and Vatican City as she rose  
through the Catholic Church, achieving a position and level of 
responsibility rare for a woman. 
</P>
<P>
	Linscott first was exposed to the Notre Dame Congregation  
through her high school teachers. The Congregation was founded in 
1586 in Napoleonic France and today is working under many different 
educational systems. 
</P>
<P>
	She entered the Notre Dame de Namur novitiate in 1945.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1969, she became superior general of the Notre Dame  
Congregation, a position normally held by a Belgian or a French 
women. She then was elected president of the Union of International 
Superiors General in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	Linscott initially was responsible for dealing only with the  
religious communities of women, but in 1985 she was promoted and 
given the same responsibility for men. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Robert H. Mollohan    	
</P>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) -- Robert H. Mollohan, a nine-term  
congressman and father of U.S. Rep. Alan Mollohan, D-W.Va., died 
Tuesday of cancer. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Mollohan died at Washington (D.C.) Hospital Center.  
</P>
<P>
	Mollohan was elected to the U.S. House in 1952 along with future  
U.S. senator and friend Robert C. Byrd (D-W.Va.). 
</P>
<P>
	Mollohan served two terms in Congress before running for West  
Virginia governor in 1956. He defeated four others in the 
Democratic primary but lost to Republican Cecil Underwood, who 
became the youngest governor in state history. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1966, Mollohan lost to Arch A. Moore Jr. in his bid to return  
to Congress. When Moore became governor in 1968, Mollohan won the 
U.S. House seat and served until his retirement in 1982, the same 
year Alan Mollohan was elected to the first of nine consecutive 
terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the elder Mollohan's major initiatives was securing the  
Pratt &AMP; Whitney aircraft facility at Bridgeport's Benedum Airport. 
He also was instrumental in passage of a federal Emergency Medical 
Services Act. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Yitzhak Rafael    	
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Yitzhak Rafael, a former legislator and  
government minister who helped bring hundreds of thousands of 
immigrants to Israel in its early years, died Tuesday after a long 
illness. He was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	Rafael, who came to Israel from Poland in 1935, headed the  
immigration department in the quasi-governmental Jewish Agency in 
the nation's early years and oversaw waves of immigration from 
1948-1953. 
</P>
<P>
	He made ``brave decisions at a young age,'' National Religious  
Party lawmaker Yigal Bibi told The Associated Press, crediting 
Rafael with refusing to limit Jewish immigration despite the strain 
on the new state's resources. 
</P>
<P>
	Rafael was religious affairs minister from 1974-1977 and served  
seven terms as a lawmaker from the National Religious Party. After 
retiring from public life, he wrote and published religious and 
Zionist writings as head of a Jerusalem institute affiliated with 
the party. In 1981, he published an autobiography, ``You Didn't 
Find the Light by Chance.'' 

</P>
<P>
                          *Kenneth J. Stack    	
</P>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn., (AP) -- Kenneth J. Stack, a copy editor at The  
Hartford Courant for 20 years, died Monday of cancer. He was 59. 
</P>
<P>
	Stack began working at The Courant in 1977. He was responsible  
for editing stories, assigning space in the newspaper and writing 
headlines. 
</P>
<P>
	He also worked at newspapers in Massachusetts, Pennsylvania and  
Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	Stack is survived by his wife, Kathleen Heasly Stack, and  
children Gregory, Martha and Megan. Megan Stack is a newswoman in 
the Dallas bureau of The Associated Press. 
</P>
