<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybeans Climb on Crop News / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Corn and soybean futures continued their steep  
climb Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade after the government 
sharply lowered its assessment of crop conditions in major growing 
states. Wheat futures retreated 
</P>
<P>
	Investors in corn and soybeans ignored forecasts for beneficial  
showers to fall in the next 10 days over major growing areas as 
they digested the U.S. Agriculture Department's weekly crop update. 
The USDA reported conditions worsened in Illinois and Indiana in 
the past week under hot, dry weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Crops in Ohio and Eastern states also were suffering under  
severe drought conditions. The unexpected turn in the weather 
during a growing season that has generally been beneficial to crop 
development now has analysts revising downward their fall 
production figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures retreated after the government reported an  
improvement in spring wheat conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 11 cents to $2.87 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn rose 4 1/4 cents to $2.30 3/4 a bushel; December oats fell 
1 1/4 cents to $1.17 a bushel; November soybeans rose 15 1/4 cents to 
$4.78 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and lean hog futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while pork bellies rose sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell 0.43 cent to 64.27 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell 0.50 cent to 76.32 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs fell 0.25 cent to 49.70 cents a pound; August pork bellies 
jumped 4.5 cents to 59.62 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
