<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Withdraws From Delaware Primary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- Republicans have withdrawn from next  
year's Delaware presidential primary, saying it's not worth feuding 
with New Hampshire over an event that major candidates will 
boycott. 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire officials, upset that Delaware's primary was  
scheduled just four days after their first-in-the-nation event, 
persuaded candidates not to campaign in the First State. 
</P>
<P>
	Delaware GOP Chairman Basil Battaglia said Monday, the deadline  
for opting out, that Republicans are studying options such as 
having a caucus vote to select a presidential candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``To continue with a primary that almost every major candidate  
in both parties is boycotting accomplishes very little,'' Battaglia 
said. ``Under current law, it is very possible the current 
front-runner won't even be on our ballot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush is the Republican front-runner.  
</P>
<P>
	Delaware Democrats plan to proceed with a primary, Chairman  
Richard Bayard said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
