<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Senate Rejects Farm Bailout Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today voted 54-44 to reject a  
Democrat-backed $11 billion farm economy bailout bill. The 
Republican-controlled Senate defeated the plan after Democrats 
narrowly failed to kill a $7 billion GOP emergency farm package. A 
final vote on the GOP plan was put off while Democrats and 
Republicans tried to find a compromise. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia Campaign Intensified  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- State-run Yugoslav media and senior  
government officials intensified their campaign against the 
opposition, and accused the West of trying to put President 
Slobodan Milosevic's opponents in power. The stepped-up effort came 
after independent opposition figures released a platform calling 
for a transitional government to replace Milosevic. President 
Clinton and other Western leaders have said Serbia will get no 
substantial reconstruction aid as long as Milosevic is in power. 

</P>
<P>
	US Wraps Up Honduran Reconstruction  
</P>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- U.S. national guardsmen who  
participated in the final phase of the aid effort to 
hurricane-devastated Honduras began to head home today. The 
seven-month program included 2,000 guardsmen who built three 
medical clinics and four schools, dug four wells and repaired a 
bridge and 15 miles of highway damaged by Hurricane Mitch last 
fall. Hurricane Mitch killed more than 9,000 people and left more 
than 2 million homeless in Central America. Over 5,000 of those 
deaths, mainly due to flooding, occurred in Honduras. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Lauds Welfare Gains  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- President Clinton said today the percent of  
Americans on welfare assistance is at a 32-year low. ``As pleased 
as we are, we have to do more,'' Clinton told a national conference 
of the Welfare to Work Partnership. He met with some 350 business 
leaders and former welfare recipients in Chicago. Experts credit 
tough new rules and the strong economy for the reduction in welfare 
rolls. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Gives $55M in Heat Aid  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- President Clinton offered $55 million today to  
help low-income people in nine states pay their electricity bills 
or buy cooling equipment. He said he hoped the money would help 
encourage older people to run air conditioners without fear of high 
utility bills. Since July 19, the midsummer heat wave has killed at 
least 256, including 119 in Illinois. Joined by Mayor Richard 
Daley, Clinton thanked city workers in Chicago for helping to 
protect people from the heat. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's Candor Clarified  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton does not  
blame her husband's marital infidelity on the tumult of his 
childhood, her spokeswoman said today, despite the apparent link 
she drew in a Talk magazine article. ``She did not say the 
president's childhood in any way caused his behavior, nor does she 
believe that,'' spokeswoman Marsha Berry said. ``I think that she 
was basically stating some feelings about his childhood, but that 
they do not excuse his behavior,'' Berry said. 

</P>
<P>
	JFK Film Price Is $16M  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government must pay the heirs of Dallas  
dressmaker Abraham Zapruder $16 million for his 26-second film that 
captured the assassination of President Kennedy. In a 2-1 vote, 
announced by the Justice Department, arbitrators set the amount 
after the government and the Zapruder family could not agree on a 
price. The government offered $1 million; the family asked for $30 
million. In 1997, the film was declared to be the property of the 
federal government. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Up 31.35; Nasdaq Off 35.63  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks ended mixed today as a forecast of  
economic growth kept investors on edge about interest rates. The 
Dow Jones industrial average was up 31.35 to 10,677.31 after 
shifting between positive and negative for much of the day. On the 
NYSE, losers led gainers 1,876-1,122. The Nasdaq fell 35.63 to 
2,588 as tech stocks faltered. 

</P>
<P>
	Umpires Charge Unfair Labor Practice  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The umpires' union today filed unfair labor  
practice charges against the American and National leagues in an 
attempt to block them from ``unlawfully discharding'' 22 umpires. 
Major league baseball replaced the 22, beginning Sept. 2, after 
they submitted their resignations as a tool to start negotiations 
on a new contract. Other umpires were allowed to withdraw their 
resignations. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  
  	   	
</P>
