<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Recalls Dad and Civil Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, recalling his father's  
fights with bigots spewing the ``N-word,'' told the Progressive 
National Baptist Convention: ``I want to create a future where 
nobody knows that term.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While convention president C. Mackey Daniels introduced the  
campaigning Democrat as ``President Al Gore, one of the greatest 
leaders of all time,'' Gore said he was speaking Tuesday as 
``someone who is a child of the Kingdom and a person of strong 
faith.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He juiced up his standard campaign speech with Biblical  
references and a preacher's cadence. Many in the audience of black 
religious activists leapt to their feet when Gore said school 
districts should ``recruit more African-American teachers as role 
models for these boys and girls to look up to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Government should help parents with after-school care so young  
people can be safe and productive, ``without going home to the 
'Jerry Springer Show' or some other trashy program,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president cast the Democrats' fight with Republicans in  
Congress over tax cuts in stark class-warfare terms: The GOP 
leadership wants ``a risky tax scheme aimed at those at the top -- 
who already have much -- at the expense of our economy just at the 
time when it's starting to work for those at the bottom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke at length of his father, Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore  
Sr., who died last December, and his battle through the 1940s, 50s 
and 60s for civil rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``He supported the Voting Rights Act in 1965 and lost his next  
re-election. But his conscience won and he taught me that was more 
important than any election.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 23:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brown Widow Sees Congressional Seat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The widow of Rep. George E. Brown has  
decided to run for his seat, setting the stage for a tough 
Democratic primary in a campaign that will likely draw national 
attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Marta Macias Brown, 54, was expected to announce her candidacy  
as early as today, said Art Torres, chairman of the California 
Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sept. 21 election and likely November runoff will be closely  
watched as a bellwether one year before the 2000 congressional 
races, when Democrats will try to break the GOP's slim hold in the 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	The race will feature at least two Hispanic Democratic  
contenders in a Southern California district where the electorate 
is 27 percent Hispanic and growing. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown was the oldest living member of the House when he died  
July 15 following an infection he developed after heart surgery. He 
was 79 and had been elected to the House 18 times. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown was the third California congressman to die in office  
since October 1997. The other two widows -- Republican Mary Bono and 
Democrat Lois Capps -- captured their late husbands' seats. 
</P>
<P>
	``Running against a widow is always very difficult, because  
there's a sympathy factor,'' said Mike Madrid, political director 
for the state GOP when it fielded Tom Bordonaro against Capps, the 
widow of Democratic Rep. Walt Capps, last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Brown's leading Democratic opponent is Joe Baca, who  
alienated himself from Brown supporters by publicly mulling a run 
against the congressman in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Brown's candidacy further splinters the Democratic vote and  
virtually eliminates the possibility a Democrat will win a majority 
in the primary. Another Democrat, Donald Hubner, also plans to run. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Republicans likely to run are attorney and real estate  
businessman Elia Pirozzi, who lost to Brown last year; Linda Wilde, 
a Superior Court judge who lost in 1996 to Brown; and businessman 
John Corry. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 20:05:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Angolan Rebels Massacre 46 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Eyewitnesses said Angola's UNITA rebels  
drove 50 villagers from their homes in a northern town, fatally 
shot them and dumped their bodies in a nearby river, the Portuguese 
news agency Lusa reported Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The massacre is alleged to have taken place early Sunday in  
Quipacassa, Lusa said. 
</P>
<P>
	One witness, Mateus Sacaia, said the operation began at dawn  
when guerrillas shot 46 civilians who had recently returned to 
their homes from Malanje. They then hurled the bodies in the Cuanza 
River, Lusa said. 
</P>
<P>
	Independent verification of the report was not possible, and the  
UNITA leadership could not be contacted for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The government last week claimed to have retaken Kangandala from  
the rebels, but UNITA disputed the claim. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels have also denied responsibility for several mass  
graves containing hundreds of bodies, reportedly unearthed near the 
central highland city of Kuito. 
</P>
<P>
	Since a two-decade war flared again in December after four years  
of relative peace, the rebels have gained control over more than 
half the vast country, while the government remained set on 
defending major cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Government troops on Monday repelled a rebel attack targeting  
fuel depots owned by the state oil company Sonangol in the central 
city of Huambo, the state-controlled daily Jornal de Angola 
reported Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper reported that 10 rebels were killed in the clash.  
There was no mention of government casualties. 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting between the government and UNITA, a Portuguese acronym  
for the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, first 
erupted after the country in southwest Africa gained independence 
from Portugal in 1975. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 09:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Makes Small Stock Fraud 'Sweep' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal securities regulators announced  
enforcement actions today against 82 people and companies in 26 
cases of alleged stock fraud that bilked investors of millions of 
dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	As officials of the Securities and Exchange Commission announced  
the agency's second nationwide ``sweep'' against fraud involving 
small-company stocks, they also worried that a proposal by a key 
House committee that would reduce the SEC's budget could hamper 
their enforcement efforts if it became law. 
</P>
<P>
	``It certainly would cut into our ability to bring cases,'' SEC  
Enforcement Director Richard Walker said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest fraud sweep differed from the first, conducted last  
October, which cracked down on investment fraud over the Internet 
by people promoting small-company stocks who don't disclose they 
are paid to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, only four of the 26 cases involved the Internet,  
which allegedly was used to disseminate false information about 
companies to lure investors to their stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The people and companies targeted in the new sweep raked in some  
$12.5 million in illegal gains, the SEC said. 
</P>
<P>
	The current sweep includes a gamut of small-stock fraud cases,  
such as stock-price manipulation schemes, sales of unregistered 
stocks and ``boiler room'' frauds in which brokers make 
high-pressure, unsolicited phone calls to people to sell stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC's actions against the 82 people and companies included  
seeking civil injunctions, barring individuals from the securities 
industry and imposing sanctions against accountants and attorneys 
who participated. No fines were imposed. Some of the cases have 
been settled, with the companies and individuals involved neither 
admitting to nor denying wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker also warned that a House Appropriations Committee  
proposal could have ``serious consequences'' for the SEC's 
fraud-fighting efforts. The proposal, approved last week, includes 
$324 million in funding next year for the SEC -- less than the 
agency's requested $351 million and its current operating budget of 
$337.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The full House is expected to vote on the legislation this week  
before Congress adjourns for its summer recess. Parallel 
legislation already approved by the Senate would give the SEC 
$370.8 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 08:24:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strawberry Suspension Cut by Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Darryl Strawberry persuaded commissioner Bud  
Selig to cut his drug suspension short by a week. Next, he has to 
prove to the New York Yankees that he can play again. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry's 120-day suspension for his arrest on solicitation  
and drug charges April 14 was reduced Monday, making him eligible 
to play Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm feeling good and I'm ready to get on with my life,''  
Strawberry said in Tampa, Fla. ``I'm starting to get into the frame 
of mind of playing. I'm looking forward to it. I'm ready to get 
going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry's penalty was originally scheduled to run through  
Aug. 11. Selig decided to shorten the suspension after reviewing 
medical records and speaking to Strawberry twice. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good thing out of this for me was, it allowed the time off  
to really take care of myself physically and mentally,'' said 
Strawberry, who hasn't played since learning last Oct. 1 that he 
had colon cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Getting the suspension lifted and returning to the Yankees  
lineup for the first time in 10 months are different tasks. 
Strawberry's first priority is to prove at Triple-A Columbus that 
his surgically repaired left knee is healthy enough to play the 
outfield. 
</P>
<P>
	With Chili Davis entrenched at designated hitter, Strawberry  
will have to be able to play left field to get into the lineup 
consistently. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now we've got to find out how the knee is going to hold out,  
whether he can play the outfield,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``I 
think it's too far ahead right now. We all know what he brings to 
the table as an offensive threat, so it's tempting. But let's not 
get too excited until we see how his knee is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry is expected to play Wednesday night against Norfolk.  
Torre said Strawberry will need at least one week, probably more, 
before he will be ready to return to the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry has been working out at the Yankees' minor league  
complex in Tampa since July 9. His batting practice performances 
have shown that the majestic left-handed swing that has hit 332 
career homers hasn't deserted him. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he gets the chance to do it in the minors. After waiting for  
a ruling from Selig since July 22, Strawberry isn't concerned about 
how long it will take to return to the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's too far ahead,'' Strawberry said. ``I really haven't  
thought about that. I'm just taking it day by day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry, who was suspended 60 days for testing positive for  
cocaine in 1995, admitted last month that an alcohol relapse 
contributed to his arrest. He has been attending Alcoholics 
Anonymous meetings in Tampa, while working out. 
</P>
<P>
	He hasn't played in a game since the final week of the 1998  
season, before surgery for colon cancer forced him to miss the 
playoffs and the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been gone so long and we know everything he's been  
through,'' Davis said. ``To see him actually rise above everything 
else and come back, I know that's going to be uplifting for me. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry was one of the most popular Yankees in the clubhouse  
before the cancer and suspension. And his teammates aren't worried 
that his return could disrupt the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is a positive influence,'' Derek Jeter said. ``I don't see  
how Darryl could be a distraction. He's all about the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry's availability has been a recurring theme around the  
Yankees for the past five seasons. He joined the Yankees on Aug. 4, 
1995, after spending four weeks in the minors following his first 
drug suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	He played sporadically and was not brought back at the start of  
1996. After a stint in the independent Northern League, Strawberry 
was brought back to New York in July 1996 and helped the Yankees 
win the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	He played only 11 games in an injury-plagued 1997. He made his  
biggest contributions last season, hitting 24 homers in 295 at-bats 
before being diagnosed with colon cancer during last year's 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	His expected return this season was delayed by chemotherapy  
treatments and then the arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a unique organization,'' Torre said. ``Billy Martin  
came back five times. ... Distractions are always there. It's how 
you handle them that matters.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 01:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
