<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- After an initial downturn, European stocks closed  
higher Monday, boosted by receeding fears of a U.S. interest rate 
increase this month. 
</P>
<P>
	With little European corporate news, traders said the main issue  
was a key reading on the U.S. economy and what impact it might have 
when Federal Reserve officials meet on Aug. 24 to decide on the 
central bank's rate strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	A monthly survey of factory executives showed that manufacturing  
activity wasn't as brisk as expected during July. If the economy is 
slower than people thought, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan may not 
push for another boost in rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``The markets are bouncing from one economic number to another,  
all the while worried about short-term interest rates,'' said 
Richard Batty, European equities strategist at HSBC Markets in 
London. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies closed up  
0.41 points at 301.69, while the Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which 
tracks 297 companies in countries that joined the euro single 
currency, was down 0.57 points at 311.78. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index finished down 5.18 points at  
3633.44, while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index was up 5.95 points at 3629.86. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Insurance index was virtually unchanged.  
</P>
<P>
	Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index was up 0.5 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	The Paris CAC 40 index was 0.1 percent lower, Milan's MIBtel  
index rose 1.0 percent, and Madrid's IBEX-35 index was up 0.1 
percent. London's FTSE 100 index was up 0.9 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 07:50:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Economic Indicators Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A widely-watched indicator of future economic  
activity rose 0.3 points in June, chalking up gains in eight out of 
the past nine months and signaling that the U.S. economy could be 
in its longest expansion ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board, a private New York-based economic research  
group, reported today that its index of leading indicators stood at 
107.7 in June, up from 107.4 in May. The index also rose by the 
same amount in May. The last decline, in April, was 0.1. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Boldin, director of business cycle research at The  
Conference Board, said that while the economic expansion is 
``firmly on track,'' concerns that the Federal Reserve will raise 
interest rates could roil financial markets and create some 
uncertainty. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board's index of current economic activity rose  
by 0.4 points in June, while its lagging index decreased by 
0.4 1/8pomts. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the ten indicators that make up the leading index rose  
in June. The most significant increases came in manufacturers' new 
orders of consumer goods and materials, money supply, and the 
difference between long-term and short-term interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	During the six months ended June 30, the leading index rose 1.2  
pointw and seven of the 10 components advanced, the Conference 
Board said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several components of the leading indicators index gave details  
about the growing economy. Manufacturers took in $166.4 million of 
new orders in June, up from $162.3 million in May. Money supply 
rose to $3.962 billion from $3.947 billion. And the difference, or 
spread, between the yield on 10-year Treasury bonds and the 
overnight Federal Reserve lending rate rose to 1.14 percent from 
0.80 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	However, in a sign that the labor market may not be heating up  
enough to push wages higher, the average number of hours worked per 
week by production workers was 41.7, unchanged from May. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall index is calculated from a base of 100, set in 1992.  
</P>
<P>
	The stock and bond markets had little immediate reaction to the  
report. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
