<DOCNO> APW19990803.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 11:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Pilots, NTSB Make More Rest Request  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Airline pilots made their case before Congress  
today for reduced work periods. Current federal rules say pilots 
may not fly more than eight hours and must receive at least eight 
hours of rest in a 24-hour period. The pilots want to increase the 
rest period to at least 10 hours. The Federal Aviation 
Administration agrees, but also wants to increase the pilots' 
flight time to 10 hours, and all flying would have to be done 
within a 14-hour window. The FAA argues the airlines would get more 
flight time from the pilots in any given day, and the pilots would 
get more rest. 

</P>
<P>
	Zapruder Heirs To Get $16M for Film  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The family of the man who took the famous home  
movie of John F. Kennedy's assassination says a $16 million payment 
from the government is fair. The Zapruder family sought $30 million 
for Abraham Zapruder's film, but arbitrators ruled $16 million 
would be the compensation. An assassination panel decided two years 
ago that the film was the property of the people of the United 
States, meaning the Zapruder family had to be compensated. The 
government offered $1 million. The Justice Department says the 
resolution of this dispute will ensure that the film ``will be 
protected for scholarly and research uses.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Sweepstakes Cos. Face Crackdown  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate has voted to put new restrictions  
on the sweepstakes industry, saying too many people are being 
deceived into thinking that buying unwanted magazines and other 
items will help them win big prizes. The bill, passed 93-0 
yesterday, would require sweepstakes sponsors to include ``clear 
and conspicuous'' messages in their mailings telling consumers that 
no purchase is necessary to enter or win a sweepstakes. Violators 
could face fines of up to $2 million. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Investigating Sudan Bomb Report  
</P>
<P>
	NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- The United Nations is sending a medical  
team to Sudan to check out rebel claims that the government dropped 
chemical or biological bombs on two towns held by southern rebels, 
a senior U.N. official said today. The team will leave tomorrow and 
will camp outside the towns of Kaaya and Lainya in Western 
Equatoria province, where the Sudanese air force allegedly dropped 
the bombs on July 23, officials said. A Sudanese rebel spokesman 
said since the bombing ``almost all pregnant women have aborted or 
are gravely ill'' and goats, sheep, cats, dogs and birds are dying 
in large numbers. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Endorses Democrat Farm Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore today endorsed an $11  
billion assistance package for farmers that was proposed by Senate 
Democrats. But Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman declined to tell 
the Senate Agriculture Committee how much help he thought farmers 
needed, deciding not to choose between the Democrats' plan and a 
GOP proposal for nearly $7 billion in aid. A worldwide glut of 
grain has kept commodity prices low for the second year in a row, 
and USDA projects that net farm income will dip to $43.8 billion 
this year, about 4 percent off the average for the decade. 

</P>
<P>
	Woman Sues Cuba for 'Sham' Marriage  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A woman has sued Cuba, claiming it is responsible  
for sexual assaults she endured during her marriage to a man she 
says married her only to serve his own needs as a spy for the 
communist nation. Ana Margarita Martinez, former wife of Juan Pablo 
Roque, is seeking unspecified damages. The only defendant named is 
the Republic of Cuba. The lawsuit asserts that Martinez never would 
have married Roque had she known that he was using the marriage 
``as a mere pretext to carry out his spy mission for a terrorist 
state.'' Because of the deception, the suit says, sex between the 
pair constituted sexual battery. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 3  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 3.17 to 10,649.13. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,950-925. The Nasdaq was down 50.00 to 
2,573.63. 

</P>
<P>
	Utah Man Pleads Guilty in Olympics Case  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Salt Lake City businessman agreed today to  
plead guilty to a misdemeanor tax violation in connection with the 
2002 Olympic Games, the first criminal case in the federal probe of 
a bribery scandal. The Justice Department said the plea stemmed 
from a scheme in which David E. Simmons helped the son of an 
International Olympic Committee member obtain lawful permanent 
resident status by offering the son a fraudulent job at his 
company, the government said. The father had a vote on which city 
would get the 2002 Winter Olympics. Salt Lake City was awarded the 
Games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
