<DOCNO> APW19990803.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 14:46:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Source: MLS Chief To Be Removed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Doug Logan will be removed as commissioner of Major League  
Soccer in the second shakeup of senior management at the league in 
six months, a soccer source said. 
</P>
<P>
	MLS is expected to replace Logan with Don Garber, the senior  
vice president and managing director of NFL International, perhaps 
as soon as Wednesday, according to the source, who spoke on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The league scheduled a news conference for Wednesday in New York  
to make a ``significant announcement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Logan, who has been the league's only commissioner in its 3 1-2  
years, is fluent in Spanish and has aggressively marketed MLS to 
Hispanics, overseeing the acquisition of several Latin and South 
American players. 
</P>
<P>
	No team has folded or been moved since the MLS began play in  
1996, and Logan oversaw its expansion to Chicago and Miami, 
bringing the league to 12 teams. 
</P>
<P>
	However, flat television ratings have plagued the league since  
the beginning of its second year, and it is still well below the 
average crowd of 17,406 it achieved in its first season. Some team 
officials have grumbled privately about Logan, particularly 
following his dismissal of deputy commissioner Sunil Gulati in 
February. 
</P>
<P>
	Logan was not in his office Tuesday and MLS canceled his weekly  
conference call with reporters. No reason was given. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not commenting on the matter at the present time,''  
league spokesman Dan Courtemanche said. ``However, we do expect to 
have further details within the next 48 hours.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Logan's impending ouster was first reported Tuesday by The  
Washington Post, also citing unidentified sources. His contract 
with league runs through the 2000 season. 
</P>
<P>
	The 56-year-old Logan, who was born in Glen Ridge, N.J., and  
grew up in Cuba, was recruited by MLS after nearly 20 years in 
entertainment management and promotion, including seven years with 
Ogden Entertainment and three more with OCESA in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	After 15 years with the NFL, the 41-year-old Garber was  
appointed to his post at NFL International in October 1996, with 
the responsibility of promoting interest in American football 
worldwide. Among his duties are management of NFL Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Logan had predicted a 15 percent increase in average attendance  
from the league's first year to the second. But attendance actually 
fell from 17,406 to 14,619, a 16 percent drop. 
</P>
<P>
	It further fell to 14,312 last season but has rebounded to  
15,174 through this past weekend's games. 
</P>
<P>
	Gulati has been a major figure in American soccer for more than  
a decade, including having a key role in the organizing committee 
of the 1994 World Cup, the U.S. Soccer Federation and the formation 
of MLS. 
</P>
<P>
	His removal before the start of the season angered many in the  
league. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue was his decision last year to unilaterally exercise the  
league's option to renew the contract New York-New Jersey 
MetroStars midfielder Tab Ramos, a close friend. 
</P>
<P>
	Gulati reportedly did not consult with MetroStars management,  
which angered Stuart Subotnick, one of the club's two 
investor-operators. 
</P>
<P>
	MLS operates under a ``single-entity'' concept in which  
companies invest in the league and receive the rights to operate a 
club. The league contracts with all the players, assigns the major 
stars to clubs in the name of competitive balance and gate 
attraction, and pays them from a central fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the salaries the league negotiates with the players,  
each team must stay under a $1.7 million salary cap. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Umpires Charge Unfair Labor Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With unemployment less than a month away for  
one-third of its members, the umpires' union filed an unfair labor 
practice charge Tuesday against the American and National leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Owners in turn filed a grievance against the umpires, saying  
their mass resignations violated their labor contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Many labor lawyers say the National Labor Relations Board is  
more likely to rule for the owners than the umpires. To the 
individual umpires about to lose their jobs, the legal maneuvers 
may be their final hope. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to work as hard as I can to save my job,'' said a  
visibly angry Bill Hohn, one of the 22 umpires notified last week 
that baseball had accepted their resignations, which are effective 
Sept. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Umpires want the NLRB to issue a complaint against owners that  
the agency could use to seek an injunction in federal court to 
prevent baseball from getting rid of the 22. The board is expected 
to decide on the charge in 4-6 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the umpires contend the July 14 decision to submit  
their mass resignations was ``protected concerted action'' under 
federal labor law and did not violate the provision in their labor 
contract stating ``there shall be no strike nor other concerted 
work stoppage.' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see how that could sit in the parameters within the  
National Labor Relations Act,'' said Stanford law professor William 
Gould, the NLRB's former chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	In baseball's first statement since the controversy began,  
commissioner Bud Selig, AL president Gene Budig and NL president 
Len Coleman said the charge had no merit. 
</P>
<P>
	``The leagues will vigorously contest each and every  
allegation,'' they said. 
</P>
<P>
	The umpires held their news conference in a room at the Official  
All-Star Cafe filled with player jerseys. A sign of their plight 
was the absence of any umpire memorabilia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not the guys out there charging $6 for a beer, charging  
$5 for a hot dog,'' said Ed Montague, one of the NL umpires who is 
keeping his job. ``We're not the guys who raised World Series 
tickets from $75 to $150. But we're the ones who get beat on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Umpires, fearful that baseball would lock them out next year,  
hoped the mass resignations would force owners to negotiate an 
agreement to replace the one that expires Dec. 31. The move 
backfired when 13 umpires didn't quit and another 14 withdrew their 
resignations. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball then hired 25 new umps from the minors, effective Sept.  
1, and accepted the resignations of the 22. 
</P>
<P>
	The umpires contend baseball induced many of their colleagues to  
withdraw their resignations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was unlawful for the leagues to convert these into  
discharges,'' said Susan Davis, the umpires' new lawyer. ``It's 
illegal to punish people who stood up for their union and in a 
retaliatory manner pick and choose who you chip. They went one by 
one and picked them off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The umpires contend Selig made ``unilateral changes in  
significant terms and conditions of their employment'' late last 
year, shifting authority over the umpires from the league 
presidents to the commissioner's office. The union also says it was 
illegal for owners to change the strike zone without their 
participation and say they feared owners would get rid of 20 umps. 
</P>
<P>
	In a sign of the split between AL and NL umps, six NL umps  
attended the news conference but just one from the AL. Of the 27 
umps who broke with the union by not quitting or withdrawing their 
resignations before July 25, 23 were from the AL. 
</P>
<P>
	Anger toward the AL umps and toward the replacements filled the  
room. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel totally betrayed by the umpires who left the union,  
quit my family, put us in this position,'' Hohn said. ``They just 
turned their backs on us. You want to go through the next century 
with these kinds of people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montague's wife, Marcia, wrote an angry letter last week to  
Denise Hirschbeck, the wife of AL ump John Hirschbeck, who has been 
organizing umpires opposed to union head Richie Phillips.	   ``My wife felt and wrote this from her heart,'' Montague said. 
``She did not write this with hatred toward Denise Hirschbeck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Drew Coble, the only AL umpire at the news conference, says he  
never resigned. The AL says he did. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was at home caring for my wife, who was undergoing  
chemotherapy,'' he said. ``Because of this family crisis, I didn't 
attend the union meeting and didn't know that any resignations had 
been submitted until several days later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On another front, the president of the minor league umpires said  
they fired Phillips as their negotiator Monday before he quit, a 
charge Phillips denies. The minor leaguers were upset Phillips 
failed to ask the NLRB to hold an election to certify their union, 
and during a telephone poll Friday and Saturday they decided to 
seek another lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told Richie Phillips that,'' International League ump Mike  
Billing said. ``He told me that was fine with him because he was 
resigning anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Umpires supporting Phillips and those opposed are vying for the  
support of the 25 minor leaguers who become permanent major league 
umpires on Sept. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want a head count in our league of the new guys they  
hired to see if they could count on knocking Richie out or not,'' 
Angel Hernandez said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 20:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Police Brace for Neo-Nazi Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Police in the nation's capital said Tuesday  
they are braced for a neo-Nazi rally and counterdemonstrations 
scheduled Saturday in front of the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Park Police said Tuesday they expect about 300 people to  
participate in the American Nationalist Party-sponsored four-block 
march along Pennsylvania Avenue to Lafayette Park and about 500 
counterdemonstrators. 
</P>
<P>
	Commander Michael Radzilowski of the Special Operations Division  
of the Metropolitan Police Department, said his entire unit will be 
working Saturday. Overall, Assistant Police Chief Terrence Gainer 
estimated 80 percent of the capitol city's force would be on the 
job. 
</P>
<P>
	Park Police expect to have 500 to 600 officers on duty.  
</P>
<P>
	The South Carolina-based white supremacist group received police  
permits for the march, followed by a rally in the park and 
demonstration afterwards in front of the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Police also have issued permits for a counterdemonstration  
billed as a ``vigil against hate'' planned by the American Jewish 
Congress, the NAACP and other civil rights and community groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're preparing for trouble,'' said Commander Radzilowski.  
</P>
<P>
	Similar confrontations in the past have ended in violence and  
arrests. In 1990, a Ku Klux Klan march to the U.S. Capitol ended 
with more than 30 arrests. Eight years earlier, a Klan rally ended 
with rioting and looting by some of those who were 
counterdemonstrating against it. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said they had no choice but to issue the permits. ``They  
can't deny permits, because they don't like what they're saying. 
They'd just sue us,'' said Quintin Peterson, a D.C. police 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	On its Internet site, the ANP said the aim of the march is ``to  
take back our nation from the criminals who have cheated their way 
into Washington.'' It also said it welcomed participation from any 
``white person who would like to build a better world for our 
youth'' but warned marchers to expect counterdemonstrators 
``shouting jeers and hurling objects.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Mayor Anthony Williams said plans are afoot for what  
he called ``a peaceful rally'' Saturday at the Lincoln Memorial 
several blocks from the White House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 16:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians DL Gooden, Activate Wright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Cleveland Indians placed Dwight Gooden on the  
15-day disabled list on Tuesday, a day after he pulled himself from 
a start with shoulder stiffness after just 2 2-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Gooden, 3-3 with a 5.81 ERA in 21 appearances, went on the  
disabled list to make room for Jaret Wright, who was activated from 
the DL in time to start Tuesday night's game against Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never really recovered from my last start,'' Gooden said.  
``I probably shouldn't have taken the mound.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians now have five players on the disabled list,  
including regulars Travis Fryman, Sandy Alomar and Wilfredo 
Cordero. 
</P>
<P>
	Gooden, who had pitched seven strong innings in his previous  
start, is eligible to come off the disabled list on Aug. 18. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Mike Hargrove said Gooden was going to miss at least one  
start and perhaps two. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
