<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs More Snow Goose Hunting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House approved legislation Monday to allow  
24 states to expand hunting of snow geese as they migrate north. If 
the bill becomes law, it would restore hunting rules that the 
government withdrew in response to a lawsuit by animal advocates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Interior Department said last February it would allow eased  
state hunting restrictions because the snow geese's soaring 
population growth threatened the Arctic tundra where they feed 
during the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Humane Society of the United States sued, and the  
regulation by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service was withdrawn. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation, passed by voice vote and now awaiting Senate  
action, essentially codifies the regulations announced in February. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, officials said an estimated 1.2 million birds were  
expected to be shot. Over the past three decades, the population of 
snow geese has exploded from 800,000 birds to an estimated 5 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Many conservation and hunting groups endorsed the plan on the  
grounds that dramatic action was needed to reduce the snow geese 
population. The birds annually migrate from the U.S. Gulf Coast 
area across the Great Plains to Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	So many birds make the migration now, however, that they've  
destroyed thousands of acres of tundra and salt marsh in Canada's 
Hudson Bay area, biologists said. 
</P>
<P>
	The geese are protected under the 1918 Migratory Bird Treaty  
Act, but the Fish and Wildlife Service has authority to allow 
limited hunting as well as ban certain hunting techniques or types 
of guns that can be used. As part of its February regulation, the 
agency sought to ease some of the restrictions so more birds would 
be killed. 
</P>
<P>
	While it refused to block the regulation, the U.S. District  
Court ordered the Fish and Wildlife Service to conduct a detailed 
environmental impact statement that could take several years. 
</P>
<P>
	``During that time the tundra will continue to be systematically  
destroyed, an acre at a time,'' Rep. Jim Saxon, R-N.J., said during 
debate on the bill when it was in committee. Saxon is a sponsor of 
the legislation and chairs the House Resources fisheries 
subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24 states where increased hunting would be allowed are  
Alabama, Arkansas, Colorado, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kansas, 
Kentucky, Louisiana, Michigan, Minnesota, Mississippi, Missouri, 
Montana, Nebraska, New Mexico, North Dakota, Ohio, Oklahoma, South 
Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Wisconsin and Wyoming. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
