<DOCNO> APW19990803.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 03:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EPA To Review Pesticides for Dangers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Environmental Protection Agency is taking  
a fresh look at more than 40 risky pesticides to determine whether 
to restrict their use because they may be a threat to children. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Administrator Carol Browner announced Monday that the  
agency has reached agreements with manufacturers to stop the sale 
for most uses of one of the high-risk pesticides, methyl parathion, 
and to sharply curtail the use of another. 
</P>
<P>
	The dozens of pesticides under review, including a class of  
organophosphates used for decades on most fruits and vegetables, 
have been controversial because of concern that the residue levels 
the government deems acceptable pose risks to infants and children. 
</P>
<P>
	Allowable residue levels for many pesticides were set decades  
ago when the potential health impacts on infants and children were 
not taken into account. 
</P>
<P>
	Browner said at a news conference that fruits and vegetables are  
safe and that children and adults alike should not stop eating 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``The benefits of a diet that includes fruits and vegetables far  
outweigh the risks of pesticides,'' said Browner. However, she 
said, ``It is becoming increasingly clear that foods can be made 
even safer, especially for children,'' adding that ``today's 
technologies allow our farmers to use safer alternatives and safer 
approaches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA's intention to end the use of methyl parathion on fruits  
and vegetables and curtail the use of azinphos methyl was reported 
last week. The pesticides are widely used nationwide on such crops 
as apples, peaches, pears, grapes, carrots and certain beans. 
</P>
<P>
	Browner dismissed criticism that her agency is not going for  
enough even as she acknowledged that the EPA had not met its own 
deadlines in completing the pesticide reviews demanded by Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealing with these pesticides ``has proven to be more difficult  
than we thought,'' Browner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics contend the EPA delayed taking action because of  
pressure from agriculture interests. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
