<DOCNO> APW19990803.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 22:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ralphs Inks Internet Promotion Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Ralphs food stores signed a cross-promotional  
deal with Checkout.com, the Internet entertainment site backed by 
former Hollywood agent Michael Ovitz and former grocery magnate 
Ronald Burkle. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, scheduled to be formally announced today,  
Ralphs shoppers can get a discount on their next grocery bill if 
they buy music CDs or other merchandise from Checkout. 
</P>
<P>
	``The general approach to getting customers on the Web has been  
to try and get them from Internet portals,'' said Richard Wolpert, 
the former Disney Online president who heads Internet ventures for 
Yucaipa Cos., the site's other major backer. ``We think there's 
going to be a much closer relationship between physical retailers 
and online retailers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Checkout.com will debut today in limited form. Visitors will be  
able to buy games, CDs and videotapes and read reviews or news 
about celebrities, but will see only a portion of the news archives 
merchandise catalogues that will be available when the site 
formally opens later this summer, said Wolpert. 
</P>
<P>
	``The majority of functionality is going to be there,'' Wolpert  
said in an interview. ``We wanted to give people a sneak preview.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Ralphs deal also renews a link between the chain and  
Yucaipa, which owned Ralphs parent Fred Meyer Inc. until selling 
the business to Kroger for $8 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of the sale, Yucaipa became Kroger's largest single  
shareholder and Yucaipa founder Ron Burkle got a seat on Kroger's 
board. 
</P>
<P>
	``We look at this as a part of a very long relationship. This is  
probably the first of many things we are going to do with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Ralphs promotion will include flyers that encourage  
customers to visit the chain's Web site at www.ralphs.com. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 20:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen Wednesday morning  
as fear of joint Japan-U.S. intervention appeared to recede. Tokyo 
share prices dropped mainly on selling of export-oriented blue 
chips. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 115.04 yen at late morning, down 0.36 yen from  
late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 
115.28 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 225.91 points,  
or 1.26 percent, to finish the morning session at 17,744.02. On 
Tuesday, the average closed up 144.23 points, or 0.81 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar's decline came despite strong  
words hinting at dollar-buying intervention from Zembei Mizoguchi, 
director-general of the international bureau at Japan's Ministry of 
Finance. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will think of appropriate measures at every turn of  
events,'' Mizoguchi told reporters at the ministry Wednesday 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Fear of intervention emerged after Finance Minister Kiichi  
Miyazawa and U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers agreed in 
phone talks Tuesday that they will maintain close ties on foreign 
exchange policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said, however, that there has been no indication of any  
joint intervention since the two officials spoke the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent months, the Bank of Japan has bought dollars to stop  
the yen's rise against the greenback, an action meant to help the 
country's nascent economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.02 yen, down  
from 123.08 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices fell as investors remained worried  
about the negative impact of the yen's strength on Japan's blue 
chip exporters, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The recent appreciation of the yen against the dollar has  
weakened momentum in Japan's stock market,'' said Yoshihiko 
Kuroichi, an analyst at Kankaku Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	A higher yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad and  
thus less competitive and reduces the dollar-denominated earnings 
of Japanese exporters when translated into yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Other morning losers were telecommunication issues, including  
the nation's giant Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of NTT lost ground amid concerns about a glut in supply  
after the Finance Ministry announced Tuesday it will sell 952,000 
shares it holds in the telecommunications giant between 
mid-November and December, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The move lower in Tokyo came despite a rise in the Dow Jones  
industrial average. On Wall Street, the Dow rose 31.35 points to 
close Tuesday at 10,677.31. But, the technology heavy Nasdaq Index 
fell 35.64 points to close at 2,587.99. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 15.05 points, or 1.02 percent, to 1,466.94. 
The TOPIX closed up 13.37 points, or 0.91 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.8900 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.8800 percent, driving 
its price down to 99.23 yen from 99.32 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
