<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Racing for Golden League Jackpot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTE CARLO, Monaco (AP) -- Four track stars will be trying to  
stay in the race for the $1 million Golden League jackpot at 
Wednesday's Herculis meet. 
</P>
<P>
	And with the world championships in Seville less than three  
weeks away, there will be more attention than ever on events at the 
Stade Louis II stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Amateur Athletic Federation offers the  
million-dollar purse for those who win at all seven Golden League 
meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson Kipketer, Bernard Barmasai, Marion Jones and Gabriela  
Szabo won at the three previous meet in Oslo, Rome and Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, one of three who shared last year's jackpot, and Kipketer  
seem to be at their best. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is difficult to be in top form every race in the 200  
meters, to get sub 22 seconds each time, but I am not far away from 
my very best form,'' Jones told a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	At the last Golden League meet in Paris, the 23-year-old Jones  
extended her unbeaten streak to 18 races over three seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 800 meters, Kipketer, the world record-holder battling  
back after a bout of malaria, was the class of the field despite 
losing a shoe with more than a quarter of the race remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Szabo again looks to be the best in the 3,000 meters.  
</P>
<P>
	In Paris, the Romanian held off a strong challenge from Zahra  
Ouaziz -- who set an African record of eight minutes, 26.64 seconds 
-- to win in the fastest time of the year, 8:25.59. 
</P>
<P>
	World record-holder Barmasai continues to dominate the  
3,000-meter steeplechase, and is favored to win again in Monaco. 
</P>
<P>
	Three others their hopes of a share in the jackpot disappear in  
Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's Svetlana Masterkova lost to her 800-meter rival Maria  
Mutola, hurdler Allen Johnson couldn't compete because of a 
strained right calf and Eric Walder was beaten in the long jump. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
