<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 20:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Agree on $792B Tax Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans reached agreement Tuesday night on  
a plan to cut personal income tax rates and provide relief from the 
marriage penalty as they sculpted a $792 billion measure President 
Clinton has vowed to veto. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every income taxpayer in America will get relief in this  
bill,'' Rep. Bill Archer, the chief House tax-writer, said as GOP 
negotiators wrapped up two intense days of negotiations on the item 
that sits atop their legislative agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	The House-Senate compromise measure, salted with breaks for  
education, health care, corporations and other interests, ``is the 
biggest tax relief bill for the American people since 1981,'' added 
the Texas Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the  
proposal calls for a gradual cut of 1 percentage point in each 
personal income tax rate. The 15 percent tax bracket would go to 14 
percent, for example, and the 39.6 percent bracket would become 
38.6 percent. That means the percentage reduction would be greater 
at lower incomes. 
</P>
<P>
	To alleviate the marriage penalty, the Republican bill would  
gradually raise the standard deduction for couples until it is 
double the deduction for individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, lawmakers decided to widen the current 15 percent  
bracket for couples so it would apply to some income that currently 
is taxed at 28 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders hope to push the measure to final passage by week's  
end, the next step in a veto clash that both the majority party and 
Clinton seem eager to have. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic critics contend the bill would shortchange Social  
Security, Medicare and other vital domestic programs, and could 
threaten a return of soaring budget deficits. Clinton has 
threatened a veto numerous times in recent weeks, and there is no 
doubt that Democrats in Congress would supply the votes to sustain 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican officials said the final measure would cut the  
personal capital gains tax rate from 20 percent to 18 percent and 
from 10 percent to 8 percent, and then adjust the rates annually to 
discount the effects of inflation. There would be no cut in the 
corporate capital gains tax. The estate tax would be eliminated 
gradually. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance  
Committee, said contribution limits to individual retirement 
accounts would rise gradually from $2,000 to $5,000 annually. He 
added that the self-employed would be permitted to deduct the 
entire cost of their health insurance premiums, as would employees 
who work for firms that don't offer health insurance. Other 
officials said medical savings accounts, tax-deductible accounts 
set aside for health-related costs, would be more readily 
available. 
</P>
<P>
	Roth also said the bill contains a provision mandating that  
money from pre-paid state tuition plans be paid out to students 
tax-free. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, taxpayers who care for elderly relatives in their  
homes would be eligible for tax breaks, and insurance premiums for 
long-term care would be partially tax-deductible for the first 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the broad-based relief would total roughly $400  
billion over the next decade. The provisions designed to offset the 
marriage penalty would save taxpayers another $100 billion, they 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	In a bow to GOP moderates in the House, the final compromise  
will include a provision making each annual installment of the tax 
rate reductions dependent on a decline in the government's cost of 
borrowing. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials cautioned that some minor adjustments were likely in  
the bill, as aides draft precise language that can fit without 
exceeding the $792 billion price tag. 
</P>
<P>
	Precise details were unlikely to be available until Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	For two days, senior Republicans and aides shuttled in and out  
of these bargaining sessions, and others were consulted by phone. 
But there was no place for Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, the senior Democrat on the  
tax-writing House Ways and Means Committee, invited himself briefly 
into the closed-door GOP deliberations in a bit of political 
theater. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like having two Christmas lists, and you select the best  
from each list knowing that Santa is not coming,'' he said in a 
reference to Clinton's promised veto. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott, R-Miss., and House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., were  
pressing to have the compromise passed through the House and Senate 
by week's end, to permit rank-and-file lawmakers to trumpet the 
advantages of tax cuts during Congress' long August break. 
</P>
<P>
	Only when lawmakers return to Washington after Labor Day would  
the bill be sent to the White House for Clinton's expected veto, 
although some Republicans practically taunted Clinton to sign it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not give up on the possibility that he will sign (tax  
cuts). But if he vetoes them, we think he'll find he's disappointed 
the American people,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey of 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that Clinton ``is a man who will disappoint everyone in  
his life except his pollster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott told reporters that ``maybe the president will conclude at  
some point that he needs to work with us.'' For now, he added, ``I 
just don't see it happening, so we have to go forward with doing 
what we think is right for the American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House and most Democrats oppose a bill of the  
magnitude favored by Republicans, saying it would shortchange 
Social Security and Medicare and lead to deep spending cuts in 
other domestic programs including education and health care. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has repeatedly termed the GOP proposals risky and said  
that because they rely on anticipated surpluses, the tax cuts could 
return the nation to a new era of deficits. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Republicans, there remained scattered signs of a desire to  
compromise before the bill goes to the White House. Sen. Olympia 
Snowe, R-Maine, released a letter to Lott urging that a final 
House-Senate deal be held up in hopes there could be a 
``negotiated, bipartisan agreement ... achieved in September that 
ultimately addresses a variety of needs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Privately, other Republicans expressed similar sentiments, but  
there was no immediate indication they were having an impact on the 
leaders' strategy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
