<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Regulators To OK Global One Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Union antitrust regulators  
said Tuesday they intend to clear Global One -- a joint venture 
created by Deutsche Telekom, France Telecom and Sprint -- to provide 
full telecommunications services within the 15-nation EU. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Commission approved the joint venture after its was  
created in 1996, but imposed a number of conditions reflecting the 
lack of competition in a sector then dominated by national 
monopolies. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, the EU executive said the liberalization of the  
market since then prompted it to lift the restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commission said it was waiting to hear comment from  
``interested parties'' before taking a formal decision, but added 
it intended to allow the venture ``to provide all 
telecommunications services, including voice telephony, in all the 
EU member states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Global One's president and chief executive officer, Gary Forsee,  
resigned last month following published reports that the venture 
was failing and could be dissolved. Company officials denied the 
reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Global One was formed in 1996 to offer large multinational  
corporations complete, integrated telecommunications services 
worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Relations within the venture have been strained by Deutsche  
Telekom's ill-fated attempt to take over Telecom Italia. Since that 
bid failed in May, there has been intense speculation that the 
German company is seeking new international partners. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
