<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DuBose Family Wants Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- The family of a former Tampa Bay Buccaneers  
linebacker who was killed by police officers has initiated an 
independent autopsy and investigation into the shooting after 
witnesses indicated the athlete may have been shot in the back. 
</P>
<P>
	Demetrius DuBose, 28, was shot several times by police officers  
July 24 after he allegedly charged at officers with nunchakus, a 
martial arts weapon that he took away from an officer, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	But preliminary findings of the family's investigation show  
DuBose was initially calm and cooperated with officers' 
investigation of a burglary call until they began to ``intimidate 
and harass'' him, likely because he was black, said H.J. Sims of 
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People in 
San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the police first arrived the gentleman was patient for  
about five to 10 minutes,'' Sims said Monday. ``It was only after 
they tried to place him in handcuffs that the unprofessionalism of 
police allowed the situation to escalate and prompted the gentleman 
to run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego City Councilmen George Stevens and Byron Wear are  
calling for a thorough investigation into the shooting to allay any 
concerns that it was unjustified. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose had been arrested three times in the past year.  
</P>
<P>
	The latest was June 14, when California Highway Patrol officers  
found DuBose ``very dazed, very confused'' in his car parked on the 
side of a highway near Mammoth Lakes, said Mono County prosecutor 
Tim Kendall. 
</P>
<P>
	After conducting field sobriety tests and observing ``white  
powdery substance dripping from his nose,'' officers determined he 
was under the influence of PCP, Kendall said. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose became increasingly agitated as the investigation went  
on, but officers were able to get him handcuffed, Kendall said. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose also was reportedly under the influence of an unknown  
drug Feb. 3, when he allegedly forced his way into a Mammoth Lakes 
restaurant after being denied entrance several times, Kendall said. 
</P>
<P>
	In August 1998, DuBose was arrested in South Bend, Ind., after  
he became belligerent at a nightclub. When an off-duty police 
officer ordered him to leave, DuBose allegedly grabbed a pipe from 
an overhead sprinkler system -- flooding the club with some 1,600 
gallons of water. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens noted some people have said 6-foot-2-DuBose was bending  
over when the accident happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``Others have said he was turning away. I would hope the autopsy  
would show where the first shot entered,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego police Chief David Bejarano said he welcomes outside  
input and expects an internal investigation to be completed within 
two weeks. Results, which will include toxicology results, will be 
turned over to the district attorney's office, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers claim DuBose resisted officers' attempts to question  
him and appeared to be under the influence of alcohol or other 
drugs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
