<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Government Pays Off $113.8B of Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government paid off a record $113.8  
billion of the national debt in the April-June quarter and expects 
to pay another $11 billion in debt this quarter, the Treasury 
Department said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Retirement of a portion of the $5.5 trillion in national debt is  
occurring because of record budget surpluses, now estimated by the 
Clinton administration to total $5.9 trillion over the next 15 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Both President Clinton and congressional Republicans have  
pledged to use two-thirds of those surpluses to shore up the Social 
Security trust fund by paying down the national debt. But they are 
fighting over use of the remainder: Republicans want large tax 
cuts, which Clinton considers fiscally irresponsible. 
</P>
<P>
	The net debt reduction this fiscal year will amount to more than  
$87 billion, Clinton said in a statement issued by the White House. 
He called it the ``largest deficit reduction in America's 
history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The debt reduction for this year and last year, the first with a  
budget surplus in 29 years, will total $142 billion, Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Debt reduction brings tangible benefits to American's working  
families through lower interest rates,'' Clinton said. He estimated 
an American family with a $100,000 mortgage would save more than 
$2,000 annually in lower interest payments because of the lower 
mortgage rates resulting from lower government borrowing demands. 
</P>
<P>
	In announcing its borrowing needs for the current quarter, the  
Treasury Department said Monday it expects to pay off $11 billion 
in debt coming due. That figure was in line with an earlier 
projection of a debt reduction of $10 billion for the 
July-September quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	During the April-June quarter, the $113.8 billion of national  
debt that Treasury said the government paid off was a slightly 
smaller amount than an earlier estimate of $116 billion. The 
revision was attributed to lower-than-expected tax receipts. 
</P>
<P>
	From October to December, the first quarter of the government's  
fiscal year 1999, net government borrowing was $24 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Once rare, reductions in federal debt are becoming increasingly  
commonplace as a result of the return of annual federal budget 
surpluses after 28 consecutive years of deficit, 1969 through 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration, in its midyear economic forecast,  
projected that the surplus, which totaled $69.2 billion in 1998, 
will climb to $98.8 billion in the current fiscal year, which ends 
Sept. 30, and will total $142.5 billion in 2000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
