<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 02:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colo. Begins Gun Background Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Colorado has again begun checking the backgrounds  
of gun buyers, taking over the task from the federal government 
following the shooting deaths of three young girls by their father. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Bill Owens signed an executive order mandating the change  
Sunday. The instant background checks had been performed by the FBI 
since April. 
</P>
<P>
	``The state has more complete and detailed information on  
restrictions, including restraining orders, which will help prevent 
those people who have criminal histories from legally purchasing 
firearms,'' said Inspector Pete Mang of the Colorado Bureau of 
Investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	By 5 p.m. Sunday, the CBI had reviewed 68 requests and rejected  
eight bids to buy guns, two of which it said would not have been 
denied by the FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	One request was denied because of a restraining order, the other  
because of a felony charge which the FBI check would not have 
caught because the potential buyer was not fingerprinted at the 
time of arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	The switch is the result of the June 22 slayings by Simon  
Gonzales, who purchased a handgun from a federally-licensed dealer 
only hours before he killed his three daughters as they slept. He 
died in a shootout with Castle Rock police. 
</P>
<P>
	It was later discovered that his estranged wife had filed a  
restraining order against him, something the federal checks did not 
uncover and that could have prevented the gun purchase. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colorado system still has loopholes, Mang said.  
</P>
<P>
	Gun sellers who are not federally licensed, including private  
sellers who frequent gun shows, are not required to do background 
checks. Neither are individuals who sell guns privately. 
</P>
<P>
	``If someone wants to buy a gun illegally, it is easy to do  
so,'' Mang said. ``But this provides another level of protection, 
and that might prevent someone else from slipping through the 
cracks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado began handgun-buyer background checks in 1995,  
expanding it to rifles and shotguns in November. State lawmakers 
killed the program, saying it duplicated FBI efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	The next logical step, according to David Winkler, would be to  
extend the regulation to gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17-year-old said he and a friend walked into a recent gun  
show and purchased a TEC-DC9, the same weapon used by the teen-age 
gunmen in the April 20 massacre at Littleton's Columbine High 
School. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just proves how important it is to end unrestricted  
anonymous purchases, to have any gun purchase cleared with law 
enforcement,'' said Winkler, who is a member of Safe Alternatives 
to the Firearms Epidemic. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 23:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mercedes-Benz Recalls Child Seats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Mercedes-Benz has recalled 6,000 child seats that  
automatically turn off passenger-side air bags when installed, 
saying a flaw might keep the bags turned on -- a potential danger to 
small children. 
</P>
<P>
	The BabySmart seats send and receive signals from two antennas  
in the seat cushion. Air bags in some Mercedes-Benz models are 
supposed to recognize that a BabySmart seat has been installed and 
turn off the passenger air bag. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mercedes-Benz said Tuesday that if the child seat is pushed  
forward when the seat back is leaning toward the dashboard, the 
passenger air bag might not turn off as designed. 
</P>
<P>
	Drivers would know the system was not working only because an  
``air bag off'' light would stay dark. Mercedes-Benz said there 
have been four reports that the indicator light was off, but no 
reports of accidents or injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The company recommended the seats not be used and that children  
sit in the back seat until the problem is fixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercedes dealers will exchange the seats for free. The recall  
does not affect Toddler seats. 
</P>
<P>
	Safety experts say that small infants ride in rear-facing child  
seats, but also strongly recommend that rear-facing infant seats 
never be placed in front of an air bag. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 15 infants have been killed this way by air bags since  
1994, according to the U.S. Department of Transportation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
