<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Watts Threatened To Resign As Chair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republican Conference Chairman J.C.  
Watts of Oklahoma threatened to resign his leadership post last 
week, complaining that GOP Whip Tom DeLay was usurping his job 
crafting communications strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Watts') view was that if J.C. Watts and Tom DeLay are not  
working together, neither of them will be successful at their 
leadership jobs,'' Rep. Pete Hoekstra, R-Mich., one of Watts' 
allies, said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Numerous officials close to both men said Watts, the first black  
member of the GOP leadership since Republicans took control of 
Congress in 1995, became furious last Thursday when DeLay handed 
out a packet on communications strategy during a meeting of House 
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Communications strategy traditionally has fallen within the  
purview of those holding Watt's title, the No. 4 position in the 
House GOP leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	Moments later, Watts confronted House Speaker Dennis Hastert and  
threatened to resign as conference chairman, according to GOP 
leadership officials familiar with the events. Hastert, R-Ill., 
stepped in to stop the squabble, these officials said, speaking on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	DeLay, whose job as the No. 2 official in the GOP leadership is  
to marshal votes for Republican legislation, insists he was only 
trying to help, according to his aides. 
</P>
<P>
	``Had we foreseen this (action) would have caused this much  
tension, we would have never done it in the first place,'' said 
DeLay spokesman Mike Scanlon. 
</P>
<P>
	DeLay, through his spokesman, declined to comment directly on  
the dispute. Watts issued a statement calling the brouhaha a 
``family'' matter and Hoekstra said that Watts was ``disappointed'' 
that it had become public. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials close to DeLay said he was only responding to Watts'  
call for more coordination during a meeting between the men two 
days earlier that had been requested by Watts. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after the Watts-DeLay meeting, a group of conservative  
lawmakers told DeLay that they had not been working with Watts on 
communications, according to these officials, who demanded 
anonymity. DeLay then drew up a strategy to present to the 
conference meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	An aide to DeLay called Watts' office the night before the  
conference meeting and left a message saying that Watts' office 
should call back if ``there's a problem,'' DeLay's allies say. They 
said no one from Watts' office called back. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials close to Watts said his office did respond to the call  
from DeLay's office, and requested a copy of DeLay's packet but it 
never arrived. DeLay's office said it never received such a 
request. 
</P>
<P>
	Watts has expressed frustration before about being usurped by  
other GOP leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has, there has been some of that,'' Watts told The Hill,  
a Capitol Hill newspaper, in an interview several weeks ago when 
asked if his communications strategy effort was being undermined by 
another leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't tell you where it comes from,'' Watts told The Hill.  
``I have my thoughts. But I'm bigger than that. I'll let those 
people play those games and empire-building.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
