<HEADLINE> Russia Lowers Grain Import Estimate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia expects to import 8.6 million tons of grain  
in 1999, about half as much as previously estimated, a top 
agriculture official said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Agriculture officials had said Russia would need to import at  
least 15 million tons of grain this year. But that was before grain 
harvest forecasts were increased t0 60 tons from about 50 tons. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the imported grain will be fodder for livestock, First  
Deputy Agriculture and Food Minister Anatoly Mikhalev said, 
according to the Interfax news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasts for this year's crop harvest have fluctuated  
substantially, but officials say their current estimates are more 
accurate now that the harvest is under way. About 20 percent of the 
crop has been brought in so far. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Mikhalev said that forecasts for other crops were not  
promising. Without providing figures, he predicted that harvests of 
corn, potatoes and cotton would be low. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
