<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Sign Slegr to 2-Year Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Defenseman Jiri Slegr agreed to a $2.3  
million, two-year contract Tuesday, becoming the first player to 
sign with the Pittsburgh Penguins since Mario Lemieux was approved 
as owner. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux was awarded the team in federal bankruptcy court June  
24, but may not close on the deal until next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Slegr had eight goals and 32 assists the last two seasons, with  
a plus-24 rating that ranked third on the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been very good for us, very dependable,'' general manager  
Craig Patrick said. ``We're very happy to have him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins still have five players eligible for salary  
arbitration, and must sign them within two weeks to avoid 
arbitration hearings. Also unsigned are Martin Straka, Alexei 
Kovalev, Matthew Barnaby, Ian Moran and Robert Lang. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to get these guys signed,'' said Patrick, who is  
working with a $30 million budget prepared by Lemieux's staff -- a 
$6 million increase from last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of that boost will be wiped out by Jaromir Jagr's salary,  
which jumps from $4.9 million to $10.4 million, or more than 
one-third of the Penguins' payroll. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
