<DOCNO> APW19990803.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 01:40:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Officials Declare Drought Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLES TOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- Terry Dunn's sweet corn crop is a  
total loss, his hay crop half its usual yield. His field corn is 
not worth harvesting. The chickens' eggs are smaller than usual. 
</P>
<P>
	It was on Dunn's 122-acre farm that federal officials chose to  
declare West Virginia and parts of five neighboring states 
agricultural disaster areas Monday -- the latest step as the 
region's terrible drought grows more severe each day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess I had the worst-looking crops,'' Dunn said of his  
chance to host a tour by U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman. 
``It's a dubious honor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After picking a few sickly, 3- to 4-inch ears of corn from a  
field of dry, knee-high stalks, Glickman issued the declaration for 
89 counties in Kentucky, Maryland, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Virginia and 
West Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	The order, which likely will be expanded in the coming days,  
makes farmers who have lost at least 30 percent of a crop eligible 
for low-interest federal loans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Drought is like an insidious cancer. It's slow, it infects and  
it's harder to deal with as a disaster,'' Glickman said. ``Farm 
prices are the lowest in a decade, and this drought couldn't have 
come at a worse time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the hottest Julys on record has also had a horrendous  
human cost: more than 200 heat-related deaths in 20 states since 
July 19. 
</P>
<P>
	The drought gripping the mid-Atlantic area is already the  
third-worst this century and could surpass the droughts of 1929 and 
1966 to become the most devastating, scientists with the U.S. 
Geological Survey said Monday. Some of the region's soil hasn't 
been this dry since the Depression. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a crisis here. Together we're going to try to do  
emergency assistance for the farmers and long-term policy that will 
help reverse this trend,'' Maryland Gov. Parris Glendening said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rural wells and underground aquifers, already low from a winter  
with little snow or rain, are continuing to run dry. That will hurt 
farmers again next year. 
</P>
<P>
	From Boston to Miami, rainfall in some areas is 50 percent to 80  
percent below normal. The dry weather has been felt from tree 
nurseries in the Northeast to fruit orchards in Florida. The arid 
weather has sucked the life out of crops, wilting limbs and 
dropping fruit to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	In Galway, N.Y., Christmas tree farmer Dave Eaton has lost about  
70 percent of this season's plantings, some 15,000 trees at a cost 
of $1 apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman issued a drought warning  
Monday, clearing the way for state officials to assert control over 
the state's water supply. People should conserve now or face 
possible mandatory restrictions later, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	To preserve hay for the winter, many West Virginia livestock  
growers are selling cattle early at prices their fathers and 
grandfathers got 30 to 40 years ago, Sen. Robert C. Byrd said. 
</P>
<P>
	The West Virginia Democrat is sponsoring an amendment to a $9.9  
billion farm-spending bill that would give livestock farmers $150 
million in grants to help cover the mounting losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Glickman said he would lobby for Byrd's measure. And in  
Washington, President Clinton said he would work with Congress to 
provide $10 billion in drought relief. 
</P>
<P>
	``We provide emergency assistance for disasters around the  
world, and there's no reason we shouldn't provide comparable 
assistance for people here at home,'' he said. ``And we will do 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The aid may come too late for some.  
</P>
<P>
	This year may be the last for up to 10 percent of West  
Virginia's 21,000 farmers, state Agriculture Secretary Gus Douglass 
said. Statewide, farm losses so far have surpassed $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would need about 15 inches of rain to make up for the loss,  
but the damage is already done,'' Douglass said. He said one farmer 
he saw wept as he was forced to sell his cows. 
</P>
<P>
	``Folks, it just comes down to one single word, and that is  
survival. One of the best examples of American rural culture is 
being destroyed,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughn Harshman knows that all too well.  
</P>
<P>
	After examining shin-high soybeans -- they should be more than 3  
feet tall by now -- the third-generation farmer said he wasn't sure 
his 800-acre grain and cattle business would survive. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm at the point where if they want to know what I'm going to  
do next year, I honestly don't know,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
