<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hawks Introduce Jim Jackson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Jim Jackson is expected to be with Atlanta this  
fall despite rumors that his stay could be only a temporary one 
with the Hawks, who are looking to upgrade their front court. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, a 6-foot-6 guard who backed up Isaiah Rider last season  
with the Portland Trail Blazers, was dealt to the Hawks on Monday 
along with Rider in exchange for guard Steve Smith, who led Atlanta 
in scoring, and little-used guard Ed Gray. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did not make this trade with Portland to move either  
player,'' Atlanta general manager Pete Babcock said during a news 
conference Tuesday at the Hawks' offices introducing Jackson to the 
media. 
</P>
<P>
	Babcock made the statement despite their interest in free agent  
center-forward Lorenzen Wright, who played with the Los Angeles 
Clippers last season but has said he will not return there. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's no secret Lorenzen Wright was in town today. We met with  
him and he's a very attractive free agent,'' Babcock said. ``The 
Clippers are very interested in Jim Jackson, but we told them no. 
It's too high a price. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still maintaining an interest in Lorenzen Wright, but  
not at the price of giving up Jim Jackson,'' Babcock said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson believes he'll be a Hawk when the season opens and,  
despite playing behind Ryder last season at Portland, will get more 
playing time with Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd love it. It doesn't matter to me. I pride myself on being  
a basketball player,'' said Jackson, who is expected to also play 
some small forward. ``I don't care where I play as long as I'm on 
the court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Babcock said starting positions will be won or lost in training  
camp, with the decisions being made by coach Lenny Wilkens. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very confident that Jim Jackson is a bona fide starter  
in the NBA. He's proved that in his career,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's also proved he's willing to sacrifice for the good of the  
team and that's what we're looking for,'' Babcock said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, 29, who averaged a career-low 8.4 points last season,  
signed a three-year, $6 million free agent contract with Portland 
prior to last season. He has averaged 17.9 points, 4.9 rebounds and 
4 assists during his seven years in the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	Babcock said the Hawks were looking for more scoring and to run  
more, which will be possible with Jackson and Ryder as well as the 
addition of their No. 1 draft pick, point guard Jason Terry. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're more athletic, got more scoring punch and will be able  
to run a more effective up tempo game now,'' Babcock said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was in a situation last year where I didn't start for the  
first time in my career,'' Jackson said. ``I had to make a 
sacrifice. I made that adjustment. It wasn't easy, but I adjusted 
and it paid off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers made it to the third round of the playoffs before  
being knocked out 4-0 by eventual NBA champion San Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawks, who finished second in the Central Division to  
Indiana, were swept by the New York Knicks in the second round of 
the playoffs. They have not made it beyond the second round since 
moving to Atlanta in 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson began his NBA career with the Dallas Mavericks, who  
selected him with the fourth overall pick in the 1992 draft after 
an outstanding career at Ohio State. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent 4 1/2 years in Dallas before being traded three times in  
1997-98 -- first to New Jersey in a nine-player trade, then to 
Philadelphia on draft day in the deal that sent Keith Van Horn to 
the Nets and finally to Golden State along with Clarence 
Weatherspoon for Joe Smith and Brian Shaw. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
