<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 10:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PBS List Exposes It to Bias Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- When conservative producer Lionel Chetwynd  
approached PBS with an idea for a public affairs series in the 
early '90s, he was wary of his reception. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came in with some trepidation and a chip on my shoulder,  
believing it was one big left-wing cabal. What we discovered is the 
system strives to be politically neutral,'' said Chetwynd, whose 
``National Desk'' series has become a PBS regular. 
</P>
<P>
	Chetwynd is the kind of friendly witness public broadcasting may  
need. Five years after PBS successfully battled the effort of a 
newly Republican-controlled Congress to cut or eliminate its 
funding, the service is in the soup again. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, some of its own offspring helped to put it there. At  
least two dozen of the 349 PBS stations nationwide, including many 
major outlets, have engaged in swapping lists of potential donors 
with political groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Granted, the groups were as diverse as the Democratic National  
Committee and Country Club Republicans. And PBS, which contends the 
exchanges were handled by outside list brokers, not station 
insiders, says the swaps were wrong and are being halted. 
</P>
<P>
	But the controversy represents, at the least, a careless move  
for a service that has long been the target of complaints of 
partisanship and has been forced to defend the very existence of 
public-supported TV in a free-market society. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., who had introduced a proposal to  
authorize increased funding for the Corporation for Public 
Broadcasting, withdrew it. He and Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., 
have asked for investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether perceptions of political bias are legitimate or not, PBS  
had an obligation to be sensitive to such concerns or ``suffer the 
consequences,'' Tauzin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Ervin S. Duggan, president and chief executive officer,  
PBS seemed to have become more politically inclusive, Tauzin said. 
But, he said, the list exchanges call into question its programming 
as well as its management. 
</P>
<P>
	``Were the changes they made only superficial, designed to  
overcome perception and not reality? That's a serious question. I 
suppose we're going to have to get into it,'' Tauzin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Duggan said he is prepared to respond to those seeking to  
connect PBS on-air efforts with its stations' fund-raising. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a non sequitur. Anyone who sees a connection between this  
and the editorial process simply doesn't understand how public 
television works,'' Duggan said. ``The burden of proof is on them 
to show that there's a bias. It does not exist. 
</P>
<P>
	``No organization like ours has any right to opinions of our  
own. We invite people onto our air who are of all opinions, and we 
have to be scrupulous that all opinions are heard and seen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	PBS cites polling data to bolster its claims of neutrality: In a  
1998-99 survey of leaders in government, business, medicine and 
other fields, three PBS programs were top-rated for credibility and 
objectivity, including ``The News Hour with Jim Lehrer,'' 
``Washington Week in Review'' and ``Wall Street Week with Louis 
Rukeyser.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a September 1998 phone poll of 1,000 households conducted for  
PBS, 38 percent said public television was ``mostly unbiased'' (25 
percent answered ``Don't know''). The survey found viewers who 
believed the service leans left or right were nearly evenly 
divided. No margin of error was given. 
</P>
<P>
	When it comes to critics, the picture is much the same, Duggan  
said: ``We get attacked from both sides.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In June, the liberal watchdog group Fairness and Accuracy in  
Media released a study that said PBS news and public affairs 
programming has a ``persistent elite bias'' and gives big business 
and government officials more air time than ``citizen activists'' 
or members of the general public. 
</P>
<P>
	(PBS pointed to its armful of journalism awards and called the  
survey's methodology flawed.) 
</P>
<P>
	Traditionally, conservatives have even fewer kind words for PBS.  
In 1995, Republican lawmakers cited PBS' alleged liberal bias in 
their anti-funding arguments. The picture has changed but not 
improved, say critics on the right. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our usual complaint with PBS and NPR (National Public Radio)  
was bias by commission. Now it's by omission,'' said Tim Graham, 
director of media analysis for the conservative Media Research 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Playing up sexual harassment allegations against then-Supreme  
Court nominee Clarence Thomas was typical of past PBS 
transgressions, Graham said. These days, he argued, PBS avoids 
controversy by fielding softball shows. 
</P>
<P>
	'' 'Frontline was doing a lot of shows critical of the Reagan  
administration. Now they're doing stories about Hillary Clinton's 
college class,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is inherent, he said. ``Conservatives don't believe  
that government should be in the business of broadcasting. 
Therefore, who works in public broadcasting? Not those who don't 
believe it should exist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is PBS' existence, not mailing lists, that is at the heart of  
the current debate, contends Bill Moyers, whose public affairs 
shows are a longtime public broadcasting staple. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of right-wing, ideological opponents of public  
broadcasting who would use some of the good things we do, and some 
of the dumb mistakes we make, to club public broadcasting. Every 
time they try, they get defeated -- not by public television, but by 
the people public television serves. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be a great disservice to the public if a regrettable  
oversight (by the PBS stations) were sensationalized and used as 
political ammunition against a service the public greatly 
appreciates,'' Moyers said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	MODERN MODELS: ``Models Uncovered'' is the title, but this TLC  
program is about more than lingerie. Top models including Cindy 
Crawford and Naomi Campbell talk about their rise, the pressures of 
being in the spotlight and how the perception of them as ``pretty 
faces'' belies the control they have over their careers. The 
two-hour ``Models Uncovered'' debuts 9 p.m. EDT Saturday on the 
cable channel. 
</P>
