<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> St. Paul Cos. To Cut 1,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- The St. Paul Cos. plans to cut about  
1,000 jobs as part of an effort to reduce expenses by $100 million 
next year in the highly competitive insurance industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the cuts will be identified in the third quarter and  
will be completed by the end of this year, the company announced 
today. The St. Paul expects to take a related charge in the third 
quarter of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a further step to position The St. Paul to succeed in  
the fiercely competitive property-casualty insurance industry,'' 
said Douglas Leatherdale, chairman and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have taken a hard look at how we improve our profitability  
and our service to customers,'' Leatherdale said. ``These efforts 
are not taken lightly and are not optional.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company will provide severance pay for affected employees  
and will help them find other jobs, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new layoffs are separate from actions associated with the  
company's pending sale of its personal insurance operations to 
MetLife Auto and Home. 
</P>
<P>
	That sale, announced on July 12, is expected to result in the  
transfer of approximately 1,700 personal insurance employees to 
MetLife and the elimination of 500 to 600 jobs. These reductions 
will cut expenses by approximately $50 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest cuts also follow the elimination of 2,000 jobs in the  
merger with Baltimore-based insurer USF&AMP;G that closed in April 
1998. That merger is expected to save $260 million for The St. Paul 
by the end of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The St. Paul-based insurer, which had 1998 revenues of $9.1  
billion, provides property-liability insurance, reinsurance and 
life insurance products and services worldwide. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
