<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Head of Horace Mann School Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WALLINGFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Russell Inslee Clark Jr., former  
president of the prestigious Horace Mann School in New York and 
Yale admissions dean, died Tuesday of a heart attack. He was 64. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark suffered a head injury in a fall last month while working  
as a counselor at a summer camp in Westport, N.Y. Complications 
developed and he died at Gaylord Hospital, Horace Mann said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Yale graduate, Clark became dean of the school's Trumbell  
College in 1963. He was Yale's dean of admissions from 1965 to 
1969, successfully pushing for the admission of women. He also 
lectured in sociology. 
</P>
<P>
	He became headmaster of Horace Mann in 1970. During a period of  
rapid change, he eliminated the traditional dress code of jacket 
and tie, oversaw the prep school's merger with Barnard School in 
1973 and pushed for the admission of girls, which began in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	He was promoted to president in 1981, putting him in charge of  
Horace Mann's four campuses in New York and Connecticut. During his 
tenure, the school's enrollment increased from 600 to 1,640, its 
staff more than doubled from 125 to 300 and its annual budget grew 
from $1 million to $15 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark also taught courses on government and was Horace Mann's  
baseball coach from 1975-91. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by two brothers.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
