<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rescue Workers Search for More Bodies  
</P>
<P>
	GAISAL, India (AP) -- At least 257 bodies have been removed from  
the mangled wreckage of two trains that collided yesterday in a 
remote section of northeast India. About 50 more people were 
thought to be inside three smashed train cars, but authorities 
feared that none could have survived. Railway officials said one of 
the trains was on the wrong track for unknown reasons. Railway 
Minister Nitish Kumar said today the accident was caused by 
``criminal negligence,'' and announced his resignation. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Releases $55M for Cooling  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today released $55 million  
in federal aid to help residents of nine Southern and Midwestern 
states cope with the heat. The money, provided under a program that 
is used more often to help low-income people pay for heat during 
the winter, may be used to buy air conditioners, fans and other 
relief. White House officials said the nine states would be 
identified later in the day. 

</P>
<P>
	Serb Suspect Faces Arraignment  
</P>
<P>
	THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- A Bosnian Serb accused of  
enslaving and raping Bosnian Muslim women in 1992-93 will be 
arraigned tomorrow at the Yugoslav war crimes tribunal, the U.N. 
court announced today. Radomir Kovac, 38, was arrested yesterday by 
NATO troops serving in the international Stabilization Force in 
Bosnia and flown to the tribunal's detention unit in a suburb of 
The Hague. Kovac faces a maximum sentence of life imprisonment if 
convicted of either charge. He is one of eight Serbs accused of 
raping Muslims in his hometown of Foca during the 1992-95 Bosnian 
war. 

</P>
<P>
	Regulators Targeting Travel Agents  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission today will  
announce cases against five travel companies accused of defrauding 
customers by not disclosing the full terms and costs of their 
trips. The Transportation Department is taking action against two 
other operators. Between July of 1998 and 1999, the FTC received 
nearly 2,500 travel-related complaints worth more than $610,000 in 
alleged consumer losses. Of those complaints, nearly a third were 
against companies based in Florida. The American Society of Travel 
Agents, for instance, estimates that $8 billion to $10 billion is 
lost a year because of travel scams. 

</P>
<P>
	China Offers Reward for Sect Members  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's police force will begin paying cash  
rewards for tips leading to the capture of wanted criminals, and 
the first on the list is the leader of a banned meditation sect, a 
Beijing newspaper reported today. According to the reports, police 
will pay more than $6,000 for information enabling them to capture 
wanted criminals. One TV report said the capture of Li Hongzhi, 
leader of the banned Falun Gong sect, is a top priority. Li, who 
now lives in New York, is accused of staging unauthorized protests 
and spreading superstition. 

</P>
<P>
	Defendant in Gay Murder Rejects Plea  
</P>
<P>
	ROCKFORD, Ala. (AP) -- A construction worker accused of killing a  
gay man over an unwanted sexual advance has rejected a plea 
bargain, refusing to plead guilty to protect himself from a 
potential death sentence. Charles M. Butler is one of two men 
charged in the Feb. 19 slaying of Billy Jack Gaither, who was 
beaten with an ax handle and burned atop a pile of kerosene-soaked 
tires. Co-defendant Steven Eric Mullins, who has pleaded guilty, is 
expected to testify against Butler. Prosecutors have agreed to 
recommend a sentence of life in prison without parole for Mullins. 

</P>
<P>
	`Good' Cholesterol Gene Discovered  
</P>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Researchers have identified a gene that  
regulates the level of so-called good cholesterol in the body. 
Flaws in the gene, known as ABC1, prevent the production of a 
protein that the body needs to rinse excess bad cholesterol and 
other fats out of cells and the bloodstream. The gene was 
discovered by researchers looking for the cause of Tangier disease, 
an extremely rare inherited illness in which the body produces 
virtually none of the good cholesterol, HDL. Without it, the level 
of the bad cholesterol, LDL, and other fats that contribute to 
heart attacks and clogged arteries rise unchecked. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 64  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 10 a.m. EDT, the Dow industrials  
were up 64.59 to 10,710.55. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 985-655. The Nasdaq was up 13.02 to 
2,636.65. 

</P>
<P>
	Cards, Boston Agree on Contract  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) -- Wide receiver David Boston, Arizona's top  
pick in the draft, reached a contract agreement with the team late 
last night, the team announced. Boston will get $7 million over 
four years, including a $3.8 million signing bonus. Boston missed 
the first four days of training camp as negotiations dragged on. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
