<HEADLINE> Stocks Mostly Lower; Dow Up 3.17 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned mostly lower today after a strong  
opening as interest rate concerns kept investors on edge. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up  
just 3.17 at 10,649.13, dropping back from an earlier gain of more 
than 60 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 7.58 at 1,320.47, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was down 34.98 at 2,588.65. 
</P>
<P>
	Concerns that the Federal Reserve will raise rates later this  
month in an effort to cool off the economy held most stocks back. 
The Conference Board provided the latest hint that the nation's 
unbridled economic growth is continuing, announcing that its index 
of leading indicators rose 0.3 percent in June, matching its May 
increase. The index is used to forecast economic trends for the 
coming three to six months. 
</P>
<P>
	The threat of higher rates has rattled stocks and bonds in the  
past week, dragging stock indexes well below the record highs of 
mid-July. Today, bond prices slipped once more, sending the yield 
on the 30-year Treasury bond to 6.13 percent, up from 6.12 percent 
late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stocks are attempting to do battle within an investment  
climate that is not reacting favorably to bonds and is showing no 
concrete or consistent means of leadership,'' said Brian G. Belski, 
chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City, 
Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	A report that ExciteAtHome may be acquired by Yahoo! for a price  
greater than ExciteAtHome's $17 billion market value stimulated 
some early buying in Internet and telecommunications companies. 
Shares of ExciteAtHome slipped back, however, when the company's 
president denied the rumors, falling 5/8 to 42 5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Bill Burnham, an Internet analyst at Credit Suisse  
First Boston, said in a report that online brokerages may 
experience their first-ever decline in trading volume in the third 
quarter. Shares of ETrade fell 4 to 25, and Charles Schwab fell 4 
1/16 to 38 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 12-to-7 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 328.53 million 
shares, ahead of Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 3.47 at 621.87, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 0.48 at 784.16. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was down 5.21 at  
437.42. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
