<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alaskans Lose Internet Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE (AP) -- Internet Alaska customers statewide lost access  
to the Internet for up to six hours Monday when an electrical spike 
shut down equipment in Anchorage, company officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem occurred at Anchorage Telephone Utility's north wire  
center, where Internet Alaska leases space. A momentary loss of 
electricity caused a power spike at the wire center and an ATU 
backup battery burst under the sudden load, said Mike Method, ATU's 
account manager for Internet service providers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had smoke and sizzle for about a second, which is all it  
takes to lose equipment,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet Alaska spokeswoman Holly Lind said the power loss  
scrambled data. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like turning your computer off and not saving anything,''  
she said. The service shut down at 1:50 p.m. and was restored by 
about 8 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Lind declined to say how many customers lost service, but the  
company's entire statewide system was affected. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
