<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Endorses Democrat Farm Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore raised the political  
stakes over emergency farm aid today by endorsing a $11 billion 
assistance package proposed by Senate Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's move, which could help his presidential prospects in  
Iowa, rankled Republicans, who fear getting into a bidding war with 
the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Farmers out there are really hurting badly. ... Many are now  
saying this could turn out to be the worst crisis our farmers have 
ever experienced,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	As Gore was speaking in the Capitol, Agriculture Secretary Dan  
Glickman declined to tell the Senate Agriculture Committee how much 
help he thought farmers needed. He said he saw good things in both 
the Democratic proposal and a GOP plan that would cost $4 billion 
less. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to be in a position of saying you have to spend  
'x' dollars or 'y' dollars,'' Glickman said. Asked whether the 
president would veto the GOP plan, he said, ``I'm not looking for a 
fight, if that's your bottom-line question.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Citing Gore's endorsement of the Democratic proposal, the  
committee's chairman, Sen. Dick Lugar, told Glickman, ``I'm not 
clear where the locus of authority is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last fall, Republicans proposed a $4 billion aid package only to  
have it vetoed by President Clinton. In the end, Congress approved 
$6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., said Monday the GOP package would  
``provide a wide range of benefits to producers who are eligible 
for ... assistance because of economic disasters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lugar, R-Ind., suggested that $2 billion to $3 billion in aid  
may be sufficient. 
</P>
<P>
	But farm groups say that far more than that will be needed to  
prevent thousands of producers from going out of business. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats proposed $10.8 billion in aid Monday, while  
Republicans countered with a $6.7 billion plan. The money would be 
added to an annual spending bill for the Agriculture Department. 
</P>
<P>
	``Silently and quietly, American farmers and ranchers are losing  
their businesses. They are at the end of their rope,'' said Sen. 
Tom Harkin, D-Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	The first vote was expected after separate meetings of  
Democratic and GOP senators. 
</P>
<P>
	A worldwide glut of grain has kept commodity prices low for the  
second year in a row, and USDA projects that net farm income will 
dip to $43.8 billion this year, about 4 percent off the average for 
the decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic plan includes nearly $6 billion in extra crop  
subsidies, $2.3 billion in disaster aid, and $1.4 billion in 
emergency trade provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the GOP package would go toward doubling the annual  
``market transition'' payments that farmers receive from the 
government under the 1996 farm bill. 
</P>
<P>
	That the Republicans even offered a proposal of their own this  
week was a recognition of how potent a political issue the farm 
economy has become. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders had argued that it was too early to know how  
much help farmers will need this fall and they had pressed the 
Clinton administration without success to offer its own proposal. 
The emergency label on the extra aid lets Congress ignore required 
spending limits and pay for items with the anticipated federal 
budget surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	But several farm-state GOP senators have argued that it was  
important for the Senate to take some action before lawmakers start 
their long summer recess next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate leaders put off until Wednesday a debate over the way the  
government regulates dairy prices. A proposal by New England 
lawmakers would bar USDA from going forward with an overhaul of the 
pricing system and also allow their states to continue fixing milk 
prices for another year. 
</P>
<P>
	Senators from the upper Midwest have threatened to filibuster  
the spending bill over the issue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hoops Catch on in Pan Am Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Halfway through the basketball  
competition in the Pan-American Games, the United States teams are 
starting to catch on. 
</P>
<P>
	They're getting used to the nuances of the international game  
and the way it's officiated. They're adjusting to life in the 
athletes village. And they've learned that while they may not be 
reviled, they aren't the fan favorites, either. 
</P>
<P>
	That became clear when the men beat Brazil 73-71. As Brazil  
mounted a late comeback, the fans who had stayed after Canada's 
game took up the Brazilians' cause. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's us against the world. Nobody is rooting for us,'' forward  
Travis Williams said. ``The fans want us to autograph their 
pennants and flags and programs, but once the game starts, they're 
against us. They might cheer a dunk, but that's about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The men, an all-star team from the Continental Basketball  
Association, are 2-0 and should beat the Dominican Republic (1-1) 
in the final round of pool play on Wednesday. That would clinch 
first place for the Americans in their pool. The top two advance to 
the medal round. 
</P>
<P>
	The women (2-2), who play Canada in their last preliminary game  
on Wednesday, have clinched a berth in the medal round. 
</P>
<P>
	A 95-64 loss to Cuba on Saturday was the worst ever by an  
American women's team in Pan Am play, but the Americans turned it 
around in the last two games and are coming off the best effort so 
far, a 77-72 loss to unbeaten Brazil in which they led by 16 points 
in the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took us four games to finally show what kind of team we  
are,'' guard Edwina Brown said. ``The previous games, we were 
playing like the other team. We were trying to beat them at their 
game instead of playing our own game. So I think we've learned to 
go out and play our game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That game is running, and the Americans, a young team with  
little international experience, had their fast break operating at 
peak efficiency until the Brazilians slowed them with a zone 
defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pleased with our progression,'' said Fortner, whose team  
has averaged 82 points in the last two games after averaging 63.5 
in the first two. ``I think this team played (Brazil) like they're 
capable of playing. That was a lot of fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil and Cuba will finish 1-2 in the preliminary rounds, so  
the United States would have to beat at least one and probably both 
to win the gold medal. Fortner would like to have that chance. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we played Cuba again, we would play them better,'' she  
said. ``At least we would have that experience under our belt and I 
don't think we'd let that happen to us again. If we played Brazil 
again, I think we would feel like we could beat them. I think it 
would be a very good game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The men held on against Brazil after two of their best inside  
players, Mikki Moore and Byron Houston, fouled out. Players go out 
with five fouls in international play. They're given six in the 
CBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``These games are a good adjustment for our guys to learn to  
play with two fouls,'' said U.S. coach Mo McHone, who coaches the 
CBA's Sioux Falls Skyforce. ``When you foul out with five, that one 
foul is a huge difference. We as coaches have got to adjust to that 
in our substituting. We've got to get back to that international 
mode.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McHone said his players also must understand that these games  
are going to be called differently than American pro games. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest thing for us is we have to get used to playing  
against those European patterns. Our players just aren't used to 
all those moving screens,'' McHone said. ``You can't do that in the 
CBA. But our guys are making the adjustment. They're doing a nice 
job.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
