<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 13:10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FTC Cites Five Travel Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal and state authorities announced  
actions against 25 travel companies Tuesday accused of luring 
consumers with flashy vacation offers and failing to disclose the 
full terms and costs of their trips. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Trade Commission filed suit against five businesses  
asking that they stop their deceptive practices and seeking refunds 
for bilked consumers. Two other restitution orders have been filed 
on behalf of the Transportation Department, and an additional 20 
companies face charges by state regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Between July of 1998 and 1999, the FTC received nearly 2,500  
travel-related complaints worth more than $610,000 in alleged 
consumer losses. Of those complaints, nearly a third were against 
companies based in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	But the problem may be much more pervasive. The American Society  
of Travel Agents, for instance, estimates that $8 billion to $10 
billion is lost a year because of travel scams. 
</P>
<P>
	While travel scams are always a problem, ``they proliferate when  
demand is high for certain types of travel,'' says Dina Long, 
spokeswoman for the society. 
</P>
<P>
	At this time of year, consumers receive faxes touting special,  
cheap cruise tickets even when the ship line does not give 
discounts, Long says. 
</P>
<P>
	The approaching millennium celebration already is proving a gold  
mine for opportunists to exploit travelers who are willing to pay 
higher than premium prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are coming out of the woodwork with offers that are too  
good to be true,'' Long said. 
</P>
<P>
	The five companies targeted by the FTC are First Impressions  
Inc. of Fort Lauderdale, Fla.; All Around Travel Club Inc. of 
Lauderdale Lakes, Fla.; ASQ Inc. of Las Vegas; Cerkvenik-Anderson 
Travel of Phoenix; and American International Travel Services Inc. 
of Deerfield Beach, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Cerkvenik-Anderson's general counsel, Brian Burt, denied the  
charges and said the commission was ``painting with a broad brush'' 
in including the business in its complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	Messages left with other companies were not returned.  
</P>
<P>
	Charlene Kuhaupt of Mesquite, Texas, expected a ``nice  
adventure'' after reviewing the glitzy promotional videos and 
brochures provided by American International Travel Service for her 
week-long Caribbean vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, she got hassled for refusing to attend a promotional  
meeting for time-share condos, was told she would have to pay extra 
for a cabin aboard her ``cruise'' ship to the Bahamas and 
discovered her hotel food and drink vouchers were only valid at 
certain times of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``They told a little bit of truth and covered up the rest to  
make it look like something it was not,'' said Kuhaupt. 
</P>
<P>
	In one typical travel scam, consumers receive a fancy-looking  
travel certificate in the mail claiming that they have won a free 
hotel stay. When travelers call to claim their prize, they may have 
to pay the price of a plane ticket at a huge markup. A similar scam 
involves trips in which consumers must tour a time-share condo 
while on vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Internet sites and print advertisements urge consumers to  
become a travel agent overnight, so they can reap the benefits of 
discounted industry fares. The problem is that the travel agent 
credentials -- which can cost as much as $495 -- are fake and won't 
be recognized by companies. Consumers who use them also are 
committing fraud. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
