<DOCNO> APW19990803.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 20:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Charles Oakley got the Hollywood treatment from the Los Angeles  
Lakers on Tuesday, lunch with Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant and 
a tour of the new arena from Jerry West. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Mercer was shipped from Boston to Denver, Bo Outlaw  
re-signed with Orlando and Derek Fisher landed a seven-year 
contract from the Lakers, who are trying to convince Oakley to play 
power forward for them for $2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakley is demanding $8.5 million annually for three years from  
the Toronto Raptors, who have offered $5.5 million per year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Contrary to what people in Toronto are saying, the Raptors  
haven't increased their offer,'' said Oakley's agent, Billy 
Diamond, who accompanied the veteran power forward during his 
afternoon of courtship with the Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercer was traded from the Celtics to the Nuggets in a  
six-player deal that also sent Popeye Jones and Dwayne Schintzius 
to Denver for Danny Fortson, Eric Washington, Eric Williams and a 
first-round draft choice in one of the next three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortson, a 6-foot-7 forward who ranked fourth in the NBA in  
rebounding last season, is going into the final season of his 
three-year rookie contract -- just like Mercer. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston did not want to meet Mercer's asking price, which was  
believed to be in excess of $50 million for a six-year extension. 
Mercer can be a free agent next year, and indicated he wouldn't 
re-sign with Boston if he wasn't given an extension this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had no desire to trade Ron Mercer,'' coach Rick Pitino  
said. ``I could not even come close to the numbers Ron Mercer 
wanted as a basketball player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outlaw, Orlando's wiry 6-foot-8 forward, re-signed with the  
Magic for one year and $2 million. He said he turned down more 
lucrative offers elsewhere to remain in Orlando. Outlaw will have 
full Larry Bird rights next summer, meaning the Magic will be able 
to exceed the salary cap to re-sign him again. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher, who split time with Derek Harper at point guard last  
season for the Lakers, signed a seven-year contract worth about $24 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sacramento Kings re-signed guard Jon Barry and forward Scot  
Pollard. They also acquired guard Nick Anderson from Orlando for 
guard Tariq Abdul-Wahad and a future first-round draft pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry got a three-year contract and Pollard signed for two  
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakley is being courted by several teams seeking to add an  
experienced big body along the front line. He has been in Los 
Angeles since last weekend, attending Magic Johnson's charity game, 
playing golf with Lakers representatives an finally going through 
the team's full court press Tuesday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	So eager are the Lakers to convince Oakley to sign that O'Neal  
and Bryant, not the best of friends during their three seasons 
together in Los Angeles, agreed to have lunch together with Oakley 
and Diamond. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakley later joined West and general manager Mitch Kupchak for a  
tour of the team's new practice facility and the Staples center, 
which will replace the Forum. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortson, who plays center and power forward, averaged 11.0  
points and 11.6 rebounds per game last year. His playing time 
increased considerably after rookie Raef LaFrentz went down early 
in the season with a knee injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercer, the sixth pick overall in the 1997 draft, averaged 17  
points per game last season with 2.5 assists and 3.8 rebounds. The 
6-foot-7, 210-pound Mercer was an NBA All-Rookie Team selection in 
1997-98 when he averaged 15.3 points per game. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal sends Williams back to the city where he played the  
first two years of his career. Williams averaged 15 points per game 
for the Celtics in 1996-1997. Last year in Denver, Williams 
averaged 7.3 points and 2.1 rebounds per game. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams is entering the third year of a four-year, $30 million  
contract. Denver agreed to pay $3 million of Williams' contract 
this year, the maximum percentage allowed by the league. 
</P>
<P>
	The Celtics also announced the signing of free agent guard Wayne  
Turner, a Boston native who played for Kentucky, as a third guard 
for the Celtics. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nets waived center Rony Seikaly, who played just 18 games  
over 1 1/2 with New Jersey because of injuries. New Jersey still owes 
Seikaly $4.5 million for the final season of his contract. The 
34-year-old was hampered by ankle and foot injuries during the 1999 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Isiah Thomas agreed to buy a majority stake of the Continental  
Basketball Association for about $10 million. Thomas, a 12-time 
All-Star and former part-owner and general manager of the Toronto 
Raptors, wants to reorganize the nine separately owned teams into a 
single entity with players signing contracts with the league, not 
the individual teams. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The players' union refused to comment to a report in the  
Charlotte Observer than director Billy Hunter is being given a 
six-year, $12 million contract. Hunter made less than $1 million a 
year while negotiating the collective bargaining agreement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 16:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Start Date for Eagles' McNabb Mulled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) -- As Troy Vincent so aptly put it,  
Philadelphia Eagles camp has been mostly about one person so far. 
</P>
<P>
	``Donovan, Donovan, Donovan, Donovan, Donovan,'' Vincent said  
when asked one of the dozens of questions posed about Donovan 
McNabb. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that McNabb finally is signed and in camp, the most obvious  
question is: When will he start? 
</P>
<P>
	This is one of many important questions facing the Eagles,  
trying to climb from beneath the wreckage of last year's 3-13 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	Although new coach Andy Reid named Doug Pederson the starter  
long ago, some estimates have McNabb, the second overall pick in 
the draft, winning the job as early as Week 4. As the projection 
goes, the Eagles figure to be 0-3 by then and facing the New York 
Giants on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	Why then? Well, the Cowboys visit Philadelphia the following  
week. After what happened on Monday Night Football against Dallas 
last year -- a 34-0 national embarrassment -- that might be too much 
of a pressure-cooker to throw McNabb into for his first start. 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb clearly has the strongest arm and the most potential of  
the four quarterbacks in camp. Though the Eagles could do worse -- 
and have -- than begin the season with McNabb as the starter, it is 
a delicate topic given the coach's commitment to Pederson. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not even going to touch that one,'' receiver Charles  
Johnson said. ``Everyone knows the deal, even Donovan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Listing the rest of the questions would give McNabb's 32-page  
contract a serious challenge for longest document of training camp. 
Here are just a few: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Is Reid the right coach?  
</P>
<P>
	The answer may not be known for a couple of years, and the  
Eagles' record this season shouldn't entirely be held against him. 
There are simply too many players still around from last year's 
deplorable team. 
</P>
<P>
	But Reid has made a definite impression on the players and those  
following the team. He is incredibly organized, energetic and 
demanding. He pushed the team through grueling two-a-days last week 
in the middle of a relentless heat wave. He takes such an active 
role during practices that he already is drawing comparisons to 
Dick Vermeil. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Eagles are a bad team again, it won't be for lack of  
trying -- or preparation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing I found out in those first six practices is,'' Reid  
said, ``that's a tough group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- Who's going to catch the ball?  
</P>
<P>
	This is a major concern for the Eagles, who are perhaps  
instituting the most aggressive passing offense ever seen in 
Philadelphia. As Johnson puts it, ``This offense isn't going to go 
anywhere unless we catch the ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Eagles are counting on Johnson, a secondary receiver in  
Pittsburgh last season, to step into the No. 1 role. Torrance Small 
will be asked to expand on the big-play potential he showed in 
Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is, Johnson brings a reputation for dropping balls  
with him from Pittsburgh, and he's exhibited that tendency in 
practice so far. If too many passes are dropped, the Eagles' best 
offseason move may end up being the signing of punter Sean Landeta. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Who will call the plays?  
</P>
<P>
	Reid says he will call offensive plays instead of offensive  
coordinator Rod Dowhower, a respected, experienced assistant. 
Either way, it has to be an improvement over last year, when 
play-calling duties were stripped from offensive coordinator Dana 
Bible and given to assistant Bill Musgrave. 
</P>
<P>
	The Eagles had the worst offense in the NFL last season,  
prompting this sign to be displayed at Veterans Stadium: ``We may 
have a Bible, but we don't have a prayer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- If Jeremiah Trotter is good enough to start at middle  
linebacker, why did the Eagles draft Barry Gardner? 
</P>
<P>
	Good question, although Gardner has looked sensational in  
practice the past few days. But Trotter, who never won the starting 
job under Ray Rhodes, has made so much progress that Reid may have 
to start both of them -- perhaps moving Trotter to outsider 
linebacker. 
</P>
<P>
	If they'd known that, the Eagles might have filled a need at  
wide receiver with their second-round pick instead of taking 
Gardner. 
</P>
<P>
	-- What will their record be?  
</P>
<P>
	All the ingredients are in place for a new beginning. The Eagles  
have a new coach, a new philosophy, a franchise quarterback and 
reason for optimism. They also have the luxury of a last-place 
schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately, many believe they still have last-place talent.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to play every game as hard as we can, we're going  
to be competitive and we plan to win,'' said Tom Modrak, director 
of football operations. ``There isn't another team in the league 
that doesn't have the same plan.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 15:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lions Comment on Boyd's Billboard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLINTON TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- The billboard along westbound  
Interstate 94 in this Macomb County community features the Detroit 
Lions logo, the surly visage of linebacker Stephen Boyd and the 
caption, ``I stayed here to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In your face, ex-Lion Barry Sanders?  
</P>
<P>
	Not at all, Lions marketing director Steve Harms said Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was not in response to Barry's leaving at all,'' he said.  
``In the aftermath of Barry's retirement, though, I could see some 
people asking about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The billboards featuring Boyd, quarterback Charlie Batch, wide  
receiver Herman Moore and defensive end Robert Porcher, went up 
about a month ago in the Detroit area, Harms said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boyd's statement reflects his decision to stay with Detroit  
after becoming a free agent at the end of last season, Harms said. 
He conceded that Lions marketers might have paraphrased remarks 
Boyd made off the cuff while being photographed for the billboard. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, who announced his retirement July 25, wasn't going to  
be included in the billboard campaign, Harms said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't do any more about Barry Sanders'' in terms of  
marketing, he said. ``He's about as good as you can get, in terms 
of fan recognition.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
