<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Toys R Us Recalls Doll Sets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- About 71,000 dolls that come with bathtub  
accessories were recalled today by the U.S. Consumer Product Safety 
Commission because the toys pose a choking risk to young children. 
</P>
<P>
	Bathtub Baby -- a vinyl doll that comes with a blue plastic  
bathtub, a fish-shaped strainer and a small pink ball -- was sold at 
Toys R Us stores from October 1998 until last month. After 
inspecting the toy, the commission determined the ball was too 
small for children under 3 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	Owners should immediately return the doll set for a refund. Toys  
R Us sold Bathtub Baby for about $2. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TV Helicopter Spots Women Adrift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A mother and daughter adrift overnight were plucked  
from the Atlantic Ocean on Tuesday morning after they were spotted 
by the crew of a news helicopter, and said they were grateful to be 
alive despite jellyfish stings and hypothermia. 
</P>
<P>
	Anna Goodwyn, 50, and Vicky Goodwyn, 32, were still wearing  
their orange life jackets and crying with relief during their 
rescue, which was aired live on a midday Miami news show. 
</P>
<P>
	They had been floating in relatively calm waters for almost 20  
hours, according to the U.S. Coast Guard. Their 15-foot pleasure 
boat took on water Monday at about 3:30 p.m. then sank off Elliott 
Key, about 20 miles southeast of Miami in or near Biscayne National 
Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``The boat just took on a wave real quick,'' Anna Goodwyn said.  
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Hernandez, 32, had been on the boat with his girlfriend  
and her mother, but left them in a bid to swim the 11 miles back to 
shore. He was rescued by a passing boater. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was very worried to leave them alone,'' Hernandez said.  
``I'm lucky they saved me, I really am lucky. Thank God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At first the three tied themselves together, and Hernandez later  
tried to make it to shore to get help. 
</P>
<P>
	The mother and daughter were spotted Tuesday by a news  
helicopter from WTVJ-TV, which notified the Coast Guard. They were 
taken from the water by a park ranger in a patrol boat called in by 
the Coast Guard. 
</P>
<P>
	The women were spotted at about 11 a.m. and the station  
broadcast live shots of the women bobbing in the water, one crying 
with relief and waving at the helicopter, the other appearing weak 
and barely moving. 
</P>
<P>
	They apparently suffered from hypothermia, exposure and  
jellyfish stings. 
</P>
<P>
	``The waves come into your mouth so strong that you can't  
breathe,'' Anna Goodwyn said as she was brought ashore and 
airlifted to Mercy Hospital. Her daughter and Hernandez were taken 
to the bayside hospital by a park patrol boat. 
</P>
<P>
	All three were later listed as stable.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll never go back out there again, ever,'' Vicky Goodwyn  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
