<HEADLINE> Rep. Brown's Widow To Run for Seat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The widow of Rep. George E. Brown  
plans to run for her late husband's seat, setting up a tough 
Democratic primary battle. 
</P>
<P>
	Marta Macias Brown, 54, plans to announce her candidacy  
Wednesday, said Art Torres, chairman of the California Democratic 
Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Her entry into the nationally watched race will pit two Hispanic  
Democrats against each other in a Southern California district that 
is increasingly Hispanic. 
</P>
<P>
	It will also force Mrs. Brown's leading Democratic opponent,  
Sen. Joe Baca, to campaign against the widow of a popular 
congressman. Brown was the oldest member of the House at 79. He was 
elected 18 times. 
</P>
<P>
	The race comes a year before the November 2000 elections, when  
Republicans will try to retain their slim majority in the House. 
The national Republican and Democratic parties are likely to pour 
large sums into the race. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
