<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High Jumper Flunks Drug Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Juana Rosario Arrendel of the  
Dominican Republic, winner of the women's high jump at the Pan 
American Games, failed a drug test, organizers said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosario Arrendel was quoted in the Dominican Republic as denying  
she used the banned anabolic steroid stanozolol and said the test 
may have picked up a decongestant she used before the event. 
</P>
<P>
	``In six years in athletics, I have never used substances to  
enhance my performance,'' she said in remarks published today in 
the newspaper La Informacion. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray Martinez, a baseball player from Mexico, refused to take a  
drug test Monday, Pan Ams officials also said. Organizers said that 
was tantamount to a positive test. 
</P>
<P>
	Pan American Sports Organization president Mario Vazquez Rana  
was asked about four-time men's high jump champion and world 
record-holder Javier Sotomayor of Cuba failing a drug test. While 
Rana refused to speak about Sotomayor specficially, he did mention 
that a third athlete's A test had come back positive. But until his 
B sample is examined, no name will be revealed. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosario, who won the gold medal with a leap of 6 feet, 4 inches,  
is the Dominican's only gold medalist at the games so far. The 
Dominican Republic also has won one silver and one bronze medal. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the second drug case at these games. Steve Vezina, the  
goalkeeper for Canada's in-line roller hockey team which beat the 
United States 7-6 in the title game, tested positive for stimulants 
and steroids. Canada was stripped of the gold, which was awarded to 
the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Dominicans being stripped of Rosario's medal,  
Argentina's Solange Witteveen, the runner-up, gets the gold. The 
silver goes to Brazil's Luciane Dambacher, and the bronze to 
Canada's Nicole Forrester. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
