<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DuBose Family Wants Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Relatives of a former pro football player  
killed by police officers have started their own investigation 
after witnesses said the athlete may have been shot in the back. 
</P>
<P>
	Demetrius DuBose, 28, a former linebacker for the Tampa Bay  
Buccaneers, was shot several times by two officers on July 24, 
after he allegedly charged at them with a martial arts weapon he 
took from an officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Police Chief David Bejarano said his department's investigation  
is expected to be completed within two weeks, and the results will 
be turned over to prosecutors. He said he welcomes outside comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The family's preliminary findings show DuBose was calm and  
cooperated with officers' investigation of a burglary report until 
they began to ``intimidate and harass'' him, said H.J. Sims of the 
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People in San 
Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was only after they tried to place him in handcuffs that  
the unprofessionalism of police allowed the situation to escalate 
and prompted the gentleman to run,'' Sims said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego City Councilman George Stevens said some witnesses  
said DuBose was bending over when he was shot and others said he 
was turning away. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers claim DuBose resisted attempts to question him and  
appeared to be under the influence of alcohol or other drugs. Sims 
said DuBose had drank a beer earlier in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers who shot DuBose have been removed from field work  
pending the investigation. Their names have not been released. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose had been arrested three times in the past year on  
suspicion of drug use or disorderly conduct. Two arrests were in 
California and one was at a nightclub in South Bend, Ind. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
