<DOCNO> APW19990803.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 13:10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Intensity Steps Up in Iowa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANOLA, Iowa (AP) -- At the Crouse Cafe, where the meatloaf  
special was $4.95, Gary Bauer talked heatedly about U.S. dues to 
the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	A couple of blocks away at a library, Alan Keyes enlisted block  
captains in his ``Iowa Sacred Honor Guard'' as he spoke to 24 
supporters about ``issues that address the moral decline.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They were among six Republican presidential contenders who  
crisscrossed Iowa on Tuesday in search of backers willing to show 
up at the Aug. 14 straw poll in Ames, an event into which campaigns 
are throwing money, workers, energy and candidate time. 
</P>
<P>
	Though nothing real is at stake in the straw poll, there's a ton  
of symbolism and the candidates are treating it with all the 
grimness of armed combat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, we're doing it one on one, meeting with people in  
the way they're used to in Iowa,'' said former cabinet secretary 
Elizabeth Dole. ``I don't think people want to substitute that 
retail politicking for 30-second spots.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm eating meatloaf all over Iowa,'' said Bauer.  
</P>
<P>
	There's absolutely no doubt the candidates are fighting it out.  
Publisher Steve Forbes had stops in Iowa City and Cedar Rapids on 
Tuesday, while commentator Pat Buchanan was in the state and Utah 
Sen. Orrin Hatch was wrapping up a five-day swing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really the beginning of the winnowing factor,'' said Bob  
Haus, who runs the state for Forbes. ``It's separating the wheat 
from the chaff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa's precinct caucuses early next year launch the presidential  
nominating season, and with a large and varied field of GOP 
candidates many are eager for a measurement of how they are doing. 
The straw poll offers such a measure, albeit a limited one. 
</P>
<P>
	``It decides absolutely nothing, but it has tremendous symbolic  
value put on it by the candidates and the press,'' said Drake 
University political science professor Dennis Goldford. 
</P>
<P>
	Some argue the event is an organizational test that's important  
in a state where precinct caucuses demand organizational prowess at 
a much higher level than in a state holding a traditional primary. 
</P>
<P>
	``The straw poll basically only represents a test of how many  
people you can get to show up at that event, yet showing up is what 
it's all about,'' said Keyes, who said he plans three events a day 
every day until the straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Haus said Forbes' bus would rumble through 77 of the state's 99  
counties, building toward the event. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're putting a substantial ground effort into the field,''  
said Haus. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush upped the ante, when he said he would  
not only compete in the straw poll, but would play to win. With a 
big lead in the polls and in money, that enhanced the straw's 
status. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've really raised the stakes on this thing,'' said Haus.  
</P>
<P>
	The event promises to be a spectacle, with each campaign  
erecting giant tents and tossing celebrity-laden parties for 
backers. Bush spent $43,000 just to rent a space near the 
auditorium for the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides said Bush is simply running a traditional organizational  
effort building to the event. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just doing the standard straw poll attendee  
identification,'' said spokesman Eric Woolson. 
</P>
<P>
	The intensity is a boon for the Republican Party, which is  
getting $25 for every ticket and party officials are gloating about 
the hype. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to think it was a brilliant media strategy on our  
part,'' said GOP executive director Dee Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the 400 or so press credentials, several foreign  
embassies have sent word they'll have delegations on hand to 
witness this rather bizarre part of an election process that will 
culminate with selection of the next leader of the free world. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a 20-person delegation from Mozambique,'' Finance  
Director Sara Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	Scheduled to speak are Keyes, Dan Quayle, Hatch, Bauer, Forbes,  
Bush, Mrs. Dole, Buchanan and Lamar Alexander, in that order. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Arizona Sen. John McCain has chosen to bypass the event.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
