<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Memorial Design Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The staff of the National Capital Planning  
Commission today approved a design for a memorial to 
Japanese-Americans in a small park near the Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	Commission approval could come at a meeting scheduled Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	A 15-foot statue of cranes struggling to fly through barbed wire  
will dominate the three-quarter-acre plot. The cranes symbolize the 
115,000 Japanese-Americans interned in camps on the West Coast 
during World War II. The Supreme Court upheld the action, but it 
has been repudiated by postwar presidents and Congress has voted to 
compensate those interned. 
</P>
<P>
	The monument also will memorialize Japanese-Americans who served  
in the U.S. military. 
</P>
<P>
	``The design ... provides an appropriate form for conveying the  
memorial's story and message,'' the staff evaluation said. 
</P>
<P>
	The capital's Fine Arts Commission already has approved the  
design. But it had reservations about the number of inscriptions to 
be placed on the 7-foot granite wall that will surround the central 
monument. 
</P>
<P>
	A memorial to Mahatma Gandhi, who inspired India's nonviolent  
resistance to British rule, also won approval from the commission 
staff. It will consist of a statue in a small park facing the 
Indian Embassy on Massachusetts Avenue, the capital's ``Embassy 
Row.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
