<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nine West To Eliminate 1,900 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jones Apparel Group Inc. will eliminate about  
1,900 jobs and close three factories as it looks to reduce costs in 
its newly acquired Nine West footwear and accessories division. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, which designs and markets apparel under well-known labels  
such as Jones New York, Saville and Evan-Picone labels, bought Nine 
West in June in a $1.5 billion deal that created one of the biggest 
clothing and shoe companies in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said Tuesday that it would close Nine West factories in  
Kentucky, Indiana, and the Dominican Republic. Like Jones does with 
its clothing lines, it will contract out production of its shoes to 
outside manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Jones will close Nine West's administrative office  
in St. Louis and will merge those operations into Jones' 
headquarters in Bristol, Pa., and Nine West's headquarters in White 
Plains, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	About 550 employees in the United States and 1,170 in the  
Dominican Republic will be affected as a result of the factory 
closings. About 190 jobs will be cut when the St. Louis office 
closes. 
</P>
<P>
	The layoffs represent about 12 percent of Nine West's total  
workforce of 15,600 people. Jones Apparel employs an additional 
9,000 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The closings are expected to be completed by the end of this  
year. Beginning in 2000, Jones expects to save about $7 million 
annually. 
</P>
<P>
	``These were difficult decisions, however, as we integrate the  
Jones and Nine West businesses into today's globally competitive 
women's apparel and footwear markets, it is imperative that we 
maximize worldwide sourcing capabilities and reduce costs,'' the 
company said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange, Jones slipped  
1.5 percent, or by 50 cents, to $32.93 3/4 a share. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
