<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 19:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Basks in Welfare Successes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- President Clinton basked in the testimonials of  
businesses and former welfare recipients who are helping the 
welfare rolls plummet. But many of their stories offered reminders 
of the problems that remain in trying to make welfare reform 
succeed. 
</P>
<P>
	``As pleased as we are, we have to do more,'' the president told  
participants in a national conference Tuesday of the Welfare to 
Work Partnership, a group Clinton helped launch in the months after 
he signed the 1996 overhaul. 
</P>
<P>
	The president said he was particularly concerned that people  
leaving welfare may be improperly losing their Medicaid and food 
stamp benefits. He guessed that they simply don't realize they 
remain eligible. ``We have to work on that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But most of Tuesday's session with some 350 business leaders and  
former welfare recipients was decidedly upbeat. 
</P>
<P>
	``It takes people with the courage to say, 'I'm going to change  
my life,''' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton announced that a record number of welfare recipients are  
now working even as they collect benefits, and released new figures 
showing the percent of Americans on assistance at a 32-year low. 
Experts credit a combination of tough new rules and the strong 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The president listened as much he talked, rotating his chair to  
hear one hand-picked person after another speak under the bright 
lights of what resembled a TV talk-show set. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I can go out and conquer just about anything,''  
said Consuelo McGlond, who was hired last November as an overnight 
telephone operator at a Loews hotel in Miami after 10 years on and 
off welfare. ``It has given me loads of confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since the welfare overhaul became law nearly three years ago,  
Clinton has constantly urged businesses to hire people off the 
rolls, hoping to prove wrong those critics who said there would 
never been enough jobs for the millions of families on assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	The Welfare to Work Partnership has held rallies in 17 cities  
around the country and persuaded some 12,000 companies to join, 
each pledging to hire at least one person off the rolls. 
</P>
<P>
	Its pitch has been that hiring people from welfare is good for  
businesses that need workers in an economy with low unemployment. 
And many employers -- including the federal government -- have found 
that retention rates are higher among former recipients. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton sounded the same theme Tuesday: ``Welfare recipients can  
be a rich pool of untapped talent, people who are good for the 
bottom line,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's unclear how many of the partnership's businesses have  
actually hired people, but there has been an injection of positive 
thinking about welfare among many of the country's largest 
companies. Rather than shunning people on welfare, they are 
bragging about their programs to hire them. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to put ourselves in the shoes of a welfare recipient  
moving to work,'' said Bill McDermott, who proudly reported that 
his company, Xerox, was one of the first 100 to sign up. So far, he 
said, Xerox has hired 400 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, many of the success stories pointed to remaining  
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	UPS, for instance, worked with the city of Philadelphia to  
extend bus routes out to its remote facility. But many suburban 
jobs around the country remain out of reach for people who live in 
the inner cities and often do not own cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Delaware Gov. Tom Carper told of his state's effort to get the  
fathers of children on welfare to work, but there are still many 
dads who earn very little and are not able to pay child support. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton acknowledged as much.  
</P>
<P>
	``We know there are problems out there,'' he said. ``But we also  
know that there are good people who wish to go to work and ought to 
have the chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before leaving Chicago, Clinton met for 45 minutes with AFL-CIO  
President John Sweeney and the labor federation's executive 
council. They discussed the federal budget, Medicare, a minimum 
wage increase and next year's election, said White House spokesman 
Barry Toiv. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
