<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kings Re-Sign Barry, Pollard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The Sacramento Kings re-signed guard  
Jon Barry and forward-center Scot Pollard to multiyear contracts on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kings vice president Geoff Petrie said both had been ``very  
important players for us during our playoff run last season and 
will be key members of our team as we look to the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barry got a three-year contract and Pollard signed for two  
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry, 30, has averaged 4.4 points, 1.4 rebounds and 1.8 assists  
in his seven-year NBA career. In 43 games last season, he averaged 
five points, a career-high 2.2 rebounds, a career-high 2.6 assists, 
1.23 steals, in 17.1 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've played in the league for seven years, and I can honestly  
say this is the most fun I've had,'' Barry said. 
</P>
<P>
	He praised management for ``keeping a team together that did a  
great job last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First signed as a free agent by the Kings midway through last  
season, the 6-foot-11, 265-pound Pollard averaged 5.1 points, 5.1 
rebounds 1.13 blocks, and 16.2 minutes in 16 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollard, 24, who was drafted by Detroit out of Kansas with the  
19th overall pick in the 1997 NBA draft, started five games for 
injured Chris Webber during the Kings' drive for the playoffs. He 
averaged 11.2 points, and 9 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollard acknowledged that he'd received ``a couple offers that  
were attractive,'' but added that he didn't want to leave 
Sacramento. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great place to live. It's a great place to play.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
