<DOCNO> APW19990803.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vehicle Sales Robust Again in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- July was another strong month for U.S. sales of  
cars and light trucks, as consumers took advantage of deep summer 
discounts and kept the industry on pace to break its 13-year-old 
annual sales record. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reports of the death of the sales boom are exaggerated,''  
analyst David Healy of Burnham Securities Inc. declared Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	With most major automakers' July reports in, total industry  
sales were up about 21 percent compared with July 1998. But the 
comparison was skewed by the United Auto Workers strikes that all 
but halted North American production at General Motors Corp. last 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Not surprisingly, GM posted the biggest percentage gain -- up 63  
percent. But the biggest automaker still managed to carve out only 
28 percent of the U.S. market, significantly below its target for 
the year of more than 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	That troubled Wall Street analysts because GM added more  
discounts last month in an effort to boost its share. Much of this 
extended boom in sales is due to heavy spending by automakers on 
rebates, discount leases and finance rates that have caused 
transaction prices on some models to fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``GM is not putting enough money on the table to get to their 30  
percent market share target,'' said David Garrity of Dresdner 
Kleinwort Benson. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler AG did especially well, with sales up 10 percent  
on robust demand for its Jeep and Dodge sport utility vehicles and 
Dodge Ram pickups. Most Asian and European automakers also had 
impressive gains. 
</P>
<P>
	No. 2 Ford Motor Co. posted only a 1 percent increase on the  
strength of a 10 percent improvement in car sales, excluding Jaguar 
and Volvo. Its truck sales were off 4 percent from a year ago -- its 
first decline in that category after 14 consecutive months of 
record year-over-year increases. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford blamed the strikes for an unusual 13 percent drop in sales  
of the F-series line of pickups, the nation's best-selling vehicle. 
Ford says it had record F-series sales in July 1998 because the 
strikes, combined with retooling to produce redesigned '99 models, 
severely depleted GM pickup inventories. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year we pretty much were the fox in the chicken coop,''  
Ford spokesman George Pipas said. ``The availability of GM trucks 
last year, particularly their full-size pickups, was not at full 
strength. I would not be surprised to see lower F-series sales in 
August as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Ford's truck numbers in general were a little soft,'' Healy  
said. ``I think it's primarily that they feasted off GM last year 
to a degree. But there's also not a lot new in the Ford truck line 
versus a year ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's big SUVs, the Expedition and Lincoln Navigator, also were  
down last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The first 118 Ford Excursion SUVs, the largest passenger truck  
on the market, were sold last month. Sales of the 2000 model are 
expected to become more of a factor as production is ramped up. 
</P>
<P>
	GM said it had its best July ever for SUVs and trucks overall.  
Its retail sales numbers, which exclude purchases by business and 
government fleets, were at their highest July level in a decade. 
Despite that, competitors claimed more of the increase in industry 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's redesigned full-size SUVs, led by the Chevrolet  
Suburban, hold the promise to significantly boost GM's share and 
profits. But production of those 2000 models is not expected to hit 
full speed until the fourth quarter, Garrity said. 
</P>
<P>
	At DaimlerChrysler, excluding Mercedes-Benz, car sales were off  
15 percent, but were more than offset by a 20 percent increase in 
truck sales. Jeep Grand Cherokee sales increased 62 percent, while 
the Ram pickup set an all-time monthly record with sales up 29 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Asian automakers shared in the buying frenzy, too.  
</P>
<P>
	Toyota Motor Corp. and Honda Motor Co. also posted their  
second-best U.S. sales months. Toyota's sales improved 14 percent, 
with a 13 percent gain in sales of the best-selling Camry sedan 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan Motor Co.'s U.S. rebound continued, with the automaker  
reporting an 8 percent sales increase boosted by healthy demand for 
its pickups and SUVs, including its new Xterra SUV. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda's sales also were up 8 percent, with strong demand for its  
redesigned Odyssey minivan and a 14 percent improvement in Accord 
sedan sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Barring another strike or economic catastrophe, the industry is  
expected to easily surpass the 1986 sales record of about 16.1 
million vehicles set in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time to start rewriting the record books,'' said Dick  
Colliver, executive vice president of American Honda Motor Co. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
