<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Plan To Buy ABS Global Disclosed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEFOREST, Wis. (AP) -- Britain's leading producer of cattle semen  
announced plans Tuesday to buy a Wisconsin biotechnology company 
that gained national attention for successfully cloning a calf. 
</P>
<P>
	Genus PLC of Crewe, England will buy ABS Global from Protein  
Genetics for an undisclosed price. The purchase includes ABS 
headquarters in DeForest, offices in England and facilities in 
Brazil and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale does not include Infigen, the research division that  
cloned a black-and-white Holstein calf named Gene. Infigen was spun 
off following the calf cloning in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	ABS Global spokesman Joseph Thompson said the company had been  
pursuing a merger, sale or purchase for several years to improve 
its competitive position. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an industry that's sorely in need of consolidation,''  
Thompson said. ``Right now, there's just a huge oversupply of 
product out there -- it's very hard to make a profit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ABS acquisition is expected to elevate Genus's  
cattle-breeding operations to worldwide status and give it a 
world-class genetics operation. 
</P>
<P>
	ABS ``is recognized by dairy and beef producers all around the  
world for a consistently high quality product lineup and for its 
technological and marketing innovations,'' said Genus chief 
executive Richard Wood. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson said no changes were expected in the location of ABS  
headquarters, its name or employment levels in Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Protein Genetics Inc. bought ABS in 1994 for $39 million.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
