<DOCNO> APW19990803.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 00:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cheever Contrite After Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOVER, Del. (AP) -- Aside from saying he's sorry, there isn't  
much Eddie Cheever can do to make amends for the darkest moment of 
his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, all he can do is wait to see how the Indy Racing League  
will deal with his attack on rookie Scott Harrington. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheever, angry and frustrated, set out to simply speak to  
Harrington. He wound up manhandling him. A day after the 
confrontation at Dover Downs International Speedway, Cheever was 
filled with regret. 
</P>
<P>
	``My actions were inexcusable,'' he said Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 Indianapolis 500 champion walked down pit road after  
the Indy Racing League's MBNA Mid-Atlantic 200 to where Harrington 
was seated. Profanities were exchanged, and Cheever admits he 
grabbed Harrington by his racing uniform and lifted him. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington did not accuse Cheever of going for his throat, but  
said his hands wound up there. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've still got scratches on my neck,'' Harrington, the IRL's  
rookie points leader, said by phone from Pennsylvania, where he was 
attending a picnic for sponsor CertainTeed. 
</P>
<P>
	IRL spokesman Ron Green said Cheever's postrace conduct was  
being scrutinized, and the league might soon have a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheever said he wouldn't be surprised by a fine.  
</P>
<P>
	``I am profoundly embarrassed by what I did,'' he said from  
Indianapolis, where he will compete Friday in the closing event of 
the International Race of Champions series. ``In 25 years of 
racing, I've never had words with anybody that got past the point 
of a discussion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington conceded that some drivers complained to the IRL  
about his tactics, which he said were being misinterpreted as 
blocking. He also said the league mentioned to him that he was 
shown a blue flag, which he accepted as information the leaders 
were approaching from behind rather than a signal to move over. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was set up to run on the bottom of the track, and I  
maintained my line throughout the race,'' he said. ``Behind them 
were some cars I was racing for position, and the leaders could go 
around me on the high side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although he criticized Cheever for ``unprofessional conduct''  
for his actions after the race, Harrington insists he bears no 
animosity. He says he is sorry if anyone thought he was blocking, 
and he could have misunderstood the flag. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to put it behind me and get on to the next race,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington, 17th in the points standings, is recovering from  
injuries to both legs from a crash during practice nearly two 
months ago in Fort Worth, Texas. He must use crutches or a cane. 
</P>
<P>
	After taking his Infiniti-powered Dallara from the 19th starting  
position to eighth in just 56 of 200 laps, Cheever crashed. He was 
tapped in the rear by rookie John Hollansworth as Cheever and the 
cars immediately in front of him, including Harrington's, slowed in 
heavy traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheever, who also owns his car, had an accident with Sunday's  
race winner, Greg Ray, a year earlier in the same spot. Robby 
Unser, then driving for Team Cheever, also wrecked in 1998. Cheever 
said that trip to Dover Downs cost him $800,000 of the $1.4 million 
he earned for winning the Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident Sunday relegated Cheever to a 21st-place finish. He  
dropped a spot to seventh in the standings. 
</P>
<P>
	As Cheever was walking toward Harrington, Unser decided to join  
him. Witnesses said others in the area stepped in to end the 
discord and quoted Unser as telling Harrington: ``It isn't over 
yet. This is just the beginning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Unser nor representatives of his Team Pelfrey in  
Indianapolis responded Monday to a voice-mail message. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
