<DOCNO> APW19990803.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 08:36:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Khmer Rouge Trial To Be Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- Lawmakers from Cambodia's top two  
political parties agreed Tuesday on legislation that will allow a 
three-year delay of a genocide tribunal for Khmer Rouge leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Senior legislators from Prime Minister Hun Sen's ruling party  
and junior coalition partner FUNCINPEC said after a meeting that 
both sides support a draft law that will avoid a Sept. 9 deadline 
on a trial for jailed guerrilla chief Ta Mok. 
</P>
<P>
	Approval of the bill is almost assured as the two parties  
control all but 15 seats in the 122-seat assembly. A simple 
majority is needed for passage. 
</P>
<P>
	``The objective of the draft law is to seek justice for all  
victims of the genocide regime,'' FUNCINPEC member Monh Saphan said 
of the 1975-79 Khmer Rouge government, when an estimated 1.7 
million people died of starvation, overwork, disease or systematic 
executions. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition politicians and human rights groups have bitterly  
opposed the measure, fearing the law could be used to lock up Hun 
Sen's political opponents without trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Ta Mok, one of two Khmer Rouge arrested for their role in the  
genocide, was captured by the Cambodian army on March 6 and charged 
three days later under legislation that outlawed the guerrilla 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	The charge was seen as a holding tactic while Cambodia and the  
United Nations negotiated formation of a genocide tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	But the talks have proceeded slowly, and under Cambodian law a  
suspect must face trial within six months of being charged. 
</P>
<P>
	Hun Sen called Saturday for the legislature to support an  
amendment proposed by his party that would allow a pretrial 
detention period of up to five years if a suspect is charged with 
genocide, war crimes or crimes against humanity. 
</P>
<P>
	FUNCINPEC, led by assembly speaker Prince Norodom Ranariddh,  
initially balked, but then submitted a counterproposal Tuesday: an 
entirely new law that shortens the deadline for holding a trial to 
three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruling party lawmakers approved the bill, which Monh Saphan said  
should reach the full assembly next week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 21:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Republicans Agree on $792B Tax Cut  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After shuttling in and out of bargaining  
sessions for two days, Republicans reached general agreement 
Tuesday night on a $792 billion plan to cut personal income tax 
rates and provide relief from the marriage penalty. Senate Majority 
Leader Trent Lott said, ``The deed is done,'' however, the measure 
is expected to trigger a veto showdown with the White House, which 
says the bill would shortchange Social Security and Medicare and 
lead to deep spending cuts in other domestic programs including 
education and health care. GOP officials, speaking on condition of 
anonymity, said the proposal calls for a gradual cut of 1 
percentage point in each personal income tax rate. 

</P>
<P>
	Flight Delayed Over Security Threat  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Federal agents delayed the takeoff of a 6 p.m.  
Delta Air Lines flight to Turkey on Tuesday for four hours after 
receiving word that one of the passengers may have been a security 
threat. All of the passengers on the direct flight to Istanbul were 
asked to get off the plane as a security sweep was conducted. 
Passengers were asked to identify their luggage, which had been 
removed from the plane. Seven passengers were questioned, and one 
man detained. The FBI had received information about the man 
earlier in the day as ``a potential threat to national security.'' 
The man was not under arrest, but not free to go. 

</P>
<P>
	Gunshot Injuries Cost $2.3B Per Year  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A new study found the cost of treating the  
nation's gunshot victims in a recent year was $2.3 billion -- with 
the government footing half the bill. The $2.3 billion figure is an 
estimate of what the nation spent treating gunshot victims in 1994, 
based on data from hospitals in Maryland and New York that year, 
from South Carolina emergency rooms in 1997 and other sources. The 
average cost per injury was $17,000. When a victim was 
hospitalized, the average lifetime cost jumped to $35,000, the 
researchers estimated. This has not been lost on many cities and 
counties -- at least 23 are pursuing gun makers in court to recover 
money spent treating gunshot victims. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav Media Campaign Intensifies  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The speaker of Serbia's parliament  
accused NATO Tuesday of being behind opposition street protests as 
state-run Yugoslav media and senior government officials 
intensified their campaign against the opposition, accusing the 
West of trying to put President Slobodan Milosevic's opponents in 
power. Dragan Tomic said the Western alliance was ``still trying to 
conquer the Serb people'' by demanding democratic changes in Serbia 
and trying to provoke unrest. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Gives $55M in Relief  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- In the wake of a nationwide heat wave, President  
Clinton gave low income people in nine states some relief Tuesday, 
offering $55 million to help them pay electricity bills or buy 
cooling equipment. He said he hoped the money would help encourage 
older people to run air conditioners without fear of high utility 
bills. Since July 19, the midsummer heat wave has killed at least 
256, including 119 in Illinois. Joined by Mayor Richard Daley, 
Clinton thanked city workers in Chicago for helping to protect 
people from the heat. 

</P>
<P>
	Sunscreens May Increase Cancer Risk  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- People using stronger sunscreens increase  
their risk of skin cancer because they don't feel the effects of 
sunburn as quickly and spend more time outside, according to 
findings of a study being published Wednesday in the Journal of the 
National Cancer Institute. European researchers concluded that 
``sunscreens may encourage prolonged sun exposure because they 
delay sunburn,'' results they said help explain previous studies 
linking sunscreen use with higher skin cancer rates. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices dropped Wednesday morning mainly  
on selling of export-oriented blue chips. The benchmark 225-issue 
Nikkei Stock Average shed 225.91 points, or 1.26 percent, to finish 
the morning session at 17,744.02. In New York, the Dow was up 31.35 
to 10,677.31. 

</P>
<P>
	Mets Beat Brewers 10-3  
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Robin Ventura went 4-for-4 with a homer and  
three RBIs Tuesday night as the New York Mets regained sole 
possession of first place in the NL East with a 10-3 victory over 
the Milwaukee Brewers. The Mets, 15-4 since the All-Star break, 
moved a game in front of the Atlanta Braves, who lost to Pittsburgh 
7-1. Orel Hershiser (11-8) allowed three runs in 7 1-3 innings and 
Mike Piazza hit a three-run homer and drove in four runs for New 
York. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
