<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DuBose Family Wants Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- The family of a former Tampa Bay Buccaneers  
linebacker who was killed by police officers has initiated an 
independent autopsy and investigation into the shooting after 
witnesses indicated the athlete may have been shot in the back. 
</P>
<P>
	Demetrius DuBose, 28, was shot several times by police officers  
July 24 after he allegedly charged at officers with nunchakus, a 
martial arts weapon that he took away from an officer, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	But preliminary findings of the family's investigation show  
DuBose was initially calm and cooperated with officers' 
investigation of a burglary call until they began to ``intimidate 
and harass'' him, likely because he was black, said H.J. Sims of 
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People in 
San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the police first arrived the gentleman was patient for  
about five to 10 minutes,'' Sims said Monday. ``It was only after 
they tried to place him in handcuffs that the unprofessionalism of 
police allowed the situation to escalate and prompted the gentleman 
to run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego City Councilmen George Stevens and Byron Wear are  
calling for a thorough investigation into the shooting to allay any 
concerns that it was unjustified. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose had been arrested three times in the past year.  
</P>
<P>
	The latest was June 14, when California Highway Patrol officers  
found DuBose ``very dazed, very confused'' in his car parked on the 
side of a highway near Mammoth Lakes, said Mono County prosecutor 
Tim Kendall. 
</P>
<P>
	After conducting field sobriety tests and observing ``white  
powdery substance dripping from his nose,'' officers determined he 
was under the influence of PCP, Kendall said. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose became increasingly agitated as the investigation went  
on, but officers were able to get him handcuffed, Kendall said. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose also was reportedly under the influence of an unknown  
drug Feb. 3, when he allegedly forced his way into a Mammoth Lakes 
restaurant after being denied entrance several times, Kendall said. 
</P>
<P>
	In August 1998, DuBose was arrested in South Bend, Ind., after  
he became belligerent at a nightclub. When an off-duty police 
officer ordered him to leave, DuBose allegedly grabbed a pipe from 
an overhead sprinkler system -- flooding the club with some 1,600 
gallons of water. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens noted some people have said 6-foot-2-DuBose was bending  
over when the accident happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``Others have said he was turning away. I would hope the autopsy  
would show where the first shot entered,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego police Chief David Bejarano said he welcomes outside  
input and expects an internal investigation to be completed within 
two weeks. Results, which will include toxicology results, will be 
turned over to the district attorney's office, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers claim DuBose resisted officers' attempts to question  
him and appeared to be under the influence of alcohol or other 
drugs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 21:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinals Place Bragg on DL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- St. Louis Cardinals outfielder Darren Bragg was  
placed on the 15-day disabled list Tuesday with a torn ligament in 
his right knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Bragg, injured trying to avoid a collision with J.D. Drew,  
likely is out for the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know there's a problem there, and they're discussing the  
next move,'' manager Tony La Russa said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals called up utility player Craig Paquette, acquired  
on the trade deadline from the New York Mets, from Triple-A 
Memphis. Paquette, who played for La Russa in Oakland from 1993-95, 
went 2-for-4 with a homer, double and three RBIs in his debut. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got a lot of defensive ability and he's got a nice  
swing,'' La Russa said. ``If he connects, he's got extra-base 
pop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paquette was overjoyed about the trade, which sent Shawon  
Dunston to the Mets. He said he was New York's insurance policy in 
case third baseman Robin Ventura or first baseman John Olerud got 
hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at their careers, how many things have happened to  
them?'' Paquette said. ``Ventura's been on the DL once and Olerud's 
never been on the DL, so there wasn't much opportunity there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paquette, who can play first, third and the outfield, had been  
playing for the U.S. team in the Pan American Games. He has a 
career .232 average in six major league seasons with 55 homers and 
195 RBIs in 426 games, and was batting .272 with 15 homers and 54 
RBIs in 70 games for Triple-A Norfolk. 
</P>
<P>
	Another injured Cardinals player, outfielder Eric Davis,  
attempted to swing off a tee after taking two days off with 
soreness. Davis has been on the disabled list since June 30 with a 
partially torn rotator cuff. 
</P>
<P>
	He was injured making a diving catch to help save teammate Jose  
Jimenez's no-hitter June 25. Davis took about 20 swings on 
consecutive days Friday and Saturday then had to shut it down. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't get frustrated,'' Davis said. ``I'm disappointed.''  
</P>
<P>
	Davis, batting .257 with five homer and 30 RBIs in 58 games,  
expects to make a decision on the rest of the season soon. 
Rehabbing hasn't been very effective thus far. Two-and-a-half weeks 
ago, he had zero range of motion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Either we're going to have to get it taken care of or rehab it  
and just decide to play,'' Davis said. ``I haven't given up on this 
one. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to play, I need to play, this team needs me to play.  
It's what I came here for.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 01:30:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Boast of Exposing Tax Cheats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Federal officials say they have finally  
breached the secrecy surrounding banks in the Cayman Islands with 
the help of a former banker whose records exposed hundreds of U.S. 
citizens as tax cheats. 
</P>
<P>
	The one-time banker, John M. Mathewson, 71, was sentenced Monday  
to probation on federal conspiracy and money laundering charges 
after prosecutors credited him for providing an unprecedented look 
at how Cayman banks operate. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. authorities said the case shows that the approximately 500  
banks in the British colony exist only to serve as illegal tax 
shelters for a mainly American clientele. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Cayman Islands are no longer the safe haven they once  
were,'' said a ranking FBI agent, Robert Jordan. ``This case 
enabled us to get on the inside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because of Mathewson's help, the U.S. government has recouped  
$50 million in back taxes and penalties, and can expect to get a 
total of $300 million, according to the former banker's lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities did not confirm those figures, but Jordan said the  
FBI and the Internal Revenue Service are pursuing 1,500 potential 
cases around the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Although other countries, such as Switzerland, offer tax haven  
accounts, the Caymans and other Caribbean locations are favored by 
U.S. citizens because they are close. The Cayman Islands are 290 
miles south of Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. citizens who maintain bank accounts in offshore tax havens  
must report the accounts to the IRS and pay U.S. taxes on income 
received from them. Bank secrecy laws in the Cayman Islands and 
other British colonies are under fire from London, which in March 
insisted they be scrapped. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities stumbled on the Caymans case by accident while  
pursuing a nationwide investigation into a cable piracy operation, 
according to court papers. 
</P>
<P>
	When FBI agents arrested Mathewson in San Antonio in 1996, they  
found over a year's worth of computer records from the now-defunct 
Guardian Bank &AMP; Trust Limited of Grand Cayman. 
</P>
<P>
	Mathewson, the bank's owner, immediately offered the records,  
leading to a continuing investigation that has so far brought cases 
in about 20 states, Assistant U.S. Attorney John Carney said in 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank had about 2,000 depositors, and Mathewson dealt  
personally with each and prepared fake documents for shell 
corporations, invoices and other items to help conceal the true 
account holder and the extent of their business, said Paul 
Machalek, chief criminal investigator for the IRS in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Many depositors had legitimate income, including New Jersey  
businessman Mark Vicini, who pleaded guilty to concealing millions 
in Guardian, and Jeffrey Lavigne, a surgeon who treated hemorrhoids 
and advertised on New York City subways as ``M.D. Tush.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mathewson pleaded guilty in March 1997 to charges that included  
conspiracy, money laundering and aiding income tax evasions as part 
of plea bargains with federal prosecutors in Florida, New Jersey 
and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Carney urged U.S. District Judge Alfred J. Lechner to give  
Mathewson a lenient sentence to acknowledge his cooperation, which 
included testifying to grand juries and obtaining computer software 
to decode bank computer tapes, which were encrypted. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying his cooperation ``has been unparalleled,'' Lechner  
sentenced Mathewson to five years' probation, with six months to be 
served under house arrest, a $30,000 fine and 500 hours of 
community service. He could have faced nearly five years in prison. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 10:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mostly Up; Gold Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar rose against most other major  
currencies in European trading Tuesday. Gold prices also were 
higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0648, in late European trading, down  
from $1.0660 Monday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the euro 
traded at 1.0694. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday,  
included 115.20 Japanese yen, up from 114.35; 1.5006 Swiss francs, 
up from 1.4970; 1.4962 Canadian dollars, down from 1.5118. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6161, up from $1.6158.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 115.06 yen, and  
the pound was worth $1.6215. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8368 German marks, up from 1.8347; 
6.1604 French francs, up from 6.1534; 2.0696 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0673; 1,818.44 Italian lire, up from 1,816.39. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $255.90 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$254.30 on Monday. In Zurich the bid price was $255.95, up from 
$254.35. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold rose $0.60 in Hong Kong to close at $255.85.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.44 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.36. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
