<DOCNO> APW19990803.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 15:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Newest Jaguar Faces Big Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- By now, Lonnie Marts is well aware of  
how the business side of the NFL works. 
</P>
<P>
	But the newest member of the Jacksonville Jaguars has two kids  
and a pregnant wife who are having a difficult time dealing with 
all the changes. 
</P>
<P>
	In a series of moves that seems to define pro sports these days,  
the journeyman linebacker was released by the Tennessee Titans last 
Wednesday and signed by the Jaguars on Saturday. They were two 
little-noticed transactions that had a profound effect on four, 
soon to be five, lives. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you ever get used to it,'' said Marts, a  
nine-year veteran with his fourth team. ``My wife is pregnant, my 
kids are supposed to start school and I'm getting ready to go to 
camp and fight for a job. All of the sudden, I'm released. It's 
kind of a cutthroat business. But this sport throws curve balls at 
you, and you adjust on the run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marts' release from the Titans had the economics side of pro  
football written all over it. Tennessee needed to free money to 
sign its first-round draft pick, linebacker Jevon Kearse, and 
free-agent quarterback Neil O'Donnell. They parted with a 
mid-priced linebacker and hoped to re-sign him for less money. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacksonville stepped in with an offer after Bryce Paup went down  
with an injury, leaving the Jaguars too young and thin at the 
position for coach Tom Coughlin to stomach. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lonnie Marts gains people's attention, lets everyone know  
we're very serious about making sure we have quality players at 
that spot,'' Coughlin said. ``There's competition there and 
wherever you have competition, you're going to have a good camp.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marts will make good money -- up to $1.1 million if all his  
incentives kick in -- but that won't make the emotional side of the 
move any easier on his growing family. 
</P>
<P>
	His daughter is 6 years old, his son is 3 and his wife is six  
months' pregnant. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough, because the Jaguars called and I had to make a  
decision within two hours or so,'' Marts said. ``Then, you've got 
to explain to the children that we've got to move. We won't see our 
friends anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Marts, the Jaguars get a versatile player who has experience  
at all three linebacker positions. He started 15 games last season, 
made a career-high 85 tackles and led Tennessee's anemic pass rush 
with four sacks. 
</P>
<P>
	His presence lets Jacksonville move Joel Smeenge back to his  
natural line position. It also gives the team the flexibility of 
moving Paup, once he's healthy, onto the line in certain situations 
and sticking Marts behind him at linebacker. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a guy we've been very pleased with in the couple of  
practices we've had,'' Coughlin said. ``By the time this thing is 
over, we'll be very happy we have Lonnie Marts in our program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marts hopes the move will be just as beneficial to him. He says  
the Jaguars give him something he hasn't had since his first years 
in Kansas City: good structure and a chance to win a Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a long time since I've been with a quality  
organization,'' Marts said. ``Everybody here is in sync. Any player 
who is out of shape or doesn't care about winning isn't allowed on 
the field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He wasn't thrilled with his situation in Tennessee, which made  
coming to Jacksonville a choice he couldn't refuse. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, Tennessee was in disarray,'' Marts said. ``To go from  
Tennessee to Jacksonville overnight is a big change right away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In more than one way.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 08:10:25 </DATE_TIME>
