<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Leading Economic Indicators Rise  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A widely-watched indicator of future economic  
activity rose 0.3 points in June, chalking up gains in eight out of 
the past nine months and signaling that the U.S. economy could be 
in its longest expansion ever. The Conference Board, a private New 
York-based economic research group, reported today that its index 
of leading indicators stood at 107.7 in June, up from 107.4 in May. 
The index also rose by the same amount in May. The last decline, in 
April, was 0.1. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 2.21; Nasdaq Down 28.97  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved lower today after a higher opening.  
Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 
2.21 at 10,643.75. Broader stock indicators were also lower. The 
Nasdaq composite index was down 28.97 at 2,594.66. A report that 
ExciteAtHome may be acquired by Yahoo! for a price greater than 
ExciteAtHome's $17 billion market value stimulated some buying in 
Internet and telecommunications companies. ExciteAtHome rose 4 
41/64 to 47 37/64, while Yahoo! slipped 9/16 to 131 3/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- financial figures just before 11 a.m. EDT:  
Dow Industrials:        10643.75  -  2.21
NYSE Issues:         Advances  988  Declines 1435  Unchgd  601
NYSE Volume:         149,781,910
Most Active NYSE issue:         America Online 90 3/8   - 2 1/2
S&AMP;P 500:         1322.05  - 6.00
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          785.69  + 2.05
Nasdaq Composite Index:       2594.66  - 28.97
Gold(final) -    $257.30    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.

</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! May Buy Excite/AtHome  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Excite/AtHome may be on the market. BusinessWeek  
Online reports the company has held preliminary talks with Yahoo! 
over the past six weeks. The report cites sources who say they've 
been discussing a deal in which Yahoo! would pay an amount far 
greater than Excite/AtHome's current market value of $17 billion. 
But the sources say the talks are preliminary, and that much work 
remains to be done. 

</P>
<P>
	Mazda Sells Loan Subsidiary to Ford  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's Mazda Motor Corp. will sell its credit arm  
to Ford Motor Co.'s finance subsidiary for 8 billion yen, or $69 
million, Mazda said today. The deal, to be completed by the end of 
August, will make Mazda Credit Corp. a subsidiary of Ford Motor 
Credit Co., the world's largest auto finance firm. Mazda Credit 
provides loans for people who buy Mazda cars. The company has 
annual sales of about $87 million. Ford owns 33.4 percent of 
Hiroshima-based Mazda. 

</P>
<P>
	Jones Apparel To Cut 1,900 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jones Apparel Group Inc. will slash about 1,900  
jobs and close three factories in an attempt to reduce costs as it 
integrates leading footwear maker Nine West into its business. 
Jones, which is best known for its Jones New York, Saville and 
Evan-Picone labels, bought Nine West in June in a $1.5 billion deal 
that created one of the biggest clothing and shoe manufacturers in 
the country. Jones said today that it would close Nine West 
factories in Kentucky, Indiana, and the Dominican Republic. In 
addition, Jones will close Nine West's administrative office in St. 
Louis and will merge those operations into Jones' headquarters in 
Bristol, Pa., and Nine West's headquarters in White Plains, N.Y. 

</P>
<P>
	St. Paul Cos. To Cut 1,000 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- The St. Paul Cos. plans to cut about  
1,000 jobs as part of an effort to reduce expenses by $100 million 
next year in the highly competitive insurance industry. Most of the 
cuts will be identified in the third quarter and will be completed 
by the end of this year, the company announced today. The St. Paul 
expects to take a related charge in the third quarter of 1999. The 
company will provide severance pay for affected employees and will 
help them find other jobs, he said. The new layoffs are separate 
from actions associated with the company's pending sale of its 
personal insurance operations to MetLife Auto and Home. 

</P>
<P>
	President of Money Store Resigns  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Bill Templeton, president and chief  
executive of The Money Store consumer finance unit of First Union 
Corp., has resigned. First Union bought the consumer finance 
company last year for $2.1 billion. The unit hasn't added to 
earnings as the bank promised when the purchase was made and First 
Union has laid off hundreds of Money Store employees this year in 
companywide job cuts. First Union said yesterday that Money Store 
accounting changes would lower bank earnings this year by 8 cents 
to 12 cents a share. 

</P>
<P>
	KLM Profit Slides 64 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Profits at the Dutch flag carrier  
KLM tumbled 64 percent in its first fiscal quarter, excluding a 
one-time gain, a decline the company blamed on an overall slowdown 
in the global airline industry. Without the one-time gain of $433.8 
million on the sale of its stake in Galileo International, a global 
airline ticketing company, KLM earned $37.2 million compared to 
$102.4 million in the same period a year ago. 

</P>
<P>
	Asian Stock Markets Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed higher today,  
with the key index rising in Tokyo after two straight sessions of 
declines. The Japanese 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 144.23 
points, or 0.81 percent, to close at 17,969.93. The Jakarta Stock 
Exchange's Composite Index surged 22.473 points, or 3.8 percent, to 
618.986. In Taipei, the main index plunged more than 3 percent 
before buying by government funds erased most of the losses. The 
Taiwan market's key Weighted Stock Price Index slipped 20.75 
points, or 0.3 percent, to 7,175.19. Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index 
rose 38.41 points, or 0.3 percent, to close at 13,473.84. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Leading economic indicators: up 0.3 points  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Factory orders  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Jobless claims  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Productivity  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Unemployment  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Consumer credit  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
