<DOCNO> APW19990803.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 08:36:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Storm Kills At Least 35 in S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Gales uprooted trees and flipped cars  
on a tourist island in South Korea today after three days of 
flooding farther north in the country left at least 35 people dead 
and 22 missing. 
</P>
<P>
	Floodwaters also inundated thousands of homes in the  
Philippines, where reservoirs in Manila spilled over today. One 
Manila suburb, Malabon, was 90 percent flooded, with water rising 
to shoulder-level in some parts, said city spokesman Abbi Balatbat. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivers swelled and rice fields became lakes amid persistent rain  
in parts of Asia, forcing people to flee low-lying areas, postpone 
air travel and escape from flooded homes carrying their 
possessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's new storm in the Yellow Sea dumped 9 inches of rain and  
blew with 67 mph winds as it skirted South Korea's southern and 
western coasts. It was a setback to rescue workers who have 
struggled to feed and shelter thousands left homeless by heavy 
rains north of Seoul. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the weekend, floods have forced tens of thousands to flee  
towns and villages between the South Korean capital and the border 
with North Korea, 35 miles away. A total 35 people have been 
killed, officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of tourists were stranded on the resort island of  
Cheju, south of the Korean peninsula, after four domestic airliners 
hastily flew to Seoul early today to avoid damage, and hundreds of 
homes on the island were flooded when today's rains hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the new storm, things are going from bad to worse,''  
South Korean President Kim Dae-jung said at a Cabinet meeting, 
according to a transcript of his remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	In a flooded area of Choonchun city, about 95 miles northeast of  
Seoul, a tour bus slid off a rain-slick road into a river, killing 
five people and injuring 31, rescue workers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm hit land on North Korea late today, South Korean  
weather officials said. North Korean radio warned it could cause 
crop damage in the country's traditional breadbasket in the 
southwest and blow through the capital, Pyongyang. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Philippines, three days of monsoon rains have left at  
least 27 dead and six missing, and floodwaters were still rising. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said nine people were killed in landslides and 18  
drowned. Nearly 12,000 homes were flooded, forcing the evacuation 
of some 60,000 people in the central part of Luzon island, 
including the metropolitan area of Manila. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippine President Joseph Estrada declared a state of  
emergency in the Manila area and three nearby provinces -- 
Pangasinan, Pampanga and Rizal -- opening the way for government 
aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Water spilled over the banks of La Mesa Dam, which provides  
water to the Manila region, and officials urged downstream 
residents to leave right away. 
</P>
<P>
	But hundreds of squatter families who live along river refused  
to move because of fears their shacks might be looted while they 
were gone, disaster officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The victims here are the poor people, the squatters,'' Estrada  
said. ``So that is my top priority.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Flooded streets, many waist-deep with muddy water, paralyzed  
traffic in metropolitan Manila, where schools were closed and 
financial markets suspended for the day. Some residents had to 
perch on rooftops to await rescue. 
</P>
<P>
	The monsoon rains and winds were forecast to continue to batter  
the Philippines for several more days. 
</P>
<P>
	Flooding in eastern Thailand, meanwhile, has killed at least  
five people and left at least 1,000 homeless. 
</P>
<P>
	The ground floor of the two-story Chanthaburi prison was under  
three feet of water today, forcing authorities to order an 
evacuation of 300 of the 1,200 inmates to relieve crowding. 
</P>
<P>
	The inmates waded to buses and were driven to jail facilities in  
other, drier provinces. 
</P>
<P>
	In Vietnam, 24 people have died and 25 others are still missing  
after downpours flooded parts of central provinces last week. 
</P>
<P>
	In southwestern Cambodia, police said today that about 200 yards  
of Route 4, a key highway, was underwater, halting traffic to and 
from Sihanoukville Port. 
</P>
<P>
	Floodwaters were receding on China's Yangtze River after  
rainfall eased. Heavy rains have hit many parts of central China 
this summer, forcing 140,000 military police to help out with flood 
fighting efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	No reports were available on casualties or damage in recent  
days. But state-run media said 300 people have been killed in 
flooding throughout the summer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 08:36:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
