<HEADLINE> Boy Killed at Rainier National Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASHFORD, Wash. (AP) -- A 7-year-old boy on an annual parental  
visit was apparently killed by his father in a murder-suicide at 
Mount Rainier National Park, investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholas Boyd's body was found around noon Monday about 50 yards  
downstream from the Christine Falls Bridge, on the mountain's south 
flank, and about 100 yards from where the body of his father, 
36-year-old Billy Boyd, was found late Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Boyd, a carpenter from Tacoma, left a suicide note in his  
car parked near the bridge saying he intended to take his and his 
son's life, according to park spokeswoman Maria Gillett. 
</P>
<P>
	Pierce County medical investigators have not determined how the  
boy and man died. The boy's body has not been positively identified 
yet, but officials believe it is Nicholas. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no sign of trauma, no indication weapons were  
used,'' Park Ranger Randy Brooks said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators say they believe the father jumped with his son --  
or he pushed him and then jumped -- from the 125-foot-high bridge 
into the icy stream which cascades through a rocky gorge, swollen 
by the melting snowpack. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said they knew of no motive.  
</P>
<P>
	Boyd's son was paying his annual visit from Katy, Texas, under a  
custodial agreement with Boyd's former wife, but ``it did not 
appear there was anger related to the mother,'' Brooks said. The 
couple divorced six years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Family members who read the suicide note said Billy Boyd felt  
deserted and wanted to kill himself. But he didn't want to leave 
his son behind, so the father planned to kill the boy, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Park officials say Boyd had taken his son camping on Thursday.  
They were supposed to return Saturday and the boy was to fly home 
to his mother in Texas. She reported them missing Sunday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
