<HEADLINE> Raiders' FB Crockett Breaks Foot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAPA, Calif. (AP) -- The Oakland Raiders will be without free  
agent fullback Zack Crockett from four to six weeks because of a 
broken foot. 
</P>
<P>
	The Raiders announced Tuesday that Crockett, a versatile running  
back and special teams player who split last season between 
Indianapolis and Jacksonville, broke a bone in his right foot 
during a special teams practice late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Initially, Crockett didn't regard it as serious until X-rays  
were taken. 
</P>
<P>
	``I twisted it when my foot got stuck in the ground,'' said  
Crockett, who signed a four-year, $45 million contract with Oakland 
in the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfortunate, but we hope to have him back as quickly as  
we can,'' said coach Jon Gruden, who had hoped to shore up the 
Raiders' short-yardage problems of last season with the 6-foot-2, 
245-pound Crockett. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here's a guy we were looking at in a lot of situations,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gruden said it is possible the Raiders will look for a temporary  
replacement outside the organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Otherwise, the void will have to be filled with less experienced  
candidates in camp, including Jon Ritchie, who started at fullback 
as a rookie last year, Jermaine Williams, a second-year player; and 
Randy Jordan, a six-year veteran who rushed for 159 yards on 47 
carries last season as a reserve. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
