<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP OKs 'Marriage Penalty' Tax Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans neared agreement Tuesday night on  
a plan to cut personal income tax rates and provide relief from the 
marriage penalty as they sculpted a $792 billion measure expected 
to trigger a veto showdown with the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said negotiators for the House  
and Senate hoped for a general accord on tax cuts by day's end, 
adding, ``That's good for America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GOP officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the  
proposal being crafted behind closed doors called for a gradual cut 
of one percentage point in each personal income tax rate. The 15 
percent tax bracket would go to 14 percent, for example, and the 
39.6 percent bracket would become 38.6 percent. That means the 
percentage reduction would be greater at lower incomes. 
</P>
<P>
	To alleviate the marriage penalty, the Republican bill was  
expected gradually to raise the standard deduction for couples 
until it is double the level permitted for individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, lawmakers were expected to propose widening the  
current 15 percent bracket for couples so it would apply to some 
income that currently is taxed at 28 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders hope to push the measure to final passage by week's  
end, the next step in a veto clash that both the majority party and 
President Clinton seem eager to have. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican officials said the final measure also was expected to  
provide a cut in the personal capital gains tax rate, and then to 
adjust the rates annually to discount the effects of inflation. 
There would be no cut in the corporate capital gains tax. The 
estate tax would be eliminated gradually. 
</P>
<P>
	Contribution limits to individual retirement accounts would  
rise. The self-employed would be permitted to deduct the entire 
cost of their health insurance premiums. Medical savings accounts, 
tax-deductible accounts set aside for health-related costs, would 
be more readily available. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, taxpayers who care for elderly relatives in their  
homes would be eligible for tax credits, and insurance premiums for 
long-term care would be partially tax-deductible for the first 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Precise details were unavailable on these or numerous other  
provisions in the emerging compromise taking shape in private 
meetings in the Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	Senior Republicans and aides shuttled in and out, and others  
were consulted by phone, but there was no place for Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y. the senior Democrat on the  
tax-writing Ways and Means Committee, invited himself briefly into 
the closed-door GOP deliberations in a bit of political theater. 
``It's like having two Christmas lists, and you select the best 
from each list knowing that Santa is not coming,'' he said in a 
reference to Clinton's promised veto. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott, R-Miss., and House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., were  
pressing to have the compromise passed through the House and Senate 
by week's end, to permit rank-and-file lawmakers to trumpet the 
advantages of tax cuts during Congress' long August break. 
</P>
<P>
	Only when lawmakers return to Washington after Labor Day would  
the bill be sent to the White House for Clinton's expected veto, 
although some Republicans practically taunted Clinton to sign it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not give up on the possibility that he will sign (tax  
cuts). But if he vetoes them, we think he'll find he's disappointed 
the American people,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey of 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that Clinton ``is a man who will disappoint everyone in  
his life except his pollster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott told reporters that ``maybe the president will conclude at  
some point that he needs to work with us.'' For now, he added, ``I 
just don't see it happening, so we have to go forward with doing 
what we think is right for the American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House and most Democrats oppose a bill of the  
magnitude favored by Republicans, saying it would shortchange 
Social Security and Medicare and lead to deep spending cuts in 
other domestic programs including education and health care. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has repeatedly termed the GOP proposals risky and said  
that because they rely on anticipated surpluses, the tax cuts could 
return the nation to a new era of deficits. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Republicans, there remained scattered signs of a desire to  
compromise before the bill goes to the White House for a veto. Sen. 
Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, released a letter to Lott urging that a 
final House-Senate deal be held up in hopes there could be a 
``negotiated, bipartisan agreement ... achieved in September that 
ultimately addresses a variety of needs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Privately, other Republicans expressed similar sentiments, but  
there was no immediate indication they were having an impact on the 
leaders' strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, senior Republicans were in contact with potential  
pockets of resistence to final passage. Moderate Republicans in the 
House, for example, were consulted about their demand that 
broad-based tax relief be made conditional on a reduction in the 
national debt or interest payments. One lawmaker, who spoke on 
condition of anonymity, said the party leaders suggested several 
possible alternatives for making the cuts conditional, but none 
involved the debt. The group decided to hold firm and was sending a 
letter to that effect to senior Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans hold a narrow majority of 222-211 with one  
independent and one vacancy in the House, and a majority of 54-45 
with one independent in the Senate. If Democrats oppose the tax 
bill en masse, the GOP has little room for error on final votes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
