<DOCNO> APW19990803.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 14:50:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, GOP Battle Over Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- What if they spent the budget surplus and then  
none appeared? 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton and his congressional Republican rivals stand  
a chance of learning the answer as they fight over what to do with 
$1 trillion in projected surpluses over the next decade. Here are 
some questions and answers about the huge, anticipated flow of 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: How big is the surplus supposed to be, and where does it come  
from? 
</P>
<P>
	A: Both the Congressional Budget Office and the White House's  
Office of Management and Budget anticipate surpluses totaling $2.9 
trillion over the next decade. Each says $1.9 trillion will come 
from Social Security, which is building up reserves for the 
retirement of the baby boomers. The remaining $1 trillion comes 
from the rest of the budget, they say, and it is this piece of the 
surplus that Clinton and Republicans are vying over. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: Are these surplus estimates sound?  
</P>
<P>
	A: Analysts say the economic and technical assumptions CBO and  
OMB relied on seem largely solid. Yet everyone also concedes it is 
impossible to predict how the economy will behave, how many wars 
and hurricanes there will be, and the nature of political pressures 
on spending or taxes over the next decade. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the projections have an immediate, significant  
flaw. 
</P>
<P>
	CBO and OMB assume current laws will be obeyed, usually a  
prudent supposition. But in this case, they assume spending limits 
enacted in 1997 will be honored each of the next three years -- 
which no one believes will occur. The limits expire after 2002, and 
the budget agencies assume that spending will then grow along with 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: How significant is the erroneous assumption that spending  
limits will be honored? 
</P>
<P>
	A: Critics say it is crucial.  
</P>
<P>
	The spending limits clamp down on the one-third of the $1.8  
trillion budget that includes everything but automatic payments 
such as Social Security and interest on the national debt. The 
limits would gradually reduce spending in this portion of the 
budget through 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	But lawmakers are showing an appetite to increase spending, not  
cut it. If spending simply grows at the rate of inflation, nearly 
$750 billion -- or three-fourths -- of the projected 10-year 
non-Social Security surpluses disappear, says the Center on Budget 
and Policy Priorities, a liberal-leaning policy group. 
</P>
<P>
	If lawmakers also wind up approving so-called emergency spending  
at the same average rate as they have recently, nearly 90 percent 
of the $1 trillion surplus vanishes, the center says. Emergency 
spending is extra spending exempted from the spending limits but 
paid for from the surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: Have lawmakers obeyed the spending limits in the past?  
</P>
<P>
	A: No. So far in fiscal 1999, which began last Oct. 1, Clinton  
and Congress have approved $34 billion in emergency spending, all 
of which will come from the surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: What about the coming year?  
</P>
<P>
	A: Lawmakers are threatening to use even more of the surplus in  
fiscal 2000 than they have for 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans have declared the $4.5 billion cost of the  
upcoming census an emergency, and used another $4.5 billion of the 
surplus for their proposed tax cut. Senate Republicans want $7 
billion in emergency farm aid while Democrats prefer $11 billion -- 
more surplus spending. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, final fiscal 2000 spending is expected to end up  
being far more than many of the GOP-written bills now call for 
following likely bargaining this fall with Clinton. In the most 
glaring example, the biggest bill of all -- a $300 billion measure 
financing health and education agencies -- is now nearly $20 billion 
below what Clinton wants. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: Any other gimmicks?  
</P>
<P>
	A: House Republicans have ordered the Congressional Budget  
Office to use certain more favorable estimates by the White House 
budget office, for a savings of $15 billion. If CBO's more 
conservative estimates turn out to be right, that money will also 
come out of the surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	And all of that excludes the costs of unforeseen natural  
disasters, and moves afoot to create prescription drug benefits and 
roll back some savings imposed on Medicare payments to nursing 
homes in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: So what would happen if they planned to use the surplus for  
tax cuts and spending but no surplus appeared? 
</P>
<P>
	A: Just like the bad old days left only two years ago, there  
would be a budget deficit. And once again, the politicians would be 
left to wrestle with how to get out of a deep fiscal hole. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
