<HEADLINE> N. Irish Indicted for Mailing Guns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Three people from Northern Ireland  
and a another from the Irish Republic were indicted Tuesday on 
charges they bought guns in Florida and mailed them to Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	The four men, one of whom is allegedly connected to the Irish  
Republican Army, were indicted on charges of violating the Arms 
Export Control Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the defendants bought 44 handguns from a Boynton Beach  
gun dealer and the group then mailed 15 of the weapons, without 
export licenses or proper authorization, to different addresses in 
Ireland, according to a federal indictment handed down Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Named in the indictment were Siobhan Browne, an Irish citizen  
living in South Florida; and Anthony Smyth, Conor Anthony Claxton 
and Martin Mullan, all citizens of the United Kingdom and Northern 
Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal prosecutor said Claxton admitted involvement with the  
Irish Republican Army, but Claxton's attorney denied the claim and 
authorities have acknowledged they have not confirmed if the men 
are affiliated with IRA. 
</P>
<P>
	All four were charged with conspiracy to export firearms without  
a license or approval, exporting the guns without export licenses 
or written approval, and using the U.S. Postal Service to illegally 
export the handguns. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
