<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Fights Over Training Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A legislative fight over teacher training  
opened in the Senate Tuesday as Republicans introduced legislation 
to turn President Clinton's plan to hire 100,000 new teachers into 
grants for states to educate and hire teachers as they please. 
</P>
<P>
	States know best whether they need more teachers, better-trained  
teachers or a combination of the two, Senate Republicans said. 
</P>
<P>
	``By focusing solely on classroom size, the Clinton  
administration fails to recognize that teacher quality, not 
classroom size, is the most important factor in determining student 
performance,'' said Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., who is sponsoring 
legislation similar to a bill passed by the House last month, 
239-185. Clinton has said he would veto that measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes after Republicans finished presenting the House's  
counterpart legislation, Senate Democrats accused the GOP of going 
back on what they said was a bipartisan agreement last year to 
reduce class sizes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Republican proposal forces communities to choose between  
spending funds on improving teacher quality or reducing class 
sizes,'' said Sen. Ted Kennedy, D-Mass. ``This is a false choice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's plan to hire 100,000 new teachers survived the  
year-end 1998 budget negotiations, but last month, 24 House 
Democrats joined majority Republicans Tuesday to convert the 
program into block grants. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of the block grant legislation say it provides more  
``quality control'' over who is hired and how they are trained than 
Clinton's plan. But opponents say it represents less of a 
commitment to concentrate new teachers on lower grades, where class 
size matters most. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Gregg, the Senate bill would require states and  
local government to set forth a plan for making districts and 
schools accountable for meeting performance standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the House and Senate versions would authorize $2 billion  
annually for five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Interest groups complained that the Senate bill holds districts,  
schools and teachers to lower standards on content knowledge and 
training. 
</P>
<P>
	``This bill represents a giant step backwards in the national  
effort to ensure that every American student has a fully qualified 
teacher,'' said Kati Haycock of The Education Trust, a 
Washington-based research and advocacy group promoting academic 
achievement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
