<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 06:10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boilermakers Mourn Tiffany Young </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Purdue's 1999 national championship women's basketball team was  
a family. Tiffany Young's death hit the members hard. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are a very tight Purdue family, and this is a devastating  
loss,'' said her former coach Carolyn Peck, now with the WNBA's 
Orlando Miracle. ``Tiffany's smile could brighten up a room and she 
will be physically missed, but she will always be a part of me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Boilermakers program was reeling Monday as news spread of  
Young's death in a traffic accident over the weekend when the car 
she was in was struck by a drunk driver. The 5-foot-11 guard played 
a reserve role on Purdue's national championship team, and players 
and coaches remembered her as a special presence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tiffany was an extremely integral member of our team and will  
be dearly missed,'' player Katie Douglas said. ``She will be missed 
as a teammate, but more so as a friend who was always there to give 
love and support.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young started all 33 of Purdue's games during her sophomore  
season, but was relegated to reserve duty last year with the 
emergence of Douglas in a three-guard lineup that included 
Stephanie White-McCarty and Ukari Figgs. The senior averaged 3.3 
points and 1.5 rebounds in her career with the Boilermakers, 
including 2.1 points last season, when she played sparingly. 
</P>
<P>
	During the national championship game, Young held hands with  
White-McCarty on the Purdue bench after she sprained her ankle and 
missed the last four minutes of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was overwhelmed when I heard the tragic news of Tiffany's  
death, and I am still at a loss for words to describe how I feel 
about her being gone,'' said White-McCarty, now with the WNBA's 
Charlotte Sting. ``She was such a good person, with nothing but 
love in her heart for everybody, and she cannot be replaced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young died Saturday night after visiting the family of her  
boyfriend, Neil Sinclair, in Gary, Ind. Sinclair, who was driving, 
was in the intensive care unit at a local hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The other driver, Arnold Eaton, 33, of Great Lakes, Ill., had a  
blood-alcohol content of 0.30 percent and sustained minor injuries 
in the crash, police said. He was being held on a $10,000 bond by 
the Lake County Sheriff's Department on a charge of operating while 
intoxicated resulting in death. His two passengers were 
hospitalized in stable condition with numerous broken bones. 
</P>
<P>
	Young is to be buried Thursday in her hometown of Hillsboro,  
Ala., and Purdue spokeswoman Kathleen Offer said the school was 
working on plans for a memorial. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Purdue family has lost a child, but Tiffany will always  
remain in our hearts. We will carry her love for each of us, and 
she will be our guardian angel into the future,'' assistant coach 
Kerry Cremeans said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
