<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 09:00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Credit, Debit Cards Compared </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Q: Like most people, I have several credit cards that I use  
regularly. Should I consider getting a debit card, too? 

</P>
<P>
	A: Roughly four out of five American families use credit cards  
to purchase everything from groceries to gasoline. Many of those 
same families also are finding that debit cards can be as 
convenient. 
</P>
<P>
	Credit cards let you charge purchases and pay for them later --  
with interest, of course, if the balance is not paid in full each 
month. With debit cards, the money for a purchase is subtracted 
immediately from your bank or brokerage accounts. That makes debit 
cards akin to paying with cash or a check. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an option that virtually all consumers should consider,''  
says Stephen Brobeck, executive director of the Consumer Federation 
of America in Washington, D.C. ``It allows for sounder financial 
management because you can't spend what you don't have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Americans already have spent a lot more than they have. The  
Federal Reserve recently reported that consumer credit outstanding 
hit $1.34 trillion in May. And that figure doesn't even include 
mortgage debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Debit card use has been on the rise, too. VISA International,  
the world's largest card-processing system, says debit cards now 
account for nearly a quarter of its transaction volume. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies that deal with debit cards -- which can be used to buy  
goods or to get cash from Automated Teller Machines -- emphasize 
their advantages over cash. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talk about speed, convenience and security,'' says Tracy  
Connelly, a vice president at VISA USA, which processes Check Card 
debit cards for member banks. 
</P>
<P>
	She notes that debit card holders can buy gasoline at a service  
station or purchase groceries with the swipe of a card. ``You don't 
have to worry about carrying cash or making it to a cash machine,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	An added advantage, she said, is that debit card transactions  
show up on your monthly bank statements, ``which helps in budget 
tracking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What if a debit card is lost? Most issuers limit a card holder's  
liability to the same $50 level applied to credit cards. 
</P>
<P>
	Beth Hirschhorn, senior vice president for new products at Chase  
Manhattan Bank, says use of the bank's debit card has grown 
rapidly. 
</P>
<P>
	She says people generally start at the grocery store and the gas  
station. ``Then they begin to realize it's accepted at department 
stores, drug stores, just about everywhere. We're even beginning to 
see use at some mail order houses and a number of Internet sites,'' 
she says. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks, Chase has added a bonus: Debit card holders can  
earn frequent flyer miles on Continental Airlines each time they 
use their cards. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
