<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Satellite Makers Lose Money Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- In a quiet section of an otherwise busy  
Hughes Electronics Corp. assembly plant, a satellite intended to 
link cellular phone systems across Asia sits unfinished, a casualty 
of deteriorating relations between the United States and China. 
</P>
<P>
	The project has meant a $450 million loss for Hughes -- the  
lion's share of an estimated $500 million that tighter scrutiny of 
technology exports has cost U.S. satellite makers. 
</P>
<P>
	That could grow to more than $8 billion industry-wide over the  
next five years if the government bans satellite sales to China, 
according to the Washington-based Satellite Industry Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry officials complain the crackdown on technology exports  
is creating a licensing logjam that has made it tough to do 
business even with U.S. allies. And, they say, China is taking its 
business to U.S. competitors, further hurting their bottom line. 
</P>
<P>
	``The hysteria over the Chinese situation has painted everybody  
with the same brush,'' said Douglas Heydon, president of Ariane 
Space Inc., the U.S. subsidiary of the European space consortium 
Arianespace S.A. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of non-U.S. customers are saying it's becoming too  
difficult to deal with U.S. manufacturers and they're seriously 
considering not doing it any more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since March, Orbital Sciences of Dulles, Va., hasn't been able  
to exchange technical information with its Canadian subsidiary, 
MacDonald-Detweiler, about a $160 million satellite project for the 
Canadian Space Agency. The agency has hinted it may drop Orbital 
for a non-U.S. company. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Ariane projects also have been slowed because American  
companies are reluctant to share information with European 
customers, Heydon said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, U.S. companies stand on the sidelines as China  
solicits bids elsewhere for new communication satellites. 
</P>
<P>
	Competitors likely to pick up the slack include Germany's  
DaimlerChrysler, French companies Alcatel and Aerospatiale Matra 
and Japan's Mitsubishi. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been told the intention (of tighter controls) was not to  
stop selling satellites to China, but to deal with national 
security issues involved in the launch,'' said Clay Mowry, 
executive director of the Satellite Industry Association. ``We hope 
that's true. What you do is end up giving the market to other 
suppliers and not denying anyone communications ability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes is under investigation along with Loral Corp. by the  
Justice Department for allegedly helping China improve its 
ballistic missiles. Hughes took the loss on the cell phone 
satellite after the State Department raised concerns that this 
project also could benefit the Chinese military. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies contend they complied fully with export  
regulations, and that no information was transferred that would 
affect U.S. security. Hughes' satellite business remains strong 
with $4 billion in back orders. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the Hughes-Loral investigation, U.S.-China  
relations have been damaged by the Democratic fund-raising scandal 
and congressional findings that Chinese spies have systematically 
stolen American nuclear weapons technology. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
