<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vehicle Sales Robust Again in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Never has the auto industry enjoyed such a  
sustained cycle of healthy U.S. sales. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's sales of cars and light trucks are expected to  
easily exceed the record of about 16.1 million vehicles set in 
1986. That would be an unprecedented sixth consecutive year of 
strong sales. July's results reported Tuesday gave no indication of 
a slowdown. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nirvana,'' said James P. Holden, executive vice president  
of sale for DaimlerChrysler's U.S. operations. ``It's a competitive 
cycle that's good for the consumer and good for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers last month took advantage of deep summer discounts to  
keep sales up. Industry sales increased 21 percent compared with 
July 1998, though the comparison was skewed by the United Auto 
Workers strikes that virtually halted North American production at 
General Motors Corp. last summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Not surprisingly, GM posted the biggest percentage gain -- up 63  
percent. But the biggest automaker managed to carve out only 28 
percent of the U.S. market, despite adding more discounts last 
month in an effort to boost its share. 
</P>
<P>
	``GM is not putting enough money on the table to get to their 30  
percent market share target,'' said David Garrity of Dresdner 
Kleinwort Benson. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler AG did especially well last month, with sales up  
10 percent on robust demand for its Jeep and Dodge sport utility 
vehicles and Dodge Ram pickups. Most Asian and European automakers 
also had impressive gains. 
</P>
<P>
	No. 2 Ford Motor Co. posted only a 1 percent increase on the  
strength of a 10 percent improvement in car sales, excluding Jaguar 
and Volvo. Its truck sales were off 4 percent from a year ago -- its 
first decline in that category after 14 consecutive months of 
record year-over-year increases. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford blamed the strikes for an unusual 13 percent drop in sales  
of the F-series line of pickups, the nation's best-selling vehicle. 
Ford says it had record F-series sales in July 1998 because the 
strikes, combined with retooling to produce redesigned '99 models, 
severely depleted GM pickup inventories. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ford's truck numbers in general were a little soft,'' said  
analyst David Healy of Burnham Securities Inc. ``I think it's 
primarily that they feasted off GM last year to a degree. But 
there's also not a lot new in the Ford truck line versus a year 
ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's big SUVs, the Expedition and Lincoln Navigator, also were  
down last month. Meanwhile, the first 118 Ford Excursion SUVs, the 
largest passenger truck on the market, were sold last month. 
</P>
<P>
	GM said it had its best July ever for SUVs and trucks overall.  
Its retail sales numbers, which exclude purchases by business and 
government fleets, were at their highest July level in a decade. 
Despite that, competitors claimed more of the increase in industry 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota Motor Corp. and Honda Motor Co. also posted their  
second-best U.S. sales months. Toyota's sales improved 14 percent, 
with a 13 percent gain in sales of the best-selling Camry sedan 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan Motor Co.'s U.S. rebound continued, with the automaker  
reporting an 8 percent sales increase boosted by healthy demand for 
its pickups and SUVs, including its new Xterra. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda's sales also were up 8 percent, with strong demand for its  
redesigned Odyssey minivan and a 14 percent improvement in Accord 
sedan sales. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
