<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Vs. Most Major Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against most major currencies  
Tuesday amid signs Japan and the United States might work together 
to prevent too rapid a rebound by the Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 115.28 yen,  
up from 114.22 yen at the same point on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro also lost ground against the dollar, falling to $1.0676  
from late Monday's $1.0683. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also drew support from another jump in U.S. interest  
rates in the Treasury bond market, which makes dollar-denominated 
investments more appealing. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese and U.S. officials confirmed Tuesday that they are  
maintaining close contact about the yen's rally, which could harm 
Japan's economic recovery by making its exports more expensive in 
other currencies. No specific response was outlined, but the 
countries could sell yen and buy dollars to counter the trend. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've agreed that sudden changes are undesirable. If  
necessary, we must respond,'' Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said 
Tuesday in parliament, adding that the yen's recent rise against 
the dollar has been excessively strong. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Tuesday, the dollar was quoted at 1.4968 Swiss  
francs, up from 1.4947 late Monday, and 1.4936 Canadian dollars, 
down from 1.5046. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound rose to $1.6205, up from $1.6173 a day  
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8318  
German marks, up from 1.8308 late Monday; and 6.1425 French francs, 
up from 6.1387. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
