<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mazda Sells Loan Subsidiary to Ford </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's Mazda Motor Corp. will sell its credit arm  
to Ford Motor Co.'s finance subsidiary for 8 billion yen, or $69 
million, Mazda said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, to be completed by the end of August, will make Mazda  
Credit Corp. a subsidiary of Ford Motor Credit Co., the world's 
largest auto finance firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda Credit provides loans for people who buy Mazda cars. The  
company has annual sales of about $87 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford owns 33.4 percent of Hiroshima-based Mazda. U.S.-based Ford  
is the world's second-largest automaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford Motor Credit, which now operates in 35 countries, already  
has a Japanese unit, Ford Credit Japan Inc., which finances 
purchases of Ford vehicles. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
