<DOCNO> APW19990803.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 16:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dolphins Left With Six Running Backs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVIE, Fla. (AP) -- On the first day of training camp, Tyrone  
Wheatley said the Miami Dolphins' battle at running back would be a 
six-week marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	He lasted less than a week.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheatley was released Tuesday by the Dolphins after a tentative  
performance in their first scrimmage Sunday, when he gained 18 
yards in seven carries. The move left Miami with six running backs 
to contend for a maximum of four roster spots, including the 
starting job. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately for Tyrone, we brought in a couple of rookies  
who are pretty talented,'' coach Jimmy Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifth-round draft choice Cecil Collins may pose the biggest  
threat to incumbent Karim Abdul-Jabbar. Collins, who played just 
six games in college because of drug and legal problems, scored on 
a 40-yard touchdown run in the scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cecil showed that burst of speed everybody craves in their  
offense,'' guard Kevin Donnalley said. 
</P>
<P>
	The other running backs in camp are top 1999 draft pick J.J.  
Johnson, top 1998 draft pick John Avery, veteran Bernie Parmalee 
and Canadian League export Juan Johnson. The early showings by 
Collins and J.J. Johnson made Wheatley expendable. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tyrone really had a great attitude and worked very hard in the  
offseason,'' coach Johnson said. ``Had we not brought in the young 
backs, Tyrone not only would still be on the team, I think he would 
have made our roster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wheatley, 27, was the New York Giants' No. 1 draft pick in 1995.  
But he started only eight games for them in four seasons and 
carried just 14 times for 52 yards last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami acquired Wheatley from New York in February for a  
seventh-round draft pick. 
</P>
<P>
	``From what I heard, he didn't have good work habits in New  
York, but he worked extremely hard here,'' coach Johnson said. ``He 
has turned it around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Wheatley's agent, Joel Segal: ``We'll have other  
opportunities and find a new team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Wheatley's departure, a backfield logjam remains.  
</P>
<P>
	Parmalee and Avery have a good chance to make the team because  
of their value to special teams, and Juan Johnson will probably 
wind up on the practice squad. That leaves Collins, Abdul-Jabbar 
and J.J. Johnson to contend for two roster spots, with the loser 
likely to be traded. 
</P>
<P>
	The durable Abdul-Jabbar remains the favorite for the starting  
job, which he has held since his rookie year in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got something special about him,'' coach Johnson said.  
``He's a fighter, and he has talent. The guy did rush for 3,000 
yards the past three years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Abdul-Jabbar is widely regarded as part of the Dolphins'  
problem, rather than part of the solution. Despite Johnson's 
emphasis on upgrading the ground game last year, the Dolphins 
ranked 24th in the NFL in rushing. They were 29th in 1997 and 19th 
in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Abdul-Jabbar's stiffest challenge may come from Collins, who was  
available in the fifth round of the draft only because of his 
problems off the field. He rushed for 63 yards in 13 carries in the 
scrimmage and showed the kind of breakaway ability Miami has lacked 
for years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cecil Collins is a good player, and he's only going to get  
better,'' coach Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	One sign of progress for Collins: The rookie was assigned a  
stall in the corner of the Dolphins' locker room last week, but he 
moved into Wheatley's old locker Tuesday next to the other running 
backs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to get excited,'' Collins said, ``until I make  
that last roster.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
