<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Slip Again / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bonds fell Tuesday, driven down again by  
persistent worries of higher interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond dropped 15/32  
point, or $4.68 3/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, a key 
influence on borrowing costs, rose to 6.16 percent from late 
Monday's 6.12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds have fallen in the last four sessions days by continued  
concern by investors that interest rates will rise, hurting the 
value of their existing fixed-rate securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve nudged rates up on June 30 in an attempt to  
prevent a resurgence of inflation. Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan has 
warned the central bank will act quickly again if there are new 
signs the economy is overheating. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent economic reports show the economy continues to grow at a  
moderate rate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board said Tuesday that showed its Index of  
Leading Economic Indicators rose 0.3 percent in June, matching May 
increase. The index, a barometer of future economic activity, 
points to an expansion continuing into early 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
dipped 1/32 point, while intermediate-term Treasurys fell by 3/32 
point to 9/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills remained at 4.83 percent  
while the discount rate was unchanged at 4.70 percent from the 
Monday's auction. Yields on six-month Treasurys rose to 5.00 
percent and the discount increased 0.06 percentage point from the 
weekly auction to 4.81 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	One-year yields rose to 5.14 percent as the discount increased  
0.01 percentage point from late Monday to 4.88 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.93 3/4 percent from Monday's 5.19 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 5/32 point to 117 5/16. The average 
yield to maturity was unchanged from 5.59 percent Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
