<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Athlete Ends Sex Riff, Sets Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWCASTLE, England (AP) -- An American mother of two had to prove  
to officials she was female before being allowed to compete in the 
World Veterans' Athletics Championships and then proved her ability 
by breaking a world record. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathy Jager of Phoenix underwent an examination before setting a  
world mark for her age in the 200 meters Tuesday with a time of 
28.32 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	The 56-year-old mom had been accused of being a man over the  
weekend in a protest lodged by southern hemisphere competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are trying to make trouble with these ridiculous  
allegations,'' said Jager after the decision was announced over the 
public address system at Gateshead stadium. ``I am a mother of 
two.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torsten Carlius, president of the World Association of Veteran  
Athletes, said tests had verified the athlete's sex. 
</P>
<P>
	He said organizers had taken advice from the International  
Amateur Athletic Federation and the tests were carried out within 
guidelines set down by the sport's world governing body. 
</P>
<P>
	``The protests questioning the gender of one female athlete has  
been dealt with through medical examination that has proved her 
gender as being female,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a lot of sympathy with the lady. The situation is that  
she has been accused of something that was untrue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jager, who earlier won a bronze medal in the pentathlon, is a  
home help care nurse. 
</P>
<P>
	She took up track at the age of 50 and has won a number of  
medals in state and national competitions in the U.S. 
</P>
<P>
	She is also competing in the pole vault.  
</P>
<P>
	United States' team manager Sandy Pashkin said the athlete could  
put the ordeal behind her and continue to compete in the 
championships ``which is the reason why she is here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 6,000 athletes from 74 nations have been taking part  
in the championships for women over 35 years of age and men over 
40. 
</P>
<P>
	Jager declined to comment after the 200 meters.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
