<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hoopster Damon Bailey Plays On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Damon Bailey's name was etched in  
Indiana's rich basketball lore by the time he was an eighth-grader. 
Some 40,000 fans watched his final high school game, and thousands 
more tracked his every move in college. 
</P>
<P>
	True, Bailey's basketball career hasn't exactly soared since  
then, but it hasn't fizzled, either. 
</P>
<P>
	Now approaching 28, he's plying his trade in places like Fort  
Wayne, Sioux Falls and Moline, a decent player in a league full of 
decent players, all of them hoping for the same thing: a shot at 
the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	If it comes, Bailey says he'll seize it. If not, he'll move on,  
content with what he did accomplish. 
</P>
<P>
	``All you can really do is control your own game and control  
what you do,'' said Bailey, who's playing for the United States in 
the Pan American Games. ``Because you never know when it's going to 
happen or how many times it's going to happen. 
</P>
<P>
	``So when you do get that chance, you've got to be ready, and  
that's what I've been doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey got a taste of NBA life when he was taken by his  
homestate team, the Indiana Pacers, in the second round of the 1994 
draft. But he never saw a minute of action. He had surgery on both 
knees and spent the season on injured reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	The following year, he hooked up with the Fort Wayne Fury of the  
Continental Basketball Association and has been there since, except 
for a brief sojourn with a professional team in France. 
</P>
<P>
	He did get a tryout with the Chicago Bulls before the lockout  
last summer, and he was signed by the Cleveland Cavaliers last 
January, only to be released three days later. 
</P>
<P>
	Those disappointments have come after a high school and college  
career filled with success and fame. Indiana coach Bob Knight first 
raved about Bailey when the youngster was in the eighth grade. As a 
senior, Bailey led his Bedford North Lawrence team to the state 
championship at the Hoosier Dome, and he made it to the Final Four 
with Indiana in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the NBA page in this storybook remains blank.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's not driving me nuts,'' Bailey said. ``I've been there. I  
know what it's like. It's why we all continue playing the game, 
because it's where we want to be. But I realize there's things that 
get in the way. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of good players in the CBA, not just myself,  
that aren't in the NBA just because there's no room. If you took 
the upper tier guys in the CBA and the lower tier guys in the NBA 
and switched them, nobody would know the difference. For whatever 
reason, those guys in the NBA have gotten that chance and have 
performed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey knows his time for that chance is running out. He  
understands there might not be much demand for a 28-year-old 
undersized shooting guard with two surgically repaired knees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, I'm definitely getting older,'' he said. ``How much  
longer I continue to play, I don't know. Today, I enjoy playing the 
game. I may wake up tomorrow and not enjoy it. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as there's somebody out there wanting me, whether it's  
the NBA or CBA or overseas, wherever it is, I'll continue to 
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. coach Mo McHone, who coaches the CBA's Sioux Falls  
Skyforce, likes having Bailey in the Pan Am Games because of his 
versatility. He can score against a zone or man-to-man defense, he 
can play point guard or shooting guard. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Bailey's NBA chances, McHone said he has something that  
any team needs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there's always a place for a guy who can shoot the  
basketball,'' McHone said. ``It's still the No. 1 fundamental in 
all the game, and here's a guy that's great at it. He's a little 
undersized for a 2-man in that league, but he's smart enough to 
play the one. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have any question that if he got the right situation,  
not only would he have a shot, I think he could make a 
contribution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey has been a solid contributor for the Pan Ams team. He  
averaged 13.8 points in the team's five exhibition games and scored 
13 points in each of the first two games in Winnipeg. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll play three more times in these games before returning  
home. Bailey will keep playing and see where it takes him, keeping 
in mind what he learned in his years with Knight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the thing I took away is not to worry about whether or  
not I'm in the NBA, but just going out and having fun playing and 
working as hard as I can and becoming the best player I can,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If that's good enough to get to a certain level, great. If  
not, then hey, I didn't cheat myself.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
