<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury To Hear Dr. Sam Sheppard Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- For a third time, jurors will be asked to  
decide whether Dr. Sam Sheppard killed his wife in the 1954 slaying 
that helped inspire the movie and TV series ``The Fugitive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Ron Suster, who would have decided the case, on Monday  
granted a request for a jury trial made by lawyers who are 
defending the state in a wrongful imprisonment lawsuit brought by 
Sheppard's son, Sam Reese Sheppard. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawyers wanted more than one person to analyze the massive  
amount of material that has been collected in the 45-year-old case. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Sheppard claims his father should not have spent 10  
years behind bars for the death of Marilyn Sheppard on July 4, 
1954. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Sheppard, who was pregnant with her second child, was  
beaten to death in her bedroom at the couple's home on the shore of 
Lake Erie. Her husband was convicted of murder but always insisted 
that a bushy-haired intruder killed his wife while he was napping 
downstairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Supreme Court later overturned the verdict, ruling the  
original trial judge didn't do enough to protect the jury from 
hearing the many media reports and comments about the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheppard was acquitted at a retrial in 1966. He died in 1970 of  
liver failure. 
</P>
<P>
	His son, now 51, has been trying for years to clear his father's  
name. He and his legal team have found DNA samples and other 
evidence implicating the family's former window-washer, Richard 
Eberling. 
</P>
<P>
	Eberling died in prison last year. He was serving time for  
another murder. 
</P>
<P>
	For Sheppard to win the lawsuit, his father will have to be  
declared innocent of Mrs. Sheppard's murder. That's a stronger 
legal standard than the reasonable doubt needed to clear someone in 
a criminal case. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheppard could collect an estimated $2 million if he succeeds.  
</P>
<P>
	Assistant County Prosecutor Steve Dever said he was pleased with  
the ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	``A group of people as opposed to a single individual can better  
analyze and evaluate the evidence,'' he said. ``We are comfortable 
the truth can be determined as best as it can under the history of 
this particular case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trial is scheduled to begin Oct. 18.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
