<DOCNO> APW19990803.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 15:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybeans Up; Energy Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Corn and soybean futures rocketed higher Tuesday on the Chicago  
Board of Trade after government figures showed an unexpectedly 
large decline in crop conditions, which could reduce expected 
bumper harvests. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, pork bellies futures jumped, while energy  
futures edged lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors in corn and soybeans ignored forecasts for beneficial  
showers to fall in the next 10 days over major Midwestern growing 
areas as they digested the U.S. Agriculture Department's weekly 
crop update, which showed conditions worsened last week as crops 
baked under temperatures that topped 100 degrees in many places. 
</P>
<P>
	Crops in Ohio and Eastern states were suffering severe drought  
conditions, while Illinois and Indiana row crops saw their fortunes 
reverse after weeks of nearly ideal weather. 
</P>
<P>
	The unexpectedly poor crop showings came as a surprise to  
analysts who had been predicted bin-busting harvests for weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The USDA reported late Monday that the portion of the soybean  
crop nationwide rated as being in good to excellent condition 
tumbled to 57 percent from 65 percent a week earlier. In Illinois, 
crops in good to excellent condition plunged to 53 percent from 62 
percent, while they fell to 43 percent from 58 percent in Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 13 percent of soybeans were in poor to very poor  
condition, up from 9 percent the previous week, the USDA said. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn crops fared better nationwide, with the good-to-excellent  
condition falling to 63 percent from 70 percent. But corn crop 
conditions in Illinois and Indiana also fell sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn for December delivery rose 7 1/2 cents to $2.34 a bushel;  
November soybeans rose 13 3/4 cents to $4.77 a bushel. Those contracts 
represent the crop yet to be harvested. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork bellies futures jumped on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange  
after the government snapped up nearly a fifth of the nation's 
frozen pork supply for donation to Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The USDA said it bought 110 million pounds, or 50,000 metric  
tons of hams, pork bellies used for making bacon and other pork 
products for shipment to the economically troubled country 
beginning in September. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-awaited purchase not only will help Russia but will  
help American producers by sharply reducing excess supply caused by 
large increases in the pork herd last year. 
</P>
<P>
	August pork bellies rose 4.50 cents to 59.62 cents a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil and its products fell in lackluster trading on the New  
York Mercantile Exchange as investors squared positions ahead of 
weekly inventory data expected to show little change in U.S. 
stockpiles. 
</P>
<P>
	But after the markets closed late Tuesday, the American  
Petroleum Institute reported an unexpected 1.944 million barrel 
increase, to 210.1 million barrels, in U.S. gasoline stocks in the 
week ended July 30. Crude oil inventories, meanwhile, showed a 
surprisingly steep decline of 4.996 million barrels, to 326.2 
million barrels, from the previous week's level. 
</P>
<P>
	September crude fell 15 cents to $20.30 a barrel; September  
heating oil fell 0.08 cent to 52.29 cents a gallon; September 
unleaded gasoline fell 0.07 cent to 63.02 cents a gallon; September 
natural gas rose 2.3 cents to $2.598 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles' Ripken Placed Back on DL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Cal Ripken was placed on the disabled  
list Tuesday with a sore back, the second time this season the 
Baltimore Orioles' third baseman has been disabled. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, who had never been on the disabled list before this  
year, received a cortisone shot to relieve irritation in his lower 
back Tuesday. He went on the DL from April 18-May 13 with nerve 
irritation in his lower back. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a recurrence of the previous injury,'' Orioles manager  
Ray Miller said before Baltimore's game Tuesday night against the 
Oakland Athletics. ``They say the best-case scenario is he'll be 
ready in 10 days. We were so thin already we had to put him on the 
DL.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, who played in 2,632 consecutive games until stopping the  
streak last year, is hitting .335 with 15 home runs and 47 RBIs. He 
is one homer away from 400 and 32 hits shy of 3,000 in his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken returned to Baltimore on Monday for an examination and  
was put on the disabled list retroactive to Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was fine, then he went to breakfast Sunday morning and said  
he just started getting spasms in his back,'' Miller said. ``It got 
worse all day and the next day. He said he wanted to see the 
doctor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles recalled third baseman Ryan Minor from Triple-A  
Rochester to take Ripken's place. Minor was batting .256 with 21 
homers and 67 RBI in 101 games with Rochester. He was 1-for-10 in 
four games with Baltimore in July. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
