<DOCNO> APW19990803.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 07:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Seeks To Limit Weapons Info </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House passed and sent to the president  
Monday a bill that would make it illegal to distribute information 
about weapons of mass destruction if the intent of distribution was 
to commit a crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the legislation, passed by voice vote, violators could  
face up to 20 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure, which the Senate passed last month, makes it  
illegal to teach or demonstrate the making or use of an explosive 
or a weapon of mass destruction or to distribute information about 
such weapons with the intent of furthering criminal acts. 
</P>
<P>
	The original purpose of the legislation was to codify a  
government settlement with two corporations, but Sen. Dianne 
Feinstein, D-Calif., succeeded in linking it to her provision to 
limit bomb-making material. 
</P>
<P>
	Feinstein noted that two youths responsible for the killings at  
Columbine High School in Colorado learned how to make bombs from 
information posted on the Internet. Hundreds of World Wide Web 
sites contain instructions on building bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate version of a juvenile crime bill now being considered  
by House-Senate negotiators contains similar language. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S. 606.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
