<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Sues Cuba for 'Sham' Marriage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A woman has sued Cuba, claiming it is responsible  
for sexual assaults committed by a man who married her only to 
serve his needs as a spy for the communist nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Ana Margarita Martinez, former wife of Juan Pablo Roque, filed  
the lawsuit Monday in Miami-Dade Circuit Court seeking unspecified 
damages. The only defendant named is the Republic of Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit asserts that Martinez never would have married Roque  
had she known that he was using the marriage ``as a mere pretext to 
carry out his spy mission for a terrorist state.'' Because of the 
deception, the suit says, sex between the pair constituted sexual 
battery. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba also was sued by the families of Brothers to the Rescue  
volunteers who were shot down by Fidel Castro's air force in 1996. 
A federal judge in Miami awarded the families more than $187.6 
million in damages. They're going after frozen Cuban assets for the 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez said she believes Roque married her merely to establish  
``cover'' as a family man. She has had the 11-month marriage 
annulled. 
</P>
<P>
	Roque in 1992 swam to the U.S. Navy base at Guantanamo Bay and  
requested political asylum, saying he was a disenchanted Cuban air 
force major. He met Martinez in Miami that same year, and they 
married in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	On Feb. 23, 1996, Roque vanished from the home that he shared  
with Martinez and her two children. The next day, Cuban jets shot 
down the two planes flown by Brothers to the Rescue, killing four. 
</P>
<P>
	Roque later appeared on Cuban television accusing Brothers to  
the Rescue -- which he had joined in 1994 -- of being a terrorist 
organization actively planning acts of sabotage on the island. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
