<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nuggets' Trades Revamp Roster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- In a single day, the Denver Nuggets completed a  
sweeping reorganization of their roster, keeping Nick Van Exel, 
trading for Ron Mercer and two other players, and signing George 
McCloud. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, we're done making major trades, major changes,''  
general manager Dan Issel said Tuesday. ``There's only so many 
changes you can make. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we certainly have stabilized ownership now (with  
Donald Sturm). Hopefully, we have stable management. I think what 
we need to do now is let these kids play together for two or three 
years and see what kind of basketball team we can come up with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Nuggets sent forwards Danny Fortson and Eric  
Williams and guard Eric Washington to the Boston Celtics for 
forwards Ron Mercer and Popeye Jones and center Dwayne Schintzius. 
The Celtics also will receive a first-round draft choice in one of 
the next four years. 
</P>
<P>
	Barring more deals, the Nuggets will open the 1999-2000 season  
with Raef LaFrentz, almost fully recovered from reconstructive knee 
surgery, at center; Antonio McDyess and Mercer at forward, and Van 
Exel and Chauncey Billups at guard. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, Bryant Stith and Keon Clark figure to be key players off  
the bench, and draft choices James Posey and Chris Herren also 
should be factors, especially the 6-foot-8 Posey. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's going to be real hard to keep Posey off the  
floor,'' Issel said. ``I don't think anybody has a lock on a 
starting position now because Posey is a player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's a nice mix of veterans and youngsters, and they should  
adapt well to the running game the Nuggets hope to use. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that's the only way you can be successful here,''  
Issel said. ``You have to take advantage of the altitude. We're 
still not the biggest team in the world, and so we're going to have 
to get up and down the court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the roster taking shape, Issel was asked what expectations  
he had of the Nuggets this season following 11-71 and 14-36 
campaigns the last two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, my concern is having a competitive team this first  
season in the Pepsi Center,'' he said. ``Our expectation is to be 
competitive for a playoff spot. That ought to be our goal, that 
we're still playing for a playoff spot late in the year, that we're 
not out of it by Christmas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he thought this year's team could be significantly  
better than last year's, he said, ``If you give me a healthy Raef 
LaFrentz, I would say significantly better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still think we're probably two or three years away from  
really seeing if we've done a good job or not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Issel also said the current roster ``has more athleticism than  
any team we've ever had here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heading into the offseason last spring, the Nuggets had four  
goals: acquiring a starting small forward, improving their 
perimeter shooting, upgrading their defense, and acquiring a backup 
center. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercer and McCloud fill the first two needs. Jones, Posey and  
Herren are solid defenders. But Issel suggested the backup center 
spot remains unsolved, despite the trade for Schintzius, an 
eight-year veteran. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the only gaping hole that we wanted to address that we  
have not yet is backup center,'' Issel said. ``Raef is doing 
exceptionally well in his rehab. He's been cleared to do everything 
but scrimmage. We feel quite sure he'll be ready to go full speed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need a backup center. The big problem is they're very  
difficult to come by. So we'll have to wait and see what happens. 
But Schintzius is what we have right now. That didn't sound like a 
great endorsement, did it?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Issel said the 6-foot-7 Mercer, who averaged 17 points last  
season for the Celtics, ``can get up and down the court, he can 
defend, and he's bigger than most people think. The way we want to 
play, I think he'll fit in fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the 6-8 Jones, who played in only 18 games last season  
before undergoing arthroscopic knee surgery, ``gives us a 10-12 
minute guy who can play behind Antonio. He's a good rebounder, a 
good defensive player, and he's a very solid citizen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Re-signing Van Exel was Issel's main goal this offseason.  
</P>
<P>
	``When you look at his statistics, he's one of the better point  
guards in the league, assists-to-turnover ratio,'' Issel said. ``He 
had a terrible year shooting the ball. But he made some big shots 
in the two biggest wins we had last year, beating Utah and the 
Lakers back-to-back. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we get better as a team and he doesn't feel he has to carry  
so much of it himself, he'll be a much better player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-8 McCloud is a deadly 3-pointer shooter who averaged 8.9  
points last season for Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	``He can play a lot of different positions and he can defend,''  
Issel said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
