<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed higher Tuesday,  
with the key index rising in Tokyo after two straight sessions of 
declines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained  
144.23 points, or 0.81 percent, to close at 17,969.93. On Monday, 
the average closed down 36.16 points, or 0.20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei's close was the highest since July 21, when it ended  
at 18,257.52. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo stocks rose as the dollar's gain against the yen Tuesday  
afternoon boosted shares of Japanese exporters. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen cuts the profits of exporters by making their  
products more expensive and therefore less competitive overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar was quoted at 115.40 yen, up  
1.36 yen from late Monday in Tokyo and also above its late New York 
level of 114.22 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose after Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said he  
had conferred with U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers about 
exchange rates in a recent phone call. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian shares rose sharply following a technical rebound in  
blue chips. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jakarta Stock Exchange's Composite Index surged 22.473  
points, or 3.8 percent, to 618.986. 
</P>
<P>
	In Taipei, the main index plunged more than 3 percent before  
buying by government funds erased most of the losses. Traders said 
Taiwanese investors were nervous about China's test-firing of a new 
long-range missile on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taiwan market's key Weighted Stock Price Index slipped 20.75  
points, or 0.3 percent, to 7,175.19. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippine stock and foreign currency markets were closed  
Tuesday because of monsoon rains that flooded large areas of 
metropolitan Manila. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG: Share prices closed higher for the third straight  
session in light trading. The blue-chip Hang Seng Index rose 38.41 
points, or 0.3 percent, to close at 13,473.84. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed higher, recouping  
some of Monday's losses. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 
16.82 points, or 0.7 percent, to 2,180.11. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian stock market closed higher, driven by  
gains in diversified resource stock prices and the country's major 
banks. The All Ordinaries Index rose 32.2 points, or 1.0 percent, 
to 3,032.20. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed higher following two sessions of  
declines. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 13.52 points, 
or 1.4 percent, to 973.33. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares closed higher on buying by local  
institutional funds, dealers said. The Composite Index, which 
tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, closed at 748.34 points, up 13.40 
points, 1.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed mostly lower, although the key  
index rose slightly. The Straits Times Index rose 14.72 points, or 
0.7 percent, to 2,143.37. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stock prices closed mixed. The Stock Exchange of  
Thailand index rose 3.46 points, or 0.76 percent, to 456.07. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
