<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Guzman Ready To Swing With Reds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Juan Guzman has been through this before. He  
knows why he was traded. He knows what's expected. 
</P>
<P>
	And he's happy with all if it.  
</P>
<P>
	The Baltimore Orioles traded Guzman to the Cincinnati Reds just  
before the deadline Saturday night for two minor leaguers. The 
Orioles also agreed to include some cash to help the Reds pay the 
remainder of his $5.25 million salary. 
</P>
<P>
	Guzman, 32, knew it was coming. He knew what it would be like --  
Toronto traded him to Baltimore last July 31, acquainting him with 
the midseason trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Guzman goes from a team that was one of the major leagues' most  
expensive disappointments to one of its biggest surprises. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like the beginning of the season for me now that I'm with  
a contending team that's so close to winning,'' Guzman said 
Tuesday. ``I've been in that position before. I know what to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guzman was in Seattle with the Orioles when he was traded. He  
flew to Baltimore, then joined the Reds on Tuesday. They plan to 
start him for the first time Thursday against Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	``This year I was more prepared than last year,'' Guzman said.  
``I knew for sure I was gone because I'm a free agent at the end of 
the season. I knew they were not going to let me go without getting 
anything back. For the last two months, I've been getting myself 
ready for whatever team I would go to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He wound up in an unfamiliar league. The Reds are hoping that  
hitters' unfamiliarity with Guzman gives him an advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's never been seen in the National League before,'' general  
manager Jim Bowden said. ``Sometimes that's a plus heading into 
September.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The main drawback is that Guzman will have to bat regularly for  
the first time in his major league career. Heading into this 
season, he had only two at-bats -- both in the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	He went 1-for-6 in interleague play this season with an RBI  
single off Atlanta's Kevin Millwood on June 12. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hitting?'' Guzman said. ``I've been in the American League for  
so long ... We'll see. That's all I can say.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
