<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Share Prices Close Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices closed higher today after the  
dollar's gains against the yen fueled hopes for increased profits 
among Japanese exporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 144.23  
points, or 0.81 percent, to finish the day at 17,969.93. On Monday, 
the average closed down 36.16 points, or 0.20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 115.40 yen, up 1.36 yen from late Monday in  
Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 114.22 yen 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, Tokyo share prices ended higher as the  
dollar's gain against the yen this afternoon boosted share prices 
of Japanese companies with large overseas revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen cuts into the profits of exporters by making  
their products more expensive and therefore less competitive 
overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei's close was the highest since July 21, when it ended  
at 18,257.52. 
</P>
<P>
	``The yen's weakness helped blue chips, although they had fallen  
on profit taking,'' said Sachio Ishikawa, general manager at Chuo 
Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Sony, Fujitsu and NEC were among those that ended  
higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 13.37 points, or 0.91 percent, to 1,481.99. 
The TOPIX closed down 10.31 points, or 0.70 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar rose after Finance Minister  
Kiichi Miyazawa said he had conferred with U.S. Treasury Secretary 
Lawrence Summers about exchange rates in a phone call Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``In more ways than one, we are speaking with the U.S., and  
basically, we've agreed that sudden changes (in currency rates) are 
undesirable,'' Miyazawa said today in Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. Treasury spokeswoman in Washington said Summers and  
Miyazawa pledged close cooperation on currency exchange rates. 
Miyazawa refused to elaborate on the conversation. 
</P>
<P>
	``News of the phone call sent the dollar up, and some sell  
orders disappeared,'' said Shuji Takano, assistant manager of 
foreign exchange at ABN AMRO Bank in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone conversation suggested the United States has  
softened its resistance to the Bank of Japan's attempts to weaken 
the yen. Summers had said earlier that the Bank of Japan shouldn't 
manipulate currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan has intervened in recent months to rein in the  
yen's rise against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.08 yen, up from  
121.78 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.8800 percent from Monday's finish of 1.8400 percent, 
driving its price down to 99.32 yen from 99.65 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
