<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Opening Statements in Ala. Gay Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCKFORD, Ala. (AP) -- A prosecutor acknowledged today that a  
construction worker on trial for killing a man over an unwanted 
sexual advance did not cut the victim's throat or beat him to 
death. 
</P>
<P>
	But District Attorney Fred Thompson said Charles M. Butler, 21,  
did play a key role in the Feb. 19 slaying of Billy Jack Gaither, 
39, who was beaten with an ax handle and burned atop a pile of 
kerosene-soaked tires. 
</P>
<P>
	Co-defendant Steven Eric Mullins, 25, who has pleaded guilty, is  
expected to testify against Butler. Prosecutors have agreed to 
recommend a sentence of life in prison without parole for Mullins. 
</P>
<P>
	The district attorney told jurors during opening statements this  
morning that Gaither was a homosexual ``and that is the only reason 
they killed him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It was pure, simple hatred -- hatred of someone perceived to be  
different.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Butler could be sentenced to death in Alabama's electric chair  
if convicted of capital murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, defense attorney Billy Hill Jr. acknowledged that his  
client was the first one to hit Gaither, after Gaither 
propositioned him, while the three were drinking beer in the woods. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said everything his client did was under orders from  
Mullins. Hill agreed with the prosecution that Mullins cut 
Gaither's throat and beat him to death before the body was set 
afire. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the district attorney said Butler aided in the crime  
partly by setting the tires on fire and by burning Gaither's car to 
hide evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't have to be the triggerman to be guilty of capital  
murder,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaither's slaying ignited civic leaders and gay rights  
organizations, spurring comparisons to Matthew Shepard, a gay 
college student slain in Wyoming. 
</P>
<P>
	Police have said the suspects lured Gaither from his home with a  
phone call asking him to a Sylacauga club, then took him to an 
isolated spot in Coosa County, where he was slain. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 00:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Defections Is Focus at Pan Am Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Canada tried to get the focus back on  
the competitive side of the Pan American Games, while defections 
and complaints from the Cuban delegation drew attention away from 
the 13th regional Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba's delegation criticized organizers, saying security was  
lacking and that it would respond quickly to any insult. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cuban athletes will not permit anyone or anything to humiliate  
them ... if their dignity is at stake,'' a statement from the Cuban 
delegation said. ``From now on we will react with full energy to 
provocations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The statement from the Cubans was aimed at a protester who  
jumped out of the stands with a sign ``Human Right First'' during 
their baseball semifinal game Sunday against Canada. But it also 
followed reports of more defections from their delegation. Cuban 
delegation officials insist athletes are being encouraged to 
defect. 
</P>
<P>
	Nineteen-year-old pitcher Danys Baez was the latest to leave the  
Cuban team, supposedly heading to Miami with sports agent Joe 
Cubas, who has helped many Cuban ballplayers defect. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to tell the people of Miami that another Cuban in  
search of freedom is about to become part of the people of Miami 
over there ... to wait for me over there,'' Baez told Miami 
television station WSCV. 
</P>
<P>
	Cubas said Monday that Baez left the team Sunday night after it  
beat Canada 3-2. 
</P>
<P>
	The defection would bring to eight the number of Cubans to  
reportedly leave their nation's delegation since arriving for the 
Games. According to sources close to the Cubans, 400-meter relay 
runner Michal Ortiz, a goalkeeper from the men's soccer team and an 
artistic gymnast also abandoned their compatriots. 
</P>
<P>
	While not acknowledging anyone by name, the Royal Canadian  
Mounted Police, however, said they knew nothing of the latter two 
seeking asylum. They were also unaware of an asylum petition by 
Baez. 
</P>
<P>
	Winnipeg City Police said federal officials had detained the  
protester from Sunday night's game, who gave a Miami address, for 
possible immigration violations. He was taken into custody after 
getting into a scuffle with four members of the Cuban delegation, 
who came upon the protester outside the Canadian Broadcast 
Corporation offices late Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba's anger was eased somewhat by its baseball team's 5-1  
victory over the United States Monday night for its eighth straight 
gold medal in baseball. Cuba takes the Pan Ams very seriously, and 
baseball is its most beloved sport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 14:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aide Clarifies First Lady's Comments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton does not blame her  
husband's marital infidelity on the tumult of his childhood, her 
spokeswoman said Tuesday, despite the apparent link she drew in a 
much-discussed magazine article. 
</P>
<P>
	``She did not say the president's childhood in any way caused  
his behavior, nor does she believe that,'' spokeswoman Marsha Berry 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the debut issue of Talk magazine, which went on sale Tuesday,  
Mrs. Clinton said the president was ``scarred by abuse'' as a 
child. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, he has his weaknesses,'' she told the magazine. ``Yes, he  
needs to be more responsible, more disciplined, but it is 
remarkable given his background that he turned out to be the kind 
of person he is, capable of such leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Expanding on her husband's background, Mrs. Clinton said he was  
scarred at age 4 by a struggle between his mother and grandmother. 
</P>
<P>
	``A psychologist once told me that for a boy being in the middle  
of a conflict between two women is the worst possible situation,'' 
she said. ``There is always a desire to please each one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The comment followed a frank discussion about Clinton's  
infidelities, in which Mrs. Clinton said her husband ``doesn't make 
any excuses for what he did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady's office discussed the childhood abuse question  
after news accounts of Mrs. Clinton's interview focused on that 
aspect. Mrs. Clinton's quotations were misinterpreted, Berry said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that she was basically stating some feelings about his  
childhood, but that they do not excuse his behavior,'' Berry said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart denied that the  
young Clinton suffered physical abuse but said: ``There were 
difficulties in his family. He faced issues that were hard on him; 
they were hard on his family.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
