<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airports To Offer Flights to Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Direct charter flights to Cuba will be allowed  
from airports in New York and Los Angeles for the first time since 
the United States imposed an embargo on the communist-ruled island 
four decades ago, says a leading congressman. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Charles Rangel of New York said Monday he learned in  
conversations with State Department officials that charters will be 
allowed from Kennedy International Airport in New York and Los 
Angeles International Airport sometime after October. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a commonsense decision that will make it easier and  
hopefully cheaper for more Americans to visit Cuba,'' said Rangel, 
ranking Democrat on the House Ways and Means trade subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	Allowing more travel between the United States and Cuba is the  
latest in a string of Clinton administration initiatives to loosen 
restrictions on contact between the two estranged countries. Direct 
flights now are limited to Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of a package of changes announced in January, Clinton  
re-established direct mail between the United States and Cuba and 
expanded the number of Americans able to send cash to Cubans to 
include nonrelatives. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration also said in January it was prepared to allow  
direct flights to Havana from U.S. airports other than Miami. 
Rangel's Monday disclosure was the first indication the suggestion 
was being implemented. 
</P>
<P>
	A State Department official, speaking on condition of anonymity,  
said New York and Los Angeles were the leading contenders based on 
market demand and availability of Customs Service personnel to 
handle the additional workload. 
</P>
<P>
	The official said the final decision was up to the Treasury  
Department's Office of Foreign Assets Control. Rangel said the 
Treasury Department still needed to select the airlines that will 
be allowed to fly. 
</P>
<P>
	A telephone call to Treasury was not immediately returned Monday  
night. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
