<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lynx 73, Mercury 56 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Sonja Tate and Andrea Lloyd-Curry, scoreless  
in the first half, combined for 16 points during a second-half run 
as the Minnesota Lynx beat the Phoenix Mercury 73-56 in the WNBA on 
Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lynx avenged a 79-46 loss in Phoenix on Thursday by making  
10 of their first 15 shots from the field in the second half to 
break open a close game. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota (12-10) led 29-27 with 16:03 left in the game when  
Tonya Edwards hit a 3-pointer to start a 25-15 run. 
</P>
<P>
	Tate scored six consecutive points to make it 46-34, and  
Lloyd-Curry and Tate closed the run with four consecutive free 
throws for a 54-42 lead. The pair combined for 21 second-half 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	Phoenix (10-13) never got closer than seven points after that.  
</P>
<P>
	The Lynx moved within 1 1/2 games of Sacramento for the third and  
final playoff spot in the WNBA's Western Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota had five players in double figures, led by Brandy Reed  
with 17. Angie Potthoff had a season-high 13. Marlies Askamp led 
Phoenix with 12. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota, the WNBA's lowest scoring team, averaged just 54  
points in their last five games, shooting 33 percent and winning 
just once. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lynx hit six of their first nine shots and led by as many as  
nine points in the first half. Phoenix scored the last five points 
to get within 24-20 at halftime. The Mercury made just 7-of-26 
first-half shots. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lynx ended a three-game home losing streak, while Phoenix  
fell to 1-7 in its past eight road games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
