<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holocaust Payments Formula Devised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An international commission is close to making  
recommendations on the divisive issue how much European insurers 
should pay Holocaust victims or their families based on pre-World 
War II life insurance policies. 
</P>
<P>
	A commission source on Tuesday disputed a published report  
asserting that agreement had been reached under which the insurers 
would pay 10 times the face value of their policies. 
</P>
<P>
	The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, called the  
figure an oversimplification, saying in some cases it would be less 
than 10 times and in other cases more. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission, chaired by former Secretary of State Lawrence  
Eagleburger, is composed of five major European companies, Jewish 
groups and American regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Eagleburger will seek comments from the five European insurers  
by Thursday and is expected to release final recommendations the 
next day. 
</P>
<P>
	The five companies are: Allianz AG of Germany; AXA of France;  
Assicurazioni Generali SpA of Italy; Winterthur Swiss Insurance, a 
subsidiary of Winterthur Reinsurance Corp. of America; and 
Anglo-Swiss Zurich Financial Services. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission decided in London in May to pay the ``real  
value'' of the policies. This led to approval here of a formula 
based on long-term government bond rates. The formula takes 
inflation into account and adds 2 percent interest per year, said 
Elan Steinberg, executive director of the World Jewish Congress, 
who participated in talks held here two weeks ago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
