<DOCNO> APW19990803.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 13:10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Top Antivirus Company's Security Invaded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) -- Like firefighters turning their hoses  
on arsonists inside their own firehouse, Symantec Corp. repulsed 
hackers who infiltrated the leading antivirus software company. 
</P>
<P>
	The hackers posted a message on Symantec's Web site early  
Monday, threatening to disarm the company by unleashing a worm, or 
a mutating line of destructive code sent via e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Symantec employees in the Netherlands noticed the threat after  
about an hour, and called executives in San Jose, who deleted the 
message and repulsed the contagion with Symantec's security 
software, said spokesman Richard Saunders. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials didn't say whether they were embarrassed by  
the security breach, but they did notify the FBI, which is 
investigating. 
</P>
<P>
	American businesses lost $7.6 billion due to software viruses  
during the first half of 1999 -- more than in all of 1998, according 
to Computer Economics, a research firm in Carlsbad. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 12:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saturn President Has Determination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRING HILL, Tenn. (AP) -- The determination and self-confidence  
that helped make Cynthia Trudell the first woman to head a major 
U.S. automaker were clearly in evidence the first time she bought a 
car. 
</P>
<P>
	When the native of New Brunswick, Canada, saw her dream car -- a  
yellow 1973 Ford Capri with black interior -- she knew she had to 
have it. She also knew she couldn't get it out of the dealer's lot 
because she didn't know how to drive a stick. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `I don't know how to drive this now, but I will within  
24 hours,''' Trudell recalled. ``My friend had to drive it off the 
parking lot, but I was driving it the next day!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trudell's love affair with cars never waned and has taken her to  
the presidency of Saturn Corp., a position she assumed in January. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's something just sexy and exciting about cars. I love to  
drive them and (I love) how they work,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Trudell stands out in the male-dominated hierarchy of the auto  
industry not only because she is a woman, but because she is so 
approachable. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's very down-to-earth. She talks to you, not at you,'' said  
Dora Mack-Talley, Saturn's liaison to United Auto Workers Local 
1853. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of times people are leery to approach someone in that  
capacity,'' said David Motil, who works in the Spring Hill plant. 
``But she came down here one day ... . People were amazed. They 
were going `Wow, she's actually over here interested in what we're 
doing.''' 
</P>
<P>
	He said having a woman president fits in with Saturn's  
reputation for ``pushing the envelope, trying new things and 
breaking new ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trudell, 46, has her work cut out at Saturn, a General Motors  
Corp. subsidiary that has seen its spotless reputation tarnished 
recently. 
</P>
<P>
	The sting still lingers from last year's labor unrest and sales  
continue to lag as the company transforms itself from a one-model, 
one-factory operation to a two-factory company with three models 
and likely more. 
</P>
<P>
	Trudell hasn't had much time to address those issues since she  
left GM's IBC Vehicles in Luton, England, to become the fourth 
president in Saturn's 14-year history. She took over from Donald 
Hudler, who retired after 3 1/2 years as president and 43 years with 
GM. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, while moving with her husband and two teen-age children  
to a house in Tennessee, Trudell helped put the finishing touches 
on a new mid-size car being manufactured at Saturn's Wilmington, 
Del., plant. 
</P>
<P>
	She's also preparing the Spring Hill plant to build a sport  
utility vehicle next year and spending time in Troy, Mich., where 
it's being designed. 
</P>
<P>
	And Trudell is traveling around the country meeting Saturn  
dealers while trying to get to know workers and the union leaders 
they elected this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Hankins, the new president of UAW Local 1853 in Spring Hill,  
said Trudell impressed him during their initial meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	``She seems to be somebody who sticks to her word. And she's  
absolutely committed to the partnership,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	That partnership is the Spring Hill plant's unique  
labor-management contract, which rewards productivity and gives 
workers a say in how the company is run. Saturn employees average 
about 12 percent less in salary than GM's other workers but can add 
to their base pay by hitting production goals. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers at Saturn's Delaware plant are covered by the UAW  
contract that governs all other GM employees, but they also have a 
contract with the local union that includes some of the teamwork 
aspects in the Spring Hill agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, Spring Hill workers upset with their dwindling  
bonuses and input on management decisions gave their union leaders 
authority to call a strike. They decided not to picket after 
getting word the plant would be home to a new SUV. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of us like an uncertain future. When we have those types  
of uneasiness, they come to a climax and I think last summer was 
the climax,'' Trudell said. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the plant's 7,200 union employees voted out most of  
their leaders, some of whom had represented workers since the plant 
opened. 
</P>
<P>
	While Trudell and the new leaders are sure to have ``tiffs,''  
she said she looks forward to a good relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	``The big thing is to make sure they're involved as we plan our  
future,'' Trudell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hankins said Trudell and the union are working together to keep  
Spring Hill's powertrain production unit, where engines and 
transmissions are assembled, and its 2,000 jobs. GM reportedly is 
considering moving the operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Trudell wants to keep Saturn's team approach in the factory,  
no-haggle pricing policy on the sales floor and reputation for 
premium customer service. 
</P>
<P>
	But she will make changes once she finishes evaluating the  
company. 
</P>
<P>
	``The business is going to become far more complex,'' she said.  
``So we can't naively assume we'll be able to run the business as 
we've always done it. But we still need the basic values -- people 
involvement and empowerment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trudell's first experience with automobiles came growing up in  
Saint John, New Brunswick, where her father was a car salesman. 
</P>
<P>
	``I used to get really interested in the cars my dad would bring  
home. And then when we would have to go pick up a customer's car 
because it wasn't right, I learned what quality was and what it 
wasn't,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	But she didn't jump right into the car business. She went to  
school, eventually earning a doctorate in physical chemistry at the 
University of Windsor, Ontario, in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really thought I'd be a professor in university. But somehow  
that just wasn't what was calling me,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She got a job as chemical process engineer at Ford Motor Corp.'s  
Windsor plant the next year. In 1981, GM hired her as senior 
engineering supervisor at its Windsor Transmission Plant, later 
promoting her to superintendent of manufacturing. 
</P>
<P>
	She moved up through GM's ranks, working in Michigan, Ontario  
and Delaware before heading to England to run IBC Vehicles, which 
manufactures the Fronterra 4-wheel-drive vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	Through her varied work and educational experience, she knows  
car-making from the inside-out. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're not gonna pull one over on her when it comes to that,''  
Hankins said. 
</P>
<P>
	Trudell, who reads voraciously and laughs often, said she might  
differ from a male car company president in insight into how a 
customer views a product or service. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can understand how a female customer wants to be treated. I  
personally resent it if anyone patronizes me. That's why I strongly 
identified with the philosophical culture of Saturn, where people 
are treated with respect,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Trudell also values teamwork.  
</P>
<P>
	``I bring to the party insight and strategy, but when it comes  
to execution, it's through the people that you execute,'' she said, 
quickly adding, ``That doesn't mean I tolerate mediocrity. ... I 
set extremely high standards in both quality and execution. 
Perfection is the standard I work to achieve and hold others to.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 19:52:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  High Jumper Flunks Drug Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- A physician from the Cuban delegation  
traveled to Montreal on Tuesday to examine the urine samples of an 
athlete whose initial test came up positive at the Pan American 
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	While rumors swirled that the athlete is four-time Pan Ams high  
jump champion and world record-holder Javier Sotomayor, Dr. Rodrigo 
Alvarez Cambra journeyed to the testing facility in Montreal, 
sources close to the Cuban team told The Associated Press. The 
sources, who asked not to be identified, would not say if Sotomayor 
is the athlete -- or if it is even a Cuban. 
</P>
<P>
	But, the sources emphasized, a key medical officer of the  
delegation would not be sent on such an assignment if the drug test 
did not involve a leading Cuban athlete. 
</P>
<P>
	After announcing that Juana Rosario Arrendel of the Dominican  
Republic, winner of the women's high jump, was stripped of her 
medal for failing a drug test, organizers also said another 
athlete's A test had come back positive. But no action will be 
taken and the name will not be released unless the B sample turns 
out to be positive. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked repeatedly about Sotomayor failing a drug test, Pan  
American Sports Organization president Mario Vasquez Rana refused 
to speak specifically and would say only that the positive A test 
``could belong to athletics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pan Ams organizers said Arrendel tested positive for the banned  
anabolic steroid stanozolol, the same substance that caused Ben 
Johnson to be stripped of his gold medal in the 100 meters at the 
1988 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Arrendel was quoted in the Dominican Republic as denying she  
used stanozolol and said the test may have picked up a decongestant 
she used before the event. 
</P>
<P>
	``In six years in athletics, I have never used substances to  
enhance my performance,'' she said in remarks published Tuesday in 
the newspaper La Informacion. 
</P>
<P>
	Pan Ams officials also said Ray Martinez, a baseball player from  
Mexico, refused to take a drug test Monday after his team's loss to 
Canada in the bronze medal game. That was tantamount to a positive 
test, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Arrendel's It was the second drug case announced at these games.  
</P>
<P>
	If Mexico had won the game, it would have been stripped of the  
bronze medal, Vasquez Rana said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not take him as he were dirty or cheating,'' Vasquez Rana  
said. ``He was just punished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rosario won the high jump with a leap of 6 feet, 4 inches and  
had been the Dominican Republic's only gold medalist at the games 
so far. 
</P>
<P>
	Argentina's Solange Witteveen, the runner-up, gets the gold. The  
silver goes to Brazil's Luciane Dambacher and the bronze to 
Canada's Nicole Forrester. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first drug case of the games, Steve Vezina, goalkeeper  
for the Canadian in-line roller hockey team that beat the United 
States 7-6 in the title game, tested positive for stimulants and 
steroids. Canada was stripped of the gold, which was awarded to the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Sotomayor, the world record holder, won the high jump on the  
last day of the track and field competition. But neither Vasquez 
Rana nor the medical director of the games, Eduardo de Rose, would 
confirm that the positive A test came from the last day of that 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked specifically if that test came from the final day, de Rose  
said, ``I don't want to answer your question. I have the right to 
no comment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vasquez Rana said all the track and field testing had been  
completed and ``we have no positive results officially unless we 
count that from the Dominican Republican.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, talking about the A sample, Vasquez Rana said, ``There is  
a positive A that could belong to athletics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	De Rose did say that he ``never had an experience to see a B  
(test) not confirm an A.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 19:52:04 </DATE_TIME>
