<DOCNO> APW19990803.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 16:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRL Fines Cheever, Unser $5,000 Each </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Drivers Eddie Cheever and Robby Unser were  
fined $5,000 each for unsportsmanlike conduct by the Indy Racing 
League on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman Ron Green also said the IRL would investigate rookie  
driver Scott Harrington's conduct during Sunday's MBNA Mid-Atlantic 
200. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington conceded that some drivers complained to the IRL  
about his tactics, which he said were being misinterpreted as 
blocking. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheever, angry and frustrated, walked down pit road after the  
IRL race at Dover Downs International Speedway to where Harrington 
was seated. A profane argument ensued, and Cheever admits he 
grabbed Harrington by his racing uniform and lifted him. 
</P>
<P>
	Unser joined Cheever as he walked toward Harrington. Witnesses  
said others in the area stepped in and quoted Unser as telling 
Harrington: ``It isn't over yet. This is just the beginning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A day after the confrontation, Cheever apologized.  
</P>
<P>
	``My actions were inexcusable,'' he said Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Unser said Tuesday he also regretted what happened.  
</P>
<P>
	``I should have waited and discussed the matter with the IRL. I  
did not have any intention for the situation to get out of 
control,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 14:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Close Mixed; Dow Up 31.35  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A volatile session on Wall Street ended with  
mixed results for stocks today as a forecast of continued economic 
growth kept investors on edge about interest rates. The Dow Jones 
industrial average closed up 31.35 at 10,677.31 after shifting 
between positive and negative territory for much of the day. 
Broader stock indicators were lower. The Nasdaq composite index 
suffered another steep loss as technology stocks faltered. It was 
down 35.53 at 2,588.00. ``The general tenor is one of malaise,'' 
said Scott Bleier, chief investment strategist at Prime Charter 
Ltd. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,677.31  + 31.35
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1,092  Declines 1,888  Unchgd  548
NYSE Volume:         721,899,330
Most Active NYSE issue:         America Online88 11/16 - 4 3/16
S&AMP;P 500:         1320.35  - 7.70
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          780.47  -  3.17
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,588.00  - 35.53
Gold(final) -    $257.00    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.
Silver(final) -   $5.460  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.

</P>
<P>
	Leading Economic Indicators Rise  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The U.S. economy is poised to keep growing at  
least through the first half of 2000, leaving it on track for 
achieving the longest expansion ever, according to a key gauge of 
future activity. The Conference Board said its Index of Leading 
Economic Indicators, which is designed to help spot turning points 
in the economy, rose 0.3 percent in June to 107.7. That matched the 
May increase and brought gains in the indicators to eight out of 
the past nine months. The last decline, in April, was 0.1 percent. 
The longest economic expansion in U.S. history lasted for 106 
months, from February 1962 until December 1969. The current 
expansion, which began in March 1991, would match the record if it 
continues through January 2000 and pass it if it lasts until 
February. 

</P>
<P>
	SEC Makes Small Stock Fraud 'Sweep'  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Securities and Exchange Commission officials  
announced today their second nationwide sweep against small-company 
stock fraud, a success tempered by worries over a legislative 
proposal that could reduce the SEC's budget and hamper future 
enforcement efforts. ``It certainly would cut into our ability to 
bring cases,'' SEC Enforcement Director Richard Walker said. He 
announced enforcement actions against 82 people and companies in 26 
cases of alleged stock fraud that bilked investors of millions of 
dollars. The latest fraud sweep differed from the first, conducted 
last October, which cracked down on investment fraud over the 
Internet. This time, only four Internet cases were involved. This 
time, such offenses as stock-price manipulation and sales of 
unregistered stocks were among a wide variety of targeted offenses. 

</P>
<P>
	ExciteAtHome Denies Merger Rumor  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ExciteAtHome Corp. denied a report that the  
company is in merger talks with Yahoo!, though it acknowledged 
today that the two Internet companies have talked about a 
partnership. Yahoo!, the second-largest Web search and directory 
destination, has held discussions over the last six weeks to 
acquire ExciteAtHome, the No. 6 destination, for more than $17 
billion, according to an article published on BusinessWeek Online. 
But ExciteAtHome president George Bell, speaking at a technology 
conference, told reporters, ``There is no truth to the rumors about 
acquisition discussions.'' A Yahoo! spokeswoman said the company 
does not comment on market rumors. Shares of ExciteAtHome were at 
43 3/8, up 7/8. Shares of Yahoo! were at 125 3/8, down 6 15/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Top Antivirus Company's Security Invaded  
</P>
<P>
	CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) -- Symantec Corp. repulsed hackers who  
infiltrated the leading antivirus software company. The hackers 
posted a message on Symantec's Web site early yesterday, 
threatening to disarm the company by unleashing a worm, or a 
mutating line of destructive code sent via e-mail. Symantec 
employees in the Netherlands noticed the threat after about an 
hour, and called executives in San Jose, who deleted the message 
and repulsed the contagion with Symantec's security software, said 
spokesman Richard Saunders. 

</P>
<P>
	Waste Management Meets Low Estimate  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Waste Management Inc., whose stock price shrank  
in half last month in the wake of two separate warnings of reduced 
earnings, met lowered expectations today. The nation's No. 1 trash 
hauler earned $371.8 million after special items, or 58 cents a 
share, compared with $243.2 million, or 41 cents a share, in the 
same period a year ago. Analysts initially had Houston-based Waste 
Management earning 78 cents per share, then lowered their estimate 
to 67 cents after the company's July 6 warning. Last week, the 
company issued a second warning of earnings between 58 and 60 cents 
a share. Shares of Waste Management were at 24 3/16, down 1 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Online Banking Risks Criticized  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite the inherent risks of Internet  
banking, nearly half the banks, thrifts and credit unions in a 
survey hadn't taken all the necessary steps to limit risks, 
according to a report by congressional investigators released 
today. The number of financial institutions offering Internet 
banking has nearly tripled over the past year, and more than 6 
million Americans go online to transfer money between accounts, pay 
bills, check account or investment balances and apply for loans. 
Some lawmakers are concerned about the safety and security of 
online banking and the possibility that consumers could lose money 
or have their financial privacy breached by hackers. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM Wants $11 Million Tax Refund  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- City schools would be hit hard if IBM  
wins a lawsuit that could mean a property tax refund of as much as 
$11 million. The New York-based electronics giant claims Santa 
Clara County over-assessed three of the company's properties in San 
Jose by more than $1 billion between 1990 and 1994. ``The CEO of 
IBM ... has given a lot of speeches about the poor state of public 
education, but through a technicality, IBM is now attempting to get 
a tax refund that would directly impact in a big way schools,'' 
county tax assessor Larry Stone said. ``Our commitment to education 
is indisputable,'' countered IBM spokesman Kevin McKee. In the 
lawsuit, filed Friday in Santa Clara County Superior Court, the 
company argues the county overvalued its main San Jose campus and 
two other locations during the early-'90s recession. 

</P>
<P>
	Toys R Us Recalls Doll Sets  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- About 71,000 dolls that come with bathtub  
accessories were recalled today by the U.S. Consumer Product Safety 
Commission because the toys pose a choking risk to young children. 
Bathtub Baby -- a vinyl doll that comes with a blue plastic bathtub, 
a fish-shaped strainer and a small pink ball -- was sold at Toys R 
Us stores from October 1998 until last month. After inspecting the 
toy, the commission determined the ball was too small for children 
under 3 years old. Owners should immediately return the doll set 
for a refund. Toys R Us sold Bathtub Baby for about $2. 

</P>
