<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Agent: AWOL Vikings Player To Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANKATO, Minn. (AP) -- Dimitrius Underwood skipped out on the  
Minnesota Vikings to attend to a ``family matter'' and will return 
to training camp Wednesday, his agent said after finally tracking 
down the AWOL rookie. 
</P>
<P>
	``He called to inform me that he was planning to be back in  
Mankato tonight. He apologized for the way he took off without 
talking to anybody or asking for permission from the team or even 
letting me know or anyone else know that he was doing what he was 
doing,'' agent Craig Domann said Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had to deal with a family matter that had gotten to crisis  
proportions, and he had to take care of it. He is now focusing his 
energies back on football. I informed him that he would need to be 
talking to coach Green. He said he was looking forward to doing 
that either late tonight or first thing tomorrow morning depending 
on what time he got in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Domann declined to go into specifics about the family matter or  
Underwood's whereabouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Dennis Green wouldn't discuss Underwood's status after  
learning that the rookie had been located more than 24 hours after 
his mysterious disappearance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Like I said, I only talk in the morning,'' Green said as he  
went to dinner at the team's dormitory just before 7 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, a first-round draft pick, inexplicably disappeared  
from training camp Monday, worrying the team, his agent and his 
family, all concerned about his well being. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's been my only concern the whole time,'' assistant coach  
Andre Patterson said Tuesday before Underwood was tracked down. 
``Football's just a game. I couldn't sleep because of this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Domann didn't hear from his client until Tuesday evening.  
Neither did Underwood's mother and brother in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, a 6-foot-6, 276-pound defensive end from Michigan  
State, was the 29th selection in the NFL draft. He signed a 
five-year contract Sunday for more than $5 million, including a 
partially deferred signing bonus of $1,750,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Domann dropped off his client at the team's dorm Sunday  
afternoon, and Underwood, dressed in military fatigues, proclaimed: 
``It feels good to be in Minnesota, a long anticipation. I got the 
war fatigues, got the Army fatigues, got to go to war.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He participated in Monday morning's workout, ate lunch with his  
teammates, then between noon and the players meeting at 3 p.m., he 
vanished, leaving most of his clothes and personal items, including 
a Bible, in his room. 
</P>
<P>
	About 7:30 p.m. Monday, the Vikings issued a statement saying  
Underwood, who missed his senior season at Michigan State because 
of an ankle injury, had left camp without permission and without 
telling anybody where he was going or why. 
</P>
<P>
	Defensive coordinator Foge Fazio said nothing occurred during  
the morning practice that would have indicated there was a problem. 
And his roommate, rookie defensive end Talance Sawyer, said 
Underwood never said anything about leaving camp, although he said 
Underwood received a phone call shortly before his disappearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Green was miffed by the rookie's unexcused absence from three  
workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, we're disappointed the guy would not want to play  
football. That's really what it comes down to,'' Green said. ``He's 
not the first guy to ever walk out of camp without permission and I 
guess he probably won't be the last one, either. But we'll stay 
focused on our football team. Now, it's just between Dimitrius, the 
NFL and us. We take a fairly aggressive approach on this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Green refused to elaborate or to say if Underwood, who was  
expected to compete with Stalin Colinet at left end, would face 
disciplinary action upon his return. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
