<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gunman's Two Kids Laid To Rest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITHIA SPRINGS, Ga. (AP) -- Having already lost his daughter and  
wife to violence, Bill Spivey was overcome at the thought of having 
to bury his grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	Spivey broke down in tears Monday and appeared to stagger with  
grief at the White Columns Chapel while saying goodbye to Matthew 
and Mychelle Barton, who were killed Wednesday by their father, 
Mark O. Barton. 
</P>
<P>
	Barton, a suspect in the death of Deborah Spivey Barton and  
Eloise Powell Spivey five years ago, killed his second wife, Leigh 
Ann, before opening fire at two brokerage offices in Atlanta on 
Thursday, leaving another nine dead. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Kenneth Hennesy told Spivey and 300 other friends and  
family members that they shouldn't question why the children were 
gone. He urged them to take comfort in the fact that they had gone 
on to something better. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the chapel, teddy bears and inscriptions ``Gone to be  
with Momma'' decorated the pulpit. Mourners recalled how Matthew, 
11, loved baseball and Mychelle, 7, was an active Girl Scout. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to remind you how your lives have been enriched just by  
knowing them,'' Hennesy said. ``Sometimes the answers are not there 
for the understanding of man, but there for us when we get to 
heaven.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barton was suspected but never charged in the murder of his  
mother-in-law and first wife -- the children's mother -- five years 
ago. The women's bodies were found hacked to death in a camper in 
Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	The funeral for Barton's two youngest victims was one of three  
held Monday. Two more were scheduled for today, for day traders 
Edward Quinn and Joe Dessert. 
</P>
<P>
	In Houston, services were held for Kevin Dial, 36, a manager at  
Momentum Securities and one of the first to die in the shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Dial's sister, Sherri Dial read a letter from her brother  
written a day before his death that vowed that he would live life 
to the fullest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pretty sure you're with Elvis, having cocktails, trying to  
convince God to let (John) Belushi visit,'' Ms. Dial said, speaking 
of her brother and drawing chuckles from mourners. ``And I think 
he'll probably do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Sandy Springs, north of Atlanta, a memorial service was held  
for Russell Brown, a 42-year-old day trader at Momentum Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the first time in his life, he finally found something he  
loved in day trading -- he would have done it 24 hours a day if 
possible,'' Brown's fiancee Patti Balon told those attending the 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll miss ... his laugh, his little smirk, the way he walked,  
his hugs -- those hugs that meant it had been awhile since you'd 
seen each other and he was so glad to see you,'' said family friend 
Ray Chase. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
