<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Production Resumes in N.J., La. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Production resumed Tuesday at General Motors  
Corp. assembly plants in Louisiana and New Jersey after a problem 
with leaky brake lines on some pickups and sport utility vehicles 
was resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem, detected Friday, led GM to idle the plants Monday.  
The problem affected two-wheel-drive versions of the Chevrolet 
S-10, GMC Sonoma and Isuzu Hombre pickups produced at Shreveport, 
La., and the same pickups and two-door Chevrolet Blazer and GMC 
Jimmy SUVs made at Linden, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	GM said the leaks were found on a small number of vehicles in  
final inspection and were determined to be caused by a brake line 
wiggling loose as the trucks moved down the line. The problem was 
with assembly, not with the brake system itself, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Full production resumed at Shreveport Monday and limited  
production was under way at Linden. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
