<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lions' Westbrook Can Keep Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIVERSITY CENTER, Mich. (AP) -- Despite a broken hand, Detroit  
Lions cornerback Bryant Westbrook can continue training 
immediately, coach Bobby Ross said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Westbrook, the Lions' first-round draft pick in 1997, broke a  
bone in his left hand during Monday afternoon's practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like he can come out here and do some things in terms  
of drill work, which will keep him tuned to what he has to do,'' 
Ross said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ross said that he can begin working out and running, although he  
is off-limits to hitting drills. Ross added that Westbrook should 
be back by the second week of the exhibition season, and that he 
shouldn't have to rush in order to be ready for season opener on 
Sept. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	``That'll be okay,'' Ross said. ``That'll be fine as long as he  
can keep his conditioning and keep his work on the field. I want 
him to keep his sharpness because he came back (into training camp) 
very good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ross also said cornerback Kevin Abrams, out with a foot injury,  
will travel to New York to see a specialist. 
</P>
<P>
	Ross added he wants another opinion on Abrams' injury ``just to  
make sure'' that it is all right for him to begin practicing. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet another Lions player sidelined Tuesday was offensive lineman  
Aaron Gibson, a first-round pick in the 1999 draft. The 380-pound 
Gibson was red-shirted for the day due to a recurring shoulder 
injury that has hampered him since mini-camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibson underwent an MRI and an ultrasound Tuesday. Ross said he  
was not sure yet what the results of the procedures were, adding 
that he is keeping Gibson out of practice for now as a precaution. 
</P>
<P>
	The report on rookie defensive end Jared DeVries, the Lions'  
third-round pick in April, was better than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Ross, the injury which DeVries sustained when his  
foot was stepped on by a cleat Monday resulted in a mild sprain but 
no broken bones. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's day-to-day,'' Ross said. ``It could be a while because  
there's a lot of swelling, but we dodged a bullet on that one, and 
we feel pretty good about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defensive tackle Luther Elliss continues to be held out of  
practice as he recovers from a broken orbital bone beneath his eye 
suffered in a July surfing accident. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
