<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mount Baker Sets Snowfall Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans sweltering in the summer heat may  
want to take a moment to imagine 95 feet of snow in the driveway. 
</P>
<P>
	That's how much accumulated last winter at Mount Baker, Wash.,  
setting a seasonal snowfall record for the United States and the 
world, the National Climatic Data Center announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Climate Extremes Committee said the 1998-99  
snowfall at Mount Baker totaled 1,140 inches. 
</P>
<P>
	That topped the previous record of 1,122 inches set at Mount  
Rainier, Wash., in the winter of 1971-1972, the data center 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	While the extremes committee was concerned only with national  
records for the United States, the data center said this total also 
stands as a world record for a verifiable amount. 
</P>
<P>
	The record snowfall was measured at the Mount Baker Ski Area,  
which made an unofficial claim on the record in May, announcing a 
total of 1,124 inches even though the snow season wasn't over. Now 
the extremes committee has made the record official, at a higher 
total than the ski area originally announced. 
</P>
<P>
	The figure of 1,140 inches was accepted after study by the  
extremes committee, which included representatives of the National 
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, the American Association of 
State Climatologists and a regional expert from the Western 
Regional Climate Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Snowfall can be difficult to measure accurately because it  
settles, melts and drifts from place to place. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee said the measurement met snowfall observation  
standards and practices prescribed by the National Weather Service, 
and was thus considered to be an accurate depiction of the amount 
that fell. 
</P>
<P>
	``The measurement frequency was once a day; a flat surface was  
used to measure daily snowfall amounts; and a snow stake for snow 
depth measurement was also in place,'' said Raymond Downs, an 
observations standards expert on the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mount Baker Ski Area is located at an elevation of 4,200  
feet, nine miles northeast of the summit of the Mount Baker 
volcano. The snowfall season is for the period from July 1, 1998, 
through June 30, 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavy snow is common in the Northwest with regular winter storms  
coming ashore loaded with moisture from the Pacific Ocean. When 
that wet air meets the mountains and rises the moisture condenses 
into snow. 
</P>
<P>
	Last winter a moderately strong La Nina in the Pacific Ocean  
increased the stormy pattern, with a much higher frequency of wet 
and cold weather systems affecting especially the area from the 
Cascade Range westward. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 11:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers Sign Sean O'Brien </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Flyers have signed  
defenseman and left wing Sean O'Brien to a one-year contract, the 
team announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Brien, 27, had six goals and 13 assists for 19 points and 215  
penalty minutes in 63 regular-season games last season. He had a 
goal, two assists and 60 penalty minutes in 18 games for the 
Philadelphia Phantoms, the Flyers' American Hockey League 
affiliate, after being acquired on Feb. 10 from the Pittsburgh 
Penguins in exchange for future considerations. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is a guy that we feel is a depth player and a player that  
at times can play for the Flyers, but basically he has been signed 
for the Phantoms,'' Flyers assistant general manager Paul Holmgren 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-foot-11, 190 pound O'Brien was a member of the Phantoms'  
1998 Calder Cup Championship team before being signed as a free 
agent by Pittsburgh in the summer of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the contract were not disclosed.  
  	   	
