<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 13:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Won't End Botsford's Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Winning an Olympic gold medal often  
means the end of a career for a swimmer. Not for Beth Botsford. At 
least not for now. 
</P>
<P>
	Botsford was the youngest individual swimming champion at the  
1996 Olympic Games, winning the women's 100-meter backstroke when 
she was only 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``While that was a great accomplishment, and I'm proud of it,  
that's not all there is to swimming,'' she said. ``I didn't think 
it was then and I don't think it is now. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still have swimming in college and I would like to drop my  
times down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Botsford will swim the 100-meter and 200-meter backstrokes this  
week at the Pan American Games, then get ready for her freshman 
year at Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Swimming for a team other than the North Baltimore Aquatic Club  
will be a new experience for Botsford. She has been with that team 
for 8 1/2 years, except for a two-month break in 1998 when she wasn't 
sure she wanted to continue swimming. 
</P>
<P>
	``I needed to take time off to decide where I was going with my  
swimming,'' Botsford said, ``and how long I wanted to stay in the 
sport.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her coach at the Aquatic Club didn't try to stop her.  
</P>
<P>
	``He was very agreeable and told me to do what was in my best  
interest,'' Botsford said. ``I said I would come back when I missed 
it. I was losing the spark. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was one of the best decisions I ever made. I wasn't into my  
sport as much as I wanted to be. Taking time off made me realize 
how much I missed it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Botsford's burnout didn't last long, but it cost her valuable  
training time. When she returned last summer, she wasn't sharp. 
</P>
<P>
	In the national championships that determined the makeup of the  
Americans' A, B and C teams, she finished fourth in the 100 
backstroke and fifth in the 200. Instead of qualifying for the A 
team and a trip to the Pan Pacific Games in Sydney later this 
month, she was sent to the Pan Am Games. 
</P>
<P>
	That has not dampened her enthusiasm.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited to be here,'' she said. ``I'm so ready to swim.''  
</P>
<P>
	Botsford, a member of several national teams, calls this the  
closest-knit of the squads. 
</P>
<P>
	``This group meshes nicely,'' she said. ``It's very tight.''  
</P>
<P>
	It's also very colorful.  
</P>
<P>
	Botsford and several other women are wearing glistening red,  
white and blue nail polish. Others are sporting little American 
flags on their nails. 
</P>
<P>
	With her experience, Botsford is considered one of the veterans  
of the team, the opposite of her experience at the '96 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Atlanta, I was a little uncomfortable with my age,'' she  
said. ``It was always a factor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was always put in the category of being lucky. I said  
because I was 15, that doesn't set me aside. I've worked just as 
hard as anyone else. I didn't think my age should have been such a 
factor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got nervous, I got butterflies, just like everyone, but I  
knew what I was doing. I was there to perform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Botsford also performed well in the 400-meter medley relay,  
winning a second gold medal. 
</P>
<P>
	Her two golds don't occupy a prominent place in her parents'  
home in Timonium, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're in boxes between two bookshelves near the fireplace in  
the family room,'' she said. ``They're not on display. That's not 
my style. I would feel weird putting them on display. 
</P>
<P>
	``If people ask to see them, I'm always willing to show them.  
</P>
<P>
	``When we go away, my parents put them in safe deposit boxes.''  
</P>
<P>
	Since the Atlanta Games, the 5-foot-7, 130-pound Botsford has  
grown about 3 inches and added 12 pounds. She also has matured 
mentally. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've grown up a lot,'' Botsford said. ``I've also changed my  
program. I've paid attention to nutrition, I've done more 
cardiovascular exercising and I'm weight training for the first 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel better than I have in a long time.''  
</P>
<P>
	Since last summer, Botsford has had only a couple of meets in  
short-course competition. That's why the games will be a big test 
for her. She is trying to downplay the meet, the same attitude she 
employed three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of the reason I was successful in Atlanta was because I  
looked at the Olympic Games as just another swim meet,'' she said. 
``If I had thought of it as the Olympics, it would have freaked me 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sounds more amazing when other people say I'm an Olympic  
gold medalist than when I think about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The plan now is to get back to another Olympics.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
