<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 14:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sprinter Mitchell Gets Two-Year Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Dennis Mitchell, one of the world's best sprinters, received a  
two-year ban Tuesday for a failed drug test but will be eligible to 
run in the 2000 Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Track and field's governing body said his drug test from 16  
months ago showed high levels of testosterone. 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF arbitration panel ruled that Mitchell, the 100-meter  
bronze medalist in the 1992 Olympics and two-time bronze medalist 
at the world championships, had no right of appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``This decision is final and binding,'' Giorgio Reineri, a  
spokesman for the International Amateur Athletic Federation, said 
from the organization's headquarters in Monte Carlo, Monaco. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell's lawyer maintained on Tuesday the 33-year-old sprinter  
had never taken testosterone or any other banned substance. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has always been against the use of drugs in track and  
field,'' lawyer Suja Thomas said from New York. ``This is truly a 
severe disappointment to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A call to Mitchell in Florida was answered by his wife, who said  
he was not home. Mitchell ran Monday in Malmo, Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell will be ineligible from April 1, 1998, until March 31,  
2000. Any performances by him during that period are ``null and 
void.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The retroactive ban ends six months before the Sydney Olympics.  
However, Mitchell, the U.S. 100-meter champion, will miss the world 
championships this month in Seville, Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is about Dennis Mitchell and he is an exemplary person,  
and secondarily he is an athlete,'' Thomas said. ``He doesn't want 
this perception and he wants to compete. He should compete because 
he hasn't done anything wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reineri of the IAAF said he did not consider the ban a light  
punishment. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the rule for everybody,'' he said. ``According to our  
constitution, a ban starts the day after the positive doping 
test.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A three-member panel of USA Track and Field cleared Mitchell in  
December. The USATF did not release the details of Mitchell's 
defense or the reasons for exonerating him. 
</P>
<P>
	But London's Daily Telegraph reported this year that Mitchell  
won his case on grounds that his positive result stemmed from 
having sex four times and drinking five bottles of beer the night 
before the test. 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF arbitrators met July 24-25. The organization said the  
USATF decision in December was ``erroneous.'' Messages left at USA 
Track and Field in Indianapolis were not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas disputed the report that sex and beer contributed to the  
positive drug test. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's much more complicated than that,'' she said, adding that  
a combination of stress and nonbanned substances caused him to fail 
the test that day. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what this case is all about,'' she said. ``It's very  
unfortunate it has come to this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Mitchell ran the 100 in 10.09 seconds in Malmo. He  
led fellow American Maurice Greene for the first 50 meters before 
finishing second to the world record-holder. 
</P>
<P>
	His best time this season is 10.02 with three other Americans  
having run faster. He has also run a wind-assisted time of 9.97 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
	When he tested positive, Mitchell was the head of the USA Track  
and Field's Athlete Advisory Committee. He no longer holds that 
position. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
