<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Musgrove Wins Gubernatorial Primary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Lt. Gov. Ronnie Musgrove won Mississippi's  
Democratic gubernatorial primary Tuesday, and former Rep. Mike 
Parker beat five other Republicans for the nomination to succeed 
the state's first GOP governor since Reconstruction. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Kirk Fordice, who is barred from seeking a third term,  
stole the show in the final weeks of the campaign when he was 
caught returning from a vacation in France with his junior high 
school sweetheart. Fordice says he will divorce his wife of 44 
years and marry the woman. 
</P>
<P>
	Virtually all the primary candidates made a point of boasting  
about their strong marriages, their happy children and their 
small-town values. 
</P>
<P>
	Musgrove, 43, beat a GOP incumbent four years ago and  
immediately locked his sights on the governor's mansion. He won the 
nomination outright Tuesday by getting more than half the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	With 82 percent of precincts reporting, Musgrove had 254,151  
votes, or 57 percent, while former state Supreme Court Justice 
Jimmy Roberts had 113,906 votes, or 26 percent. Six lesser-known 
candidates split the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	In the GOP race, Parker, 49, narrowly avoided a runoff with  
former Lt. Gov. Eddie Briggs, who lost to Musgrove in 1995. 
Parker's campaign had concentrated on school safety, while Briggs 
had emphasized his plan to eliminate the sales tax on groceries. 
</P>
<P>
	With 84 percent of precincts reporting, Parker had 70,302 votes,  
or 51 percent, and Briggs had 38,483 votes, or 28 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the other candidates were Dan Gibson, who quit his job as  
mayor of Crystal Springs and sold his antebellum home and two cars 
to raise money for his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Republican, state Rep. Charlie Williams, had just one TV  
ad, about his days as a record-setting base stealer on the 
University of Mississippi baseball team. He was the only candidate 
Fordice praised during the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Musgrove was criticized in ads for running up $200,000 in  
expenses in private state airplanes for trips over the past four 
years. He generally ignored the attacks and stuck to scripted 
speeches about his integrity and ``straight talk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other Democrats on the ballot included a white supremacist  
and a woman whose campaign was marred by her prosecution for a 
fourth drunken-driving charge. 
</P>
<P>
	In his two terms as governor, Fordice concentrated on luring  
businesses to Mississippi and revamping welfare. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
