<DOCNO> APW19990803.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Orioles' Ripken Placed Back on DL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Cal Ripken was placed on the disabled  
list Tuesday with a sore back, the second time this season the 
Baltimore Orioles' third baseman has been disabled. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, who had never been on the disabled list before this  
year, received a cortisone shot to relieve irritation in his lower 
back Tuesday. He went on the DL from April 18-May 13 with nerve 
irritation in his lower back. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a recurrence of the previous injury,'' Orioles manager  
Ray Miller said before Baltimore's game Tuesday night against the 
Oakland Athletics. ``They say the best-case scenario is he'll be 
ready in 10 days. We were so thin already we had to put him on the 
DL.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, who played in 2,632 consecutive games until stopping the  
streak last year, is hitting .335 with 15 home runs and 47 RBIs. He 
is one homer away from 400 and 32 hits shy of 3,000 in his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken returned to Baltimore on Monday for an examination and  
was put on the disabled list retroactive to Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was fine, then he went to breakfast Sunday morning and said  
he just started getting spasms in his back,'' Miller said. ``It got 
worse all day and the next day. He said he wanted to see the 
doctor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles recalled third baseman Ryan Minor from Triple-A  
Rochester to take Ripken's place. Minor was batting .256 with 21 
homers and 67 RBI in 101 games with Rochester. He was 1-for-10 in 
four games with Baltimore in July. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
