<DOCNO> APW19990803.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 12:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Air Force Chief Backs F-22 Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A delay in construction of the Air Force's  
new-generation F-22 stealth fighter, which many in Congress seek, 
could kill the $65 billion project and upset aircraft modernization 
plans of the Navy and Marine Corps, the Air Force's top officer 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Michael Ryan said he is confident that with ``better  
education'' on the F-22 and its role in a 21st-century Air Force, 
Congress can be convinced of the need to start production next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those who are knowledgeable about what we believe will be the  
threats in 15 years or so are convinced that this airplane is what 
the (U.S. military) needs,'' Ryan told reporters over breakfast. He 
said the service chiefs and U.S. commanders around the world 
support the Air Force plane. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan and F. Whitten Peters, the Air Force secretary, met Monday  
night with Rep. Jerry Lewis, a chief force behind the House vote 
last month to delete $1.8 billion from the 2000 budget that was 
earmarked to begin production of the F-22. Ryan would not discuss 
the conversation except to say he remains confident the full 
Congress will side with the Air Force and save the F-22. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm confident the airplane is not going to be canceled,'' Ryan  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis' spokesman, Jim Specht, said the California Republican  
would not disclose details of the conversation but added, ``His 
mind is still made up that this is the way to go,'' to delay the 
start of production. 
</P>
<P>
	House and Senate appropriators will meet in September to make a  
final decision on the F-22 money. The plane has more support in the 
Senate, where the chairman of the Armed Forces Committee, Sen. John 
Warner, R-Va., has said he expects a compromise to restore enough 
money to save the project. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis and others argue that although the F-22 as designed would  
give the United States the most capable fighter aircraft in the 
world for years to come, it is too expensive given other national 
priorities. They note that the fighter it would replace, the F-15E, 
already is the best in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force so far has spent close to $25 billion on research,  
development and testing of the F-22; it expects to spend another 
$40 billion to manufacture 339 of them. The prime contractor is 
Lockheed Martin Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	In the interview Tuesday, Ryan said delaying production of the  
F-22 by even one year would be tantamount to canceling the program. 
That, he said, would weaken U.S. security in the 21st century. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you take a pause ..., the airplane will then probably be  
killed,'' he said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
