<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ExciteAtHome Denies Yahoo! Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An ExciteAtHome Corp. executive denied a report  
that the company is in merger talks with Yahoo!, though he 
acknowledged the two Internet companies have talked about a 
partnership. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo!, the second-largest Web search and directory destination,  
has held discussions over the last six weeks to acquire 
ExciteAtHome, the No. 6 destination, for more than $17 billion, 
according to an article published Monday on BusinessWeek Online. 
</P>
<P>
	The story, which cited an anonymous source, said Yahoo! might  
consider buying ExciteAtHome and spinning off the AtHome high-speed 
Internet access business, known as broadband. 
</P>
<P>
	But ExciteAtHome president George Bell, speaking at a technology  
conference Tuesday, told reporters, ``There is no truth to the 
rumors about acquisition discussions,'' adding, ``We've had talks 
with Yahoo and AOL about getting on the start page of a very 
powerful broadband opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Yahoo! spokeswoman said the company does not comment on market  
rumors. 
</P>
<P>
	ExciteAtHome is discussing a partnership that would make Yahoo!,  
America Online Inc., or perhaps another Internet service company 
the initial page ExciteAt Home's customers would see when they go 
onto the Internet, Bell said. 
</P>
<P>
	ExciteAtHome was created earlier this year by the merger of  
Excite, an Internet search and directory service, and AtHome, which 
operates a network of fiber-optic cables. 
</P>
<P>
	Any deal with Yahoo!, however, would likely hurt the Excite  
business since Excite and Yahoo! are direct competitors. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
