<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mozart Won't Make Kids Smarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The notion that listening to Mozart leads to  
brainy toddlers is likely a myth, two researchers say. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's how science spreads through our culture,'' said Kenneth  
Steele, a psychology professor at Appalachian State University in 
Boone, N.C. ``There is one kind of study and everyone assumes that 
it's true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The so-called ``Mozart Effect'' holds that listening to the  
classical music of 18th century composer Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart 
spurs brain development in children under age 3. 
</P>
<P>
	The original notion came from two studies conducted at the  
University of California-Irvine in 1993 and 1995. The studies, 
conducted on college students, found an increase in 
spatial-reasoning immediately after exposure to a Mozart piano 
sonata. 
</P>
<P>
	The belief that Mozart helps one get smarter has spread  
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	In Georgia, former Gov. Zell Miller started a program to provide  
every young mother with a CD of the composer's music. And the 
National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences Foundation handed 
out free CDs of Grammy-winning classical music at hundreds of 
hospitals in May. 
</P>
<P>
	But Steele and John Bruer, who heads the McDonnell Foundation in  
St. Louis, say there's no real benefit, and that one would see the 
same results listening to any kind of music or none at all. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have tried to produce the effect all kinds of ways,''  
Steele said. ``Not only haven't we found that it is a weak effect 
and we can't make it stronger, we can't find any kind of effect at 
all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They said follow-up studies have been unable to duplicate the  
original research. Steele conducted a study that went so far as to 
follow the same procedures used to produce the effect in the 
original study. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we went back to that and still didn't get the effect,  
that cast grave doubts on the original effect and what the effect 
means,'' Steele said. ``It can't be investigated. It can't be 
researched.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steele's research is published in the July issue of the journal  
Psychological Science; Bruer's book, ``The Myth of the First Three 
Years,'' will be published next month. 
</P>
<P>
	In his study at Appalachian State, Steele's subjects showed an  
increase in reasoning when listening to contemporary composer 
Philip Glass, or not listing to anything at all. The differences 
between silence, Mozart and Glass's music were so small, Steele 
said, they lacked any statistical significance. 
</P>
<P>
	But not all scientists feel there is no value in ``extra''  
stimulation for young children. 
</P>
<P>
	John Flohr, a professor of music education at Texas' Woman's  
University in Denton, Texas, was a consultant on the project to 
hand out Grammy-winning music to new parents. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stimulus in the environment has a significant effect in early  
childhood,'' Flohr said. ``We don't know what will do what yet. But 
music could be a part of that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
