<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Says It Can't Pursue Terrorist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Even though a victim of the 1972 terrorist  
assault on the Munich Olympics held American citizenship, the FBI 
can pursue the attack's confessed planner only if Germany asks for 
help, the Justice Department said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Under current law, the FBI could open its own investigation into  
the slaying of an American abroad. But 1972 statutes allowed no 
such pursuit outside U.S. territory, and the Constitution allow no 
retroactive laws, Jon P. Jennings, acting assistant attorney 
general, said in a letter to Rep. Steve LaTourette, R-Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	The dead American was David Berger of Shaker Heights, Ohio, who  
also held Israeli citizenship. He was among nine Israelis who died 
in a bungled rescue attempt after the Palestinian terrorists killed 
two others in the Olympic village. A German policeman and five 
terrorists also were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the Munich planners, Mohammed Oudeh, who used the nom de  
guerre Abu Daoud, chronicled in a new autobiography his central 
role in planning the attack, which aimed to take Israeli 
weightlifters hostage to dramatize the Palestinians' homelessness. 
</P>
<P>
	LaTourette has tried to round up congressional support to press  
for aggressive international pursuit of Abu Daoud. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although we understand your frustration and the feelings of  
your constituents who were directly affected by the Munich tragedy, 
we are without legal authority to investigate or prosecute this 
particular international terrorist attack,'' Jennings' letter said. 
``We stand willing to help the German authorities in any way we 
can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since publication of Oudeh's book, Germany has issued an arrest  
warrant, which Palestinian officials are trying to have rescinded; 
Israel has banned Oudeh from returning to his West Bank home; and 
France has turned Oudeh away from its border. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
