<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pilots, NTSB Make More Rest Request </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pilots, airlines and even the government  
expressed exasperation today that there has been no significant 
change in rules governing work and rest periods for flight crews 
despite the rapid growth of airline travel. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet in testimony before Congress, there was little movement  
toward a solution and a basic division into two groups: the pilots 
and the National Transportation Safety Board, which want reduced 
work periods, and the Federal Aviation Administration and the 
airlines, which want pilots to get quality rest during their 
off-duty time. 
</P>
<P>
	The difficulty in reaching consensus was evident at a hearing  
before the House Transportation aviation subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	The safety board disclosed that the co-pilot involved in the  
June 1 crash of American Airlines Flight 1420 in Little Rock, Ark., 
had been awake for 16 1/2 hours and on duty more than 13 hours the day 
of the crash, but had flown slightly less than eight hours that day 
and had obtained about 9 1/2 hours of sleep the night before. 
</P>
<P>
	That is 90 minutes more sleep than required by law, but the work  
day was nearly at the limit of the 14-hour duty period prescribed 
by the American Airlines pilot contract. Eleven people, including 
the plane's captain, were killed in the crash. Work and rest 
information for the captain is still under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fatigue has never been cited as the cause of a major airline  
disaster,'' said Rep. John Duncan, R-Tenn., chairman of the 
aviation subcommittee. ``While the federal government should not 
have to wait for a major incident to review its policies, we must 
not act in a way that would unknowingly erode safety.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under existing law, the FAA says pilots cannot fly more than  
eight hours and must receive at least eight hours of rest in a 
24-hour period. 
</P>
<P>
	Pilots want the FAA to create a universal ``duty day,'' which  
would limit the amount of time they would have to participate in 
nonflying duties such as layovers or conducting preflight checks. 
They suggest continuing the eight-hour flight period and increasing 
the rest period to 10 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pilots are continuously subjected to onerous scheduling ...  
because the FAA regulations on flight and duty time are simply not 
based upon current scientific principles and are not adequate to 
prevent fatigue,'' said Capt. Duane E. Woerth, president of the Air 
Line Pilots Association. ``These rules were implemented when the 
DC-3 airplane was state of the art.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Margaret Gilligan, deputy associate administrator of regulation  
and certification for the FAA, said pilots have balked at a 
proposal that would address some of their concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, the agency proposed increasing the rest period to 10  
hours, increasing the flight time to 10 hours as well, and creating 
a duty day of no longer than 14 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 24-hour period, that would have given the airlines two more  
hours of flight time and the pilots two more hours of rest time, 
and it would have demanded that all flying be done within a 14-hour 
window. 
</P>
<P>
	``The length of time it is taking to finalize this rulemaking  
evidences the complexity of the issue and the strong concerns of 
the parties involved,'' Gilligan told the subcommittee. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 07:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Tests Anti-Missile System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An experimental Army rocket sped into the  
skies over New Mexico, pinpointed an ``enemy'' missile and smashed 
it to bits Monday more than 50 miles above the Earth, the Pentagon 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The successful test of the Theater High-Altitude Area Defense,  
or Thaad, missile was cheered by Defense Department officials as an 
important step toward developing an effective defense against 
medium-range ballistic missiles of the kind U.S. officials say are 
owned by about two dozen countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today was probably one of the watershed events in the  
technological history of our country,'' Air Force Lt. Gen. Ronald 
T. Kadish told reporters at the Pentagon in describing the Thaad 
test conducted shortly before dawn at White Sands Missile Range in 
New Mexico. He said it was only the second time the United States 
had ``basically hit a bullet with a bullet in outer space.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After six consecutive test failures for the Thaad, dating to  
1995, the missile scored its first successful intercept in June. 
The Pentagon had said it would wait until it managed three 
successful intercepts before advancing the project beyond its 
current ``demonstrative-validation'' phase of development. But 
Monday, Kadish pointedly left open the possibility of moving ahead 
after just two successes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have great confidence now ... that we are well on our way  
to proving the technology out,'' Kadish said. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics said Monday's intercept left the Pentagon far from  
proving that Thaad and its system of launchers, radars and battle 
management computers can provide reliable protection for U.S. 
forces abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's Thaad test was akin to getting a hit in slow-pitch  
softball,'' said Tom Z. Collina, an arms control specialist at the 
Union of Concerned Scientists. He said the Pentagon needs to show 
it can hit a target moving at much higher speeds than the unarmed 
Hera target missile used in Monday's experiment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hera is a modified Minuteman II missile; in May the Pentagon  
had to scrap a Thaad test because of a problem with the Hera target 
missile. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican-controlled Congress supports Pentagon development  
of missile defenses, but many critics question whether the Thaad 
can be made to work at a reasonable cost. 
</P>
<P>
	``They still have a long road to prove reliability,'' said Brian  
Hughes, director of the Taxpayers for Common Sense's national 
security reform project. ``We make the simple observation that the 
potential missiles that this would have to be deployed against in 
the real world are faster and bigger and probably would have 
multiple targets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of Congress' staunchest supporters of missile defense  
spending, Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., said Monday's success was reason 
to look for ways to accelerate the Thaad project and field it as 
soon as possible. The government so far has spent about $4 billion 
on Thaad. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a big win for missile defense and for America's  
national security,'' Weldon said. 
</P>
<P>
	At a hastily arranged Pentagon briefing, Kadish showed a  
videotape of the Thaad launch, the infrared image of the target 
missile as Thaad closed in and a blinding white explosion in outer 
space as the two missiles collided. Kadish said Thaad hit its 
target 500 seconds after it was launched. He declined to specify 
the altitude of the intercept except to say it was greater than 50 
miles above Earth. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. Gen. Paul Kern, chief military adviser to the assistant  
secretary of the Army for weapons development, said Thaad would be 
capable of hitting North Korea's No Dong ballistic missile, which 
has a range of about 800 miles. He would not discuss Thaad's 
capabilities against other missiles such as a longer-range North 
Korean missile that U.S. officials expect to be tested soon. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
