<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trial Beginns in Alabama Gay Slaying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCKFORD, Ala. (AP) -- A construction worker on trial for the  
slaying of a gay man whose body was burned atop a pile of tires did 
not deliver the fatal blows, but is responsible just the same, a 
prosecutor told jurors on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was hatred -- hatred of someone perceived to be different,''  
District Attorney Fred Thompson said during opening statements. 
``Billy Jack Gaither was a homosexual and that is the only reason 
they killed him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charles M. Butler, 21, played a key role in the Feb. 19 slaying  
of Gaither, 39, whose body was burned atop a pile of 
kerosene-soaked tires, Thompson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Butler could be sentenced to death in Alabama's electric chair  
if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	A construction worker, Butler admitted he kicked Gaither several  
times, knocking him down. But he said a friend, 25-year-old Steven 
Mullins, cut Gaither's throat and bashed him repeatedly with an ax 
handle until his skull split open. 
</P>
<P>
	Mullins has pleaded guilty to capital murder and is expected to  
testify against Butler. As part of Mullins' plea deal, prosecutors 
agreed to recommend a sentence of life without parole for him. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson accused Butler of playing a vital role by setting the  
tires afire and then burning Gaither's car to hide evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't have to be the triggerman to be guilty of capital  
murder,'' Thompson said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
