<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Mortgage Rates Go Up  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) --The rising cost of a home mortgage is expected to  
rein in the prolonged U.S. housing boom, as potential homeowners	
balk at rates that climbed above 8 percent today for the first time	
in two years. HSH Associates, a financial publisher that surveys	
lenders, said the average rate had climbed to 8.07 percent, up from	
a two-year low of 6.85 percent in September 1998. The business for	
mortgage refinancings is expected to virtually disappear due to the	
rate increase.	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Praises Welfare Gains  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- According to new figures released by President  
Clinton, the percent of Americans on welfare assistance is at a 
32-year low. ``As pleased as we are, we have to do more,'' Clinton 
told a national conference of the Welfare to Work Partnership in 
Chicago. He met with some 350 business leaders and former welfare 
recipients. Experts credit tough new rules and the strong economy 
for the reduction in welfare rolls. 

</P>
<P>
	9 States Get $55M in Heat Aid  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- President Clinton offered $55 million today to  
help low-income people in nine states pay their electricity bills 
or buy cooling equipment. He said he hoped the money would help 
encourage older people to run air conditioners without fear of high 
utility bills. Since July 19, the midsummer heat wave has killed at 
least 256, including 119 in Illinois. Joined by Mayor Richard 
Daley, Clinton thanked city workers in Chicago for helping to 
protect people from the heat. 

</P>
<P>
	US Spent $500,000 on JFK Jr. Search  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. costs in the mid-July search for the  
late John F. Kennedy Jr.'s private plane are estimated at over 
$500,000 -- not including Air Force and Navy involvement. President 
Clinton has taken responsibility for authorizing the effort. He 
based it on the Kennedy family's role ``in our national lives, and 
because of the enormous losses that they have sustained in our 
lifetimes.'' 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady's Candor Is Clarified  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton does not blame her  
husband's marital infidelity on the tumult of his childhood, her 
spokeswoman said today, despite the apparent link she drew in a 
Talk magazine article. ``She did not say the president's childhood 
in any way caused his behavior, nor does she believe that,'' 
spokeswoman Marsha Berry said. ``I think that she was basically 
stating some feelings about his childhood, but that they do not 
excuse his behavior,'' Berry said. 

</P>
<P>
	Zapruder Film Valued at $16M  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government must pay the heirs of Dallas  
dressmaker Abraham Zapruder $16 million for his 26-second film that 
captured the assassination of President Kennedy. In a 2-1 vote, 
announced by the Justice Department, arbitrators set the amount 
after the government and the Zapruder family could not agree on a 
price. The government offered $1 million; the family asked for $30 
million. In 1997, the film was declared to be the property of the 
federal government. 

</P>
<P>
	Rest Sought for Flight Crews  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pilots, airlines and regulators agreed today  
flight crews need more rest. In testimony before Congress, the 
pilots and the National Transportation Safety Board favored reduced 
work periods. The Federal Aviation Administration and the airlines 
pressed for pilots to make sure they get the proper rest during 
their off-duty time. 

</P>
<P>
	Web Searches Are Widening  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Several Internet search services, including  
ExciteAtHome and Lycos, say they are dramatically widening their 
scope to encompass more of the 800 million Web sites on the 
Internet. ExciteAtHome said it will index up to 300 million Web 
pages, or more than a third of the Internet's public sites -- up 
from just 6 percent. Lycos plans to introduce a more comprehensive 
search by the end of the year. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Up 31.35; Nasdaq Off 35.63  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks ended mixed today as a forecast of  
economic growth kept investors on edge about interest rates. The 
Dow Jones industrial average was up 31.35 to 10,677.31 after 
shifting between positive and negative for much of the day. On the 
NYSE, losers led gainers 1,876-1,122. The Nasdaq fell 35.63 to 
2,588 as tech stocks faltered. 

</P>
