<HEADLINE> Stocks End Mixed; Dow Up 31.35 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A volatile session on Wall Street ended with  
mixed results Tuesday as a forecast of continued economic growth 
kept investors on edge about interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 31.35, closing at  
10,677.31 after shifting between positive and negative territory 
for much of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
fell 5.87 to 1,322.18 and the Nasdaq composite index, dominated by 
technology stocks, fell 35.64 to 2,587.99 as Internet stocks 
faltered. 
</P>
<P>
	With Tuesday's loss, the Nasdaq is down 9.7 percent from its  
July 16 record of 2,864.48. 
</P>
<P>
	``The general tenor is one of malaise,'' said Scott Bleier,  
chief investment strategist at Prime Charter Ltd. While volume 
outpaced the sluggish trading of recent sessions, stocks pitched up 
and down in a fairly narrow range as buyers found little reason to 
return to the market. The number of stocks that slumped easily 
outnumbered those that improved. 
</P>
<P>
	Concerns that the Federal Reserve will raise rates later this  
month in an effort to cool off the economy held most stocks back. 
The Conference Board provided the latest hint that the nation's 
unbridled economic growth is continuing, announcing that its index 
of leading indicators rose 0.3 percent in June, matching its May 
increase. The index is used to forecast economic trends for the 
coming three to six months. 
</P>
<P>
	The threat of higher rates has rattled stocks and bonds in the  
past week, dragging stock indexes well below the record highs of 
mid-July. Bond prices slipped once more Tuesday, sending the yield 
on the 30-year Treasury bond rising to 6.16 percent from 6.12 
percent late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stocks are attempting to do battle within an investment  
climate that is not reacting favorably to bonds and is showing no 
concrete or consistent means of leadership,'' said Brian G. Belski, 
chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City, 
Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks, which are vulnerable to higher interest rates,  
were weighed down by other factors. 
</P>
<P>
	Rumors that Yahoo! would acquire the recently merged  
ExciteAtHome for a price greater than ExciteAtHome's $17 billion 
market value stimulated early buying. But after ExciteAtHome's 
president refuted the rumors, the company's shares ended just 7/16 
higher, at 43 3/8. Yahoo! tumbled 6 15/16 to 125 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Bill Burnham, an Internet analyst at Credit Suisse  
First Boston, said in a report that online brokerages may 
experience their first-ever decline in trading volume in the third 
quarter. Shares of ETrade fell 4 5/16 to 24 11/16 and Charles 
Schwab lost 5 9/16 to 36 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Burnham said the brokerages' troubles are due largely to recent  
weakness among Internet stocks, which have been the favorite 
investments of many online traders. 
</P>
<P>
	In a difficult market, online florist 1-800-Flowers.com wilted  
in its initial public offering. Its shares were priced at 21 and 
opened at 21 3/4, then fell back to 18 3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the Internet stocks have had a real comeuppance,''  
Bleier said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gains by Johnson &AMP; Johnson helped support the Dow. Its shares  
rose 2 1/4 to 94 3/16 after J.P. Morgan increased its growth forecast 
for the company, and gave the stock a ``buy'' rating, upgrading it 
from ``market performer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson &AMP; Johnson also benefited from investors' subtle move  
toward consumer products companies, analysts said. Those companies, 
which include Procter &AMP; Gamble, up 3 9/16 to 93 11/16, are 
perceived as a safe haven for investors because their products 
remain in demand regardless of economic conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange. Composite volume came to 885.63 million 
shares, compared to 783.75 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 2.94 to 622.40, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index fell 3.17 to 780.47. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.35 to 436.28. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.81 percent.  
European indexes were mostly lower, as Germany's DAX index fell 0.4 
percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 dropped 0.6 percent, and France's 
CAC-40 lost 0.5 percent. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
