<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Collection Hits 5th Avenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Collector Barry Halper smiled proudly as  
strollers stopped by Bergdorf Goodman's Men's Store windows on 
Fifth Avenue Tuesday to gawk at some of his baseball memorabilia. 
</P>
<P>
	Over here was Babe Ruth's luggage and polo cap, over there was  
Joe DiMaggio's jersey and jacket. All of it was mixed in with 
Bergdorf's fashionable suits and accessories. 
</P>
<P>
	Halper, probably the premier collector of baseball  
paraphernalia, is using Sotheby's to auction off much of the 
material he has assembled over the last half century. And Sotheby's 
is using Bergdorf's windows to display a portion of the items. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the volume of material, more than 100,000 pieces in  
the largest privately owned collection of memorabilia in the world, 
the auction will last a week, Sept. 23-29. The Bergdorf window 
display will be in place until Aug. 16, a sort of appetizer for the 
main course. 
</P>
<P>
	One window is dedicated to Ruth items, another for DiMaggio.  
There is an early baseball window, and another window that includes 
a turnstile from Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the store there are smaller displays for Willie Mays,  
Jackie Robinson and Pete Rose jerseys, caps and spikes. Another 
includes a picture of normally docile Lou Gehrig arguing ewith an 
umpire. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a lifetime's work,'' Halper said.  
</P>
<P>
	Still, Halper said he was not emotional about auctioning it.  
That's because about 20 percent of the collection has been 
purchased by major league baseball and will be on permanent display 
at the Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know it's there forever,'' Halper said. ``I can rest easy.''  
</P>
<P>
	Still, when it came to packing up the rest of his collection for  
Sotheby's, Halper discovered it wasn't so easy to part with some of 
his treasures. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a Ruth contract and I said, `You can't have this.'  
Then I pulled back a Gehrig contract,'' he said. ``One of my kids 
said if I kept pulling things back, it wasn't going to be much of 
an auction. So I put it all back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What he kept were the items he prized the most like personally  
signed pictures from DiMaggio and Mickey Mantle, who became close 
friends over the years. 
</P>
<P>
	And then there were the Ruth bathroom items, which Halper  
acquired from the Babe's widow. 
</P>
<P>
	``They all have the initals `GHR,' '' Halper said. ``There's a  
hand-held mirror, a shoebrush, a hairbrush and comb, a toothbrush. 
And there was the good luck charm, a nail file. I'd hold it in my 
hand when I watched Yankees games and when they were in a tight 
spot, I'd rub the initials for good luck. 
</P>
<P>
	``My wife asked if I really thought that helped.''  
</P>
<P>
	Halper just shrugged. He doesn't know, but just in case, he's  
keeping the nail file around. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
