<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sprinter Dennis Mitchell Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTE CARLO, Monaco (AP) -- Sprinter Dennis Mitchell was  
suspended for two years today for failing a drug test 16 months ago 
but will be eligible for the 2000 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Track and field's governing body said his test showed high  
levels of testosterone. But Mitchell's lawyer said today the 
sprinter has never taken testosterone or any other banned 
substance. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's clearly very disappointed and very upset,'' attorney Suja  
Thomas said from New York. ``He has always been against the use of 
drugs in track and field. This is truly a severe disappointment to 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A call to Mitchell's home in Florida was answered by his wife,  
who said she expected to hear from him shortly. Mitchell ran Monday 
in Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF arbitration panel concluded that Mitchell, the  
100-meter bronze medalist in the 1992 Olympics and current U.S. 
champion, was ``guilty of a doping offense'' and had no right of 
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``This decision is final and binding,'' said Giorgio Reineri, a  
spokesman for the International Amateur Athletic Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	Reineri said he did not consider this a light punishment.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is the rule for everybody,'' he said. ``According to our  
constitution, a ban starts the day after the positive doping 
test.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF said Mitchell will be ineligible from April 1, 1998,  
until March 31, 2000. Any performances by Mitchell during that 
period are ``null and void.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 33-year-old sprinter would be able to run in the Sydney  
Games, which begin in September 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas said that was no consolation for Mitchell.  
</P>
<P>
	``This about Dennis Mitchell and he is an exemplary person and  
secondarily, he is an athlete,'' Thomas said. ``He doesn't want 
this perception and he wants to compete. He should compete because 
he hasn't done anything wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dennis knows in his heart that he didn't take any testosterone  
or any other prohibited substance,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	A three-member panel of USA Track and Field cleared Mitchell in  
December. The USATF did not release the details of Mitchell's 
defense or the reasons for its decision to exonerate him. 
</P>
<P>
	But London's Daily Telegraph reported this year that Mitchell  
won his case on grounds that his positive result stemmed from 
having sex four times and drinking five bottles of beer the night 
before the test. 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF arbitrators met July 24-25. The organization said today  
the USATF decision in December was ``erroneous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas said Mitchell's case was ``not a manner of sex and beer  
as people have reported.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's much more complicated than that,'' she said. ``A  
combination of factors, stress and nonbanned substances, caused a 
temporary rise in his T-E level on one day in his entire career. 
That's what this case is all about. It's very unfortuante it has 
come to this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Mitchell ran the 100 in 10.09 seconds in Malmo,  
Sweden. He led Maurice Greene for the first 50 meters before 
finishing second to Greene. 
</P>
<P>
	His best time this season is 10.02 with three other Americans  
having run faster. He has also ran a wind-assisted time of 9.97 
this season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
