<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Economic Indicators Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A widely-watched indicator of future economic  
activity rose 0.3 in June, chalking up gains in eight out of the 
past nine months and signaling that the U.S. economy could be in 
its longest expansion ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board, a private New York-based economic research  
group, reported today that its index of leading indicators stood at 
107.7 in June, up from 107.4 in May. The index also rose by the 
same amount in May. The last decline, in April, was 0.1. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Boldin, director of business cycle research at The  
Conference Board, said that while the economic expansion is 
``firmly on track,'' concerns that the Federal Reserve will raise 
interest rates could roil financial markets and create some 
uncertainty. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board's index of current economic activity rose  
by 0.4 in June, while its lagging index decreased by 0.4 1/8pomts. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the ten indicators that make up the leading index rose  
in June. The most significant increases came in manufacturers' new 
orders of consumer goods and materials, money supply, and the 
difference between long-term and short-term interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	During the six months ended June 30, the leading index rose 1.2  
pointw and seven of the 10 components advanced, the Conference 
Board said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several components of the leading indicators index gave details  
about the growing economy. Manufacturers took in $166.4 million of 
new orders in June, up from $162.3 million in May. Money supply 
rose to $3.962 billion from $3.947 billion. And the difference, or 
spread, between the yield on 10-year Treasury bonds and the 
overnight Federal Reserve lending rate rose to 1.14 percent from 
0.80 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	However, in a sign that the labor market may not be heating up  
enough to push wages higher, the average number of hours worked per 
week by production workers was 41.7, unchanged from May. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall index is calculated from a base of 100, set in 1992.  
</P>
<P>
	The stock and bond markets had little immediate reaction to the  
report. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
