<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 65 As Nasdaq Climbs 7 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened higher today as takeover  
speculation lifted Internet stocks and buyers returned cautiously 
to a battered market, hoping to find bargain stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 65.22 at 10,711.18. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher, although their gains  
were slim. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 5.16 at 1,333.21, 
and the Nasdaq composite index was up 7.77 at 2,631.40. 
</P>
<P>
	A report that ExciteAtHome may be acquired by Yahoo! for a price  
greater than ExciteAtHome's $17 billion market value stimulated 
some buying in Internet and telecommunications companies. 
ExciteAtHome rose 4 41/64 to 47 37/64, while Yahoo! slipped 9/16 to 
131 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the broader market, concerns about higher interest rates  
continue to hold most stocks lower amid light volume. Traders have 
become increasingly convinced in the past week that the Federal 
Reserve will raise rates later this month in an effort to cool off 
the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	This morning, the Conference Board provided that latest hint  
that the nation's unbridled economic growth is continuing. The 
private New York-based economic research group said its index of 
leading indicators rose 0.3 percent in June, matching its May 
increase. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey measures economic trends for the coming three to six  
months, providing analysts with the latest suggestion that 
continued growth will encourage the Fed to raise interest rates to 
prevent inflation from encroaching on the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 81.1 million shares, 
ahead of Monday's early pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 1.54 at 626.88, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 2.83 at 787.47. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.81 percent.  
European indexes were slightly lower. Germany's DAX index was down 
0.5 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.5 percent, and France's 
CAC-40 was down 0.2 percent in afternoon trading. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
