<HEADLINE> Couple Claims 'Birth Night' Prizes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOWELL, Mass. (AP) -- Four days after attending a ``Birth Night''  
promotion at a Lowell Spinners baseball game, a woman has delivered 
a baby boy and claimed a free year's supply of diapers. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul John Armstrong, who weighed 8 pounds, 4 ounces and was 20 3/4  
inches long, was born to Paul and Lisa Armstrong of Tyngsboro at 
4:01 p.m. Monday. He is their second child; Kaitlyn is 4. 
</P>
<P>
	Lisa Armstrong, 32, was due last Thursday, the date of the  
promotion. 
</P>
<P>
	``The baby was healthy and the mom's doing great as well,'' said  
Armstrong, reporting his wife was only in hard labor for about an 
hour. ``Lisa did great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Class A affiliate of the Boston Red Sox invited expectant  
mothers and their partners to Thursday night's game and offered 
prizes to the family that expanded first. It was not necessary for 
the baby to be born during the game to win. 
</P>
<P>
	A sellout crowd cheered the couples on, helping out with  
breathing exercises and taking part in scoreboard contests to name 
the baby and guess the time of delivery. Rather than name the baby 
after one of the former Spinners players, as the team 
lightheartedly suggested, the parents decided to name him after his 
father. 
</P>
<P>
	``We already had the names picked before,'' Armstrong said.  
  	   	
</P>
