<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New York Opera Adds Sound System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York City Opera will become the first  
major American company to employ an electronic sound system like 
those used in cinemas and Broadway theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	The system will be installed in the New York State Theater, home  
of the City Opera and the New York City Ballet, on an experimental 
basis in time for the Sept. 11 opening of the City Opera's fall 
season with Puccini's ``Madama Butterfly,'' the companies' 
officials said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Opera companies occasionally use sound systems to amplify spoken  
dialogue, such as in Mozart's ``Magic Flute.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the 35-year-old State Theater, designed for dance, has poor  
acoustics for music, especially the singing voice. The sound system 
will feature stationary microphones and more than 100 inconspicuous 
speakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We view it as electronic architecture,'' said Martin  
Oppenheimer, head of the board that oversees the City Opera and the 
City Ballet. 
</P>
<P>
	The sound system will enhance the acoustics of the auditorium  
but will not amplify voices, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Beverly Sills, once a leading soprano and now chairman of  
Lincoln Center, endorsed the system but said she hoped it would be 
temporary. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
