<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs Campaign Finance Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House committee approved four competing  
campaign finance bills Monday, setting the stage for debate and 
votes in September. 
</P>
<P>
	But committee Democrats warned Republicans against structuring  
floor debate to undermine the vote on a bill similar to one that 
passed the House last year with support from nearly the entire 
Democratic caucus. 
</P>
<P>
	``If that ... is to be proposed, I will be compelled and will  
urge all of my colleagues to vote against it,'' Rep. Steny Hoyer of 
Maryland, senior Democrat on the House Administration Committee, 
said at the hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Another panel, the House Rules Committee, which decides what  
bills get to the floor, is to vote thi+s week on procedures for 
that debate. House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has promised to 
allow votes on the issue next month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate also plans to debate campaign finance legislation by  
October. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the proposals approved Monday combine elements of  
measures the House considered during last year's campaign finance 
debate. Other bills are identical to those offered last summer. The 
four bills would: 
</P>
<P>
	--Crack down on election activities by foreign nationals and  
improve and expand Federal Elections Commission operations. It is 
sponsored by Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., chairman of the House 
Administration Committee, which approved it by voice vote. 
</P>
<P>
	--Remove limits on campaign contributions to federal elections,  
eliminate taxpayer financing of presidential election campaigns and 
require certain disclosures. Rep. John Doolittle, R-Calif., is the 
sponsor, and the bill was approved by a show of hands. 
</P>
<P>
	--Impose a federal ban on soft money, unlimited and unregulated  
donations to political parties to finance party activities. It also 
would index contribution limits to inflation and expand disclosure 
requirements. Sponsored by Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., it was 
approved by voice vote. The House rejected this bill last year. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ban soft money at the federal and state levels, regulate issue  
advertising and create a commission to study future reforms. 
Sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Marty Meehan, 
D-Mass., the bill was approved by a 6-3 vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the House passed the Shays-Meehan bill, 252-179. But  
Senate gridlock kept that chamber from voting on the issue as well. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bills are H.R. 2668; H.R. 1922; H.R. 1867 and H.R. 417.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
