<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgage Rates Rise Above 8 Percent / National Mortgage Survey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mortgage rates have crept above 8 percent for  
the first time in two years, causing predictions of a slowdown in 
the U.S. housing boom and mortgage refinancings that could ripple 
throughout the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The first signs of a letup in demand are expected to appear in  
the thriving business for home construction and eventually spread 
into the manufacturing and retail sectors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Construction will be the first area to be impacted, followed  
by sales of household goods,'' said Mark Vitner, an economist at 
First Union Capital Markets Group in Charlotte, N.C. He predicted a 
10 percent to 20 percent dropoff in the number of home sales during 
the fall buying season. 
</P>
<P>
	Vitner said the expected ripple effect is significant because  
home construction and household goods are the only U.S. 
manufacturing sectors that have experienced growth in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of existing single-family homes jumped 10.6 percent to a  
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.53 million units in June, the 
highest level ever, according to the National Association of 
Realtors. Comparable increases were seen across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	June's performance, however, followed two consecutive months of  
sales declines and exceeded many analysts' expectations. Housing 
experts said the increase was likely caused by home buyers who 
jumped into the market as mortgage rates began to accelerate toward 
8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The first consumers to feel the pinch will be first-time  
homebuyers, said Ed Phillips, executive vice president of the 
Homebuilders Association of Georgia. ``It will impact the people 
that need housing the most, the worst.'' 
</P>
<P>
	HSH Associates, a financial publisher that surveys mortgage  
lenders, said Tuesday the average lending rate had climbed to 8.07 
percent, up from a two-year low of 6.85 percent in September 1998. 
The weekly survey by mortgage company Freddie Mac, released 
Thursday, is expected to show a similar level. 
</P>
<P>
	The jump to an 8 percent mortgage rate has stemmed primarily  
from a similar rise in the interest rates of 10-year U.S. Treasury 
bonds. The two rates generally mirror one anothers' movements 
because most mortgages are resold as investment products known as 
mortgage-backed securities, which compete for investment dollars 
with various types of bonds, including the 10-year Treasury. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury bond rates have climbed on fears that inflation is on  
the rise, and that the Federal Reserve Bank will increase interest 
rates across the board to stem a surge in the prices of consumer 
goods. Higher interest rates tend to reduce consumer spending, and, 
consequently, the costs of goods. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, some in the home buying and building businesses  
believe too much is being made of the 8 percent benchmark. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Lurie, with the Southern Arizona Home Builders Association  
in Tucson, Ariz., said the higher mortgage rates will undoubtedly 
discourage potential home buyers who are struggling to put the 
financing together. 
</P>
<P>
	But those who have benefitted from the prolonged strength of the  
domestic economy shouldn't be deterred, he said. ``We've seen seven 
strong economic years. Many people have made some money, and now 
they can build a house,'' Lurie said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 8 percent figure is more of a psychological benchmark than  
an economic one because home buyers had grown accustomed to 
relatively low mortgage rates, said Adrian Skiles, a mortgage 
broker with Atlanta Mortgage Group. Ten years ago, he recalled, 
mortgage rates were in the double digits. 
</P>
<P>
	Like many metropolitan areas around the country, Atlanta has  
seen its housing market boom throughout the 1990s. Skiles said the 
growth is expected to continue because people relocating to the 
area for new jobs will need to buy a house regardless of rising 
mortgage rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The business for mortgage refinancings, however, is expected to  
virtually disappear in the wake of the rate increase. Refinancing 
is an option for current homeowners who want to reduce their 
mortgage payments. But experts said the cost and effort to 
refinance won't be worth it if the rates continue to rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Others see a potential silver lining to the rate increase.  
</P>
<P>
	``The housing market has been extremely strong, and this could  
put a brake on the rising cost of housing,'' said Jeremy Siegel, a 
professor of finance at the Wharton School, adding that an easing 
demand for new homes will push prices down. 
</P>
<P>
	``This goes hand in hand with (Federal Reserve Chairman) Alan  
Greenspan's goal of slowing the economy.'' 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 17:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ginats' Sehorn Has Hamstring Tear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Jason Sehorn's attempt to return to the New  
York Giants' lineup is going to be delayed about another 10 days 
because of a torn hamstring in his left leg. 
</P>
<P>
	The cornerback who missed all of last season with a serious knee  
injury had the tear detected Monday night after undergoing an MRI 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	It is almost certain that Sehorn will miss the Giants preseason  
opener at Minnesota on Aug. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a few injuries, and the hamstring is one of them,  
you can't push it,'' Giants coach Jim Fassel said Tuesday after 
practice at the University at Albany. ``You have to let it go. Some 
come back a little quicker, some are a little longer, but you 
cannot push it. If you do it will keep going and going and will 
never clear up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the NFL's top cover cornerbacks, Sehorn injured the  
hamstring working out about three weeks before training camp 
opened. He didn't think it was serious then, but it cramped about a 
week before camp opened. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been some reports that the Giants were concerned that  
Sehorn did not work out with the team while rehabilitating his 
right knee, which he hurt in a preseason game against the Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	Fassel downplayed that report, saying he personally knows Marv  
Marinovich and Kevin McNair, the two men Sehorn hired to get him 
back into shape. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew he was going to be pushed,'' Fassel said. ``He didn't  
spend as much time as he could have on stretching. Jason loves to 
work out and he pushed it hard and pulled a hamstring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sehorn said his trainers reminded him to stretch, but he didn't.  
</P>
<P>
	``At the same time I worked my butt off, I put on a lot of  
muscle,'' Sehorn said. ``The amount of time I put into stretching 
compared to the time I put in working out wasn't there. You put on 
18 pounds, you need to stretch a little bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Sehorn still sidelined, Conrad Hamilton and Phillippi  
Sparks continue to start at cornerback. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
