<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. City Claims School Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COMPTON, Calif. (AP) -- The Compton mayor declared a state of  
emergency Tuesday over a spate of school arson fires and began 
recruiting citizens to form campus patrols, a move hotly opposed by 
school officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``The state of California is responsible for these fires even if  
they haven't set them themselves,'' Mayor Omar Bradley told a news 
conference. ``We intend to make sure when the state leaves we still 
have schools to administer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The patrol plan was viewed cautiously by the Compton Unified  
School District, which was taken over by the state in 1993 as it 
teetered near bankruptcy and has been the object of a long battle 
by local officials to regain control. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is nobody will be allowed on our campus,''  
said district spokesman Fausto Capobianco. ``It would be in 
violation of state law and it would create confusion on our 
campuses. Who is to tell if one of these people is the perpetrator 
himself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eight arson fires this year have caused $1.7 million in damage  
at six facilities in the 28,000-student, 40-school district. Six 
fires damaged classrooms; two others were set in unoccupied 
buildings. No one has been hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	The district had already posted a $10,000 reward, and the city  
added another $10,000 Tuesday. Fire and police officials would say 
little about the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of the nature of the fires and the location of the  
fires we believe it's more than a firebug at this time,'' Fire 
Chief Milfred Fonza said without elaboration. 
</P>
<P>
	The city plan calls for citizen volunteers to patrol schools 24  
hours a day if possible. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have citizens who are going to be standing out  
there documenting everybody who goes into the schools and who goes 
out of the schools,'' the mayor said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20 people signed up as volunteers after the City Council  
approved the emergency declaration on a 4-0 vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``I teach in the district and I don't want to see the schools  
burn down,'' said Carl Robinson, 64, offering to watch schools for 
six hours a week. 
</P>
<P>
	Students were skeptical.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like the fact that anyone can come in and say they're  
a sentinel and patrol,'' said Leon Mitchell, 17, attending summer 
school at Compton High. 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow student Katrina Scarks, 17, said she was shocked about a  
fire last week on the campus but also dismissed the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	``They aren't going to accomplish anything,'' Scarks said.  
``Some kids leave at a certain time and come here at different 
times. They won't know who is coming and going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Capobianco said the district has already increased patrols and  
is spending $3.5 million on installing fire and intruder alarms at 
its schools, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
