<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGraw, Dixie Chicks Get CMA Nods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Touring partners Tim McGraw and the  
Dixie Chicks broke into country music's most elite circle on 
Tuesday, earning nominations for best entertainer from the Country 
Music Association. 
</P>
<P>
	The other nominees in the best entertainer category announced in  
the courtyard of the Grand Ole Opry House were Garth Brooks, George 
Strait and Shania Twain. 
</P>
<P>
	Winners will be revealed Sept. 22 during an awards ceremony  
broadcast live by CBS. Singer Vince Gill will host. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a cool deal,'' McGraw said. ``Our shows together have  
been going great and selling out every night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The McGraw-Dixie Chicks tour ends Sunday in Birmingham, Ala.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not surprised they've done so well, and I'm certainly  
pleased with my nominations,'' McGraw said. ``These nominations are 
a gauge of how your career is going, so I'm always nervous about 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGraw also was nominated for best male vocalist, album (``A  
Place in the Sun''), single (``Please Remember Me'') and music 
video (``Just to Hear You Say That You Love Me''). He'll get two 
trophies if he wins the best album or single awards, because he 
also produced the album and the song. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill, who has won the most awards (17) in CMA history, got five  
nominations: best male vocalist, album (``The Key''), song (``If 
You Ever Have Forever in Mind'') and two nods for best vocal event, 
for duets with Patty Loveless and Sara Evans. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining McGraw and Gill in the best male vocalist category were  
Strait, Alan Jackson and Steve Wariner. 
</P>
<P>
	Best female vocalist nominees were Ms. Twain, Faith Hill,  
Martina McBride, Jo Dee Messina and Trisha Yearwood. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dixie Chicks -- Natalie Maines and sisters Martie Siedel and  
Emily Erwin Robison -- also picked up nominations for best album and 
single for ``Wide Open Spaces. They'll compete with Alabama, 
Diamond Rio, Lonestar and The Wilkinsons for best vocal group. 
</P>
<P>
	The best entertainer nomination stunned the group, Ms. Robison  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty surprising to me that we would be nominated for  
that award so soon,'' she said. ``It's thrilling that the industry 
has enough faith in us to recognize us in this category.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The late country music singer Roger Miller was nominated for  
best song for his 1966 hit ``Husbands and Wives,'' which was 
returned to the charts by Brooks &AMP; Dunn. 
</P>
<P>
	George Jones continued his comeback from a near-fatal car wreck  
with a nomination for best single for ``Choices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing!'' Jones said. ``It's a miracle.''  
</P>
<P>
	Pop singer Linda Ronstadt was nominated for best vocal event  
along with Dolly Parton and Emmylou Harris for their ``Trio II'' 
album. Ms. Parton will be inducted into the Country Music Hall of 
Fame during the awards show, along with the late singers Conway 
Twitty and Johnny Bond. 
</P>
<P>
	About 6,800 workers in the country music industry nominate and  
vote for CMA winners. The awards began in 1967. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
