<HEADLINE> Kosovo Dad Has Job Interview at UPS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The family of the first baby born to Kosovo  
refugees brought to the United States might soon have steady 
income. 
</P>
<P>
	Naim Karaliju, 28, father of baby Amerikan, had complained that  
the family faced a destitute life because of unfulfilled promises 
of aid. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Karaliju is being considered for a job loading and  
unloading trucks at a United Parcel Service center in Dallas, 
company spokeswoman Peggy Gardner said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is in the interview process with us,'' she said. ``He has  
to meet the qualifications.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amerikan was born in May, days after his mother, Lebibe  
Karaliju, arrived at Fort Dix, N.J., on a refugee flight from 
Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	Anne Marie Weiss, one of a group of volunteers helping the  
family, said Karaliju is thrilled by the prospect of working at 
UPS. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great job,'' she said. ``He's very grateful.''  
</P>
<P>
	She said it has been difficult for refugees living in Dallas to  
find work because they have no transportation and speak limited 
English. 
</P>
<P>
	Refugee advocates also claimed that Refugee Services of North  
Texas, which gets federal funding, failed to provide the family 
with adequate housing, furniture, food and clothing. 
</P>
<P>
	Chip Corcoran, the executive director of Refugee Services, has  
said his agency has provided the family with quality housing and 
helped 11 of the 24 refugees in the extended Karaliju family get 
jobs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
