<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 9 States Get $55M for Power Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- President Clinton offered $55 million Tuesday to  
help low-income people in nine states pay their electricity bills 
or buy cooling equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he hoped the money would help encourage older people to  
run air conditioners during the withering heat wave without fear of 
high utility bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Joined by Mayor Richard Daley, the president greeted workers  
from the Chicago Housing Authority and other municipal agencies, 
many of whom went door-to-door in the city's high-rise apartment 
buildings to check on elderly people and get them to cooling 
centers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came here mostly to just say thank you,'' Clinton told about  
200 people gathered in a gymnasium at a local park. ``You've done a 
great job, and I am profoundly grateful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Illinois had the highest number of heat-related deaths, with  
officials reporting 119 deaths since July 19. Missouri has reported 
51 deaths. Both states received a share of the money Clinton 
announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope it will be enough,'' Clinton said. ``We probably  
haven't seen the last of the heat for the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he knew many victims of the ``blast-furnace heat'' were  
older people who sat at home with their fans or air conditioners 
off, worried that they couldn't pay their electric bills with their 
fixed incomes. 
</P>
<P>
	He urged the elderly to take advantage of the money being  
offered under the Low Income Home Energy Assistance Program, either 
by seeking help with their utility bills or accepting free fans and 
window-unit air conditioners. 
</P>
<P>
	``Send for something to keep you alive,'' Clinton said. ``People  
should never have to worry in this country about risking their 
lives because they can't pay their power bills.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the LIHEAP grants Clinton announced Tuesday, Illinois will  
get $15.9 million, Kentucky $7.7 million, Missouri $7.6 million, 
Indiana $7.1 million, Wisconsin $4.4 million, Iowa $3.4 million, 
Kansas $3.3 million, Minnesota $3 million and Nebraska $2.1 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooler temperatures brought some relief Monday to the scorching  
heat that has struck much of the Midwest and East, but the death 
toll kept rising. 
</P>
<P>
	The nationwide death toll attributed to the heat since July 19  
was 256 Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
