<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 10:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Compromising on Tax Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional Republicans are heading toward a  
tax cut compromise that grants more than $100 billion in relief 
from the marriage penalty over the next decade and eliminates 
estate taxes, according to GOP sources familiar with the 
discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	These sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said  
negotiators appear unlikely to approve any reduction in the 
corporate capital-gains tax. But they are hoping to leave room in 
their $792 billion measure for a reduction in the capital-gains tax 
rate for individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	These officials provided no precise details, and cautioned that  
these tentative decisions could change. They spoke as senior 
Republican lawmakers continued marathon negotiating sessions in a 
room on the Capitol's first floor. The group met until after 1 
a.m., picked up again at midmorning and hope to finish their work 
by midnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Eager for a veto showdown with President Clinton, Republicans  
intend to pass the resulting measure through the House and Senate 
by week's end. The legislation wouldn't be sent to the White House 
until Congress returns to the Capitol from its long August break, 
and in the meantime, rank-and-file Republicans would spend their 
break preaching the virtue of tax cuts in appearances around their 
districts. 
</P>
<P>
	At his weekly news conference with reporters, House Majority  
Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said, ``We do not give up on the 
possibility that he (Clinton) will sign (tax cuts) but if he vetoes 
them we think he'll find he's disappointed the American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, he added, ``is a man who will disappoint everyone in  
his life except his pollster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats say the GOP tax cut is too large and would shortchange  
Social Security, Medicare and other programs. They also say that 
because it is based on anticipated budget surpluses, it could 
threaten the nation's economy if those surpluses fail to 
materialize. 
</P>
<P>
	As an alternative, Democrats propose a smaller tax cut, and  
putting more money aside for Medicare and other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	On the marriage penalty, officials said negotiators were headed  
toward adoption of a provision patterned after the one contained in 
the Senate-passed bill. Like the House bill, it would slowly raise 
the standard deduction for couples until it was double that of the 
limit set for individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, though, it would allow couples to file single  
returns on a combined form, a step that would allow many to lower 
their taxes. The estimated cost of this provision alone was $112 
billion over 10 years as it cleared the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	On capital-gains taxes, the House included a cut in the  
corporate rate, but the Senate did not. 
</P>
<P>
	The House also approved a cut in the personal capital-gains tax  
rate, but the Senate proposed only excluding the first $1,000 of 
gain from the tax. Officials said the House approach was the 
preferred one among negotiators. 
</P>
<P>
	The House measure proposed phasing out the estate tax after  
2008. There was no word on the schedule that negotiators were 
likely to adopt. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no reported decision on how to craft the centerpiece  
of the measure, broad-based tax relief, either through 
across-the-board rate reductions, as the House passed, or by 
cutting the lowest tax rate and widening the bracket, as the Senate 
voted. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal-making moved on a track parallel to the political  
struggle, as each side sought to emphasize the divisions in 
Congress over how best to use projected federal surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. President ... please reconsider your staunch opposition to  
giving the people their money back,'' Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, 
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, said Monday at a 
brief, ceremonial meeting of House and Senate negotiators on the 
tax bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``Please resist the temptation to spend this budget surplus on  
more government programs. We don't need full-time government and 
part-time families, we need part-time government and full-time 
families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That drew a polite retort from Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,  
D-N.Y., who asked Archer whether he favored a ``part-time Marine 
Corps or a part-time Federal Bureau of Investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The projections of federal surpluses are ``deceptive,'' Moynihan  
said. If Republicans insist on their course, ``we will see a large 
and unanticipated decrease in government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Archer and Moynihan articulated opposing views at a brief  
evening meeting of members of the House and Senate who were 
formally appointed to negotiate a compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	The session was purely ceremonial. The real work had already  
begun behind closed doors, and it involved only Republicans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
