<DOCNO> APW19990803.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 13:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Baseball Gets Silver Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- They came to the Pan American Games as  
the first professional baseball players to represent their country 
in international competition. What many of the U.S. minors leaguers 
got was a wordly experience they won't forget. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't trade it for anything,'' third baseman Jason  
Hardtke said. 
</P>
<P>
	Drums beating and horns blaring in the stands. Fans and players  
alike singing in the seats and dugouts. And often passionate 
celebrations by players, especially the Cubans, during the course 
of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	There was also the intense pressure to represent their country  
in tournament play, where one bad inning -- even one bad pitch -- 
could have sent them home. It was a flavor of baseball that most 
American players never get to sample. 
</P>
<P>
	The strike zone was lower and rules interpretations were  
different, often leading to lengthy arguments. One by Canadian 
manager Ernie Whitt held up the opener with the United States for 
30 mintutes. An irate Whitt wrote his protest long-hand on a piece 
of paper in the dugout before it was rejected by a committee 
meeting under the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardtke and a quickly assembled group of players not on 40-man  
rosters qualified their country for the 2000 Olympics by making the 
finals of the nine-team tournament. What they could not do was win 
a gold medal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just came up short,'' Hardtke said.  
</P>
<P>
	Cuba lost two games in the preliminaries, but then the world  
champions put aside incessant talk of defection -- one of their 
relievers did leave the team and appears headed for Miami -- and 
played like the best team there is outside the major leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubans played with passion. And they showed their anger.  
</P>
<P>
	When a protester ran onto the field with a ``Human Right First''  
sign in the ninth inning of their tense 3-2 semifinal win over 
Canada, the Cubans responded vehemently, chasing the man around the 
field and then knocking him down so authorities could take him 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, their delegation accosted the same man on a downtown  
Winnipeg street. 
</P>
<P>
	Their emotions were flowing as well when they wrapped up a 5-1  
victory over the United States in the finals. They came to the stop 
of their dugout in the final innings, unfurling flags and dancing 
to the beat of the drums played by their fans in the grandstands. 
</P>
<P>
	Count U.S. manager Buddy Bell as one who enjoyed the experience,  
despite the disappointment of not getting the gold 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of differences we had to overcome,'' Bell  
said. ``We had to put a team together in two or three weeks and 
that was a tough task. We came together as well as we could and 
maybe better than anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we've done is extremely acceptable. I hope these guys get  
the chance to compete in the Olympics down the road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Everyone predicted a United States-Cuba final, although Canada  
emerged from the tournament with the best record at 6-1, with only 
a bronze medal to show for it. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States lost to Canada in the opening game and then  
won five straight, beating Panama and Mexico in the 
single-elimination quarterfinals and semis before losing to a Cuban 
team the Americans beat 10-5 in the round-robin. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubans, who form a reception line in front of the dugout  
after every home run, featured many of the same players who split a 
pair of exhibition games with the Baltimore Orioles earlier this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our guys have never been under this kind of pressure. Ever. In  
that regard, I think that will go a long way toward helping their 
personal development,'' Bell said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have bull's-eyes on our chest because of who we are and the  
kind of baseball we play. But we were not the favored team in this 
tournament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First baseman Craig Paquette, who came to the Pan Am Games as a  
player for the Mets' Triple-A team at Norfolk, was traded during 
his stay in Winnipeg. He's now headed back to the big leagues with 
the St. Louis Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Like most players on the U.S. squad, he'd love to play in  
Sydney. But he'd rather be in the big leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing in the majors is how you take care of your family,''  
Paquette said. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team that heads to Australia in September 2000 will  
likely have plenty of new faces. You can bet they'll be pros. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's getting more that the public wants to see the  
best athletes, amateur or professional,'' said Pat Gillick, who 
headed the committee that picked the U.S. team from an original 
pool of 270-some players. 
</P>
<P>
	``There might be some point where you have both pros and  
amateurs. In this case we felt this was a qualifying tournament for 
the Olympics and we just felt we should go with all 
professionals.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 07:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mystics 75, Shock 70 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Nikki McCray rebounded from an early  
injury to score 14 second-half points to help lead the Washington 
Mystics to a 75-70 victory over the Detroit Shock in the WNBA on 
Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The All-Star guard dislocated her left ring finger early in the  
game, but returned for the second half to help her team stop a 
four-game losing streak. Chamique Holdsclaw led the Mystics (7-17) 
with 23 points and seven rebounds, and Murriel Page added 11 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	Jen Azzi led Detroit (10-13) with a season-high 22 points, but  
it wasn't enough to keep the Shock from losing their fifth 
straight. 
</P>
<P>
	The game was Washington's first trip to the Palace since its  
83-78 double-overtime victory July 10. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mystics got three 3-pointers from Monica Maxwell to take a  
41-35 lead into halftime. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit tied the game at 45 on Val Whiting's free throw with  
15:19 left, but Washington stalled the Shock's comeback by scoring 
the next four points. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mystics maintained a lead between two and six points, as the  
Shock could not get the defensive stops they needed to get even. 
</P>
<P>
	McCray appeared to clinch the game by scoring five straight  
points to make it 71-63 with 1:09 to play. 
</P>
<P>
	But Azzi answered with two 3-pointers, and Holdsclaw missed two  
free throws to give Detroit another chance. 
</P>
<P>
	Val Whiting made it 73-70 when she made one of two of free  
throws with 34 seconds left, with the second one going out of 
bounds off McCray. 
</P>
<P>
	That gave Detroit a chance to tie, but Claudia Maria Das Neves  
missed two NBA-length 3-pointers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 20:06:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Braves' Perez, Cox Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Atlanta Braves catcher Eddie Perez said Tuesday  
he is upset and disappointed with a four-game suspension and $1,000 
fine for his role in a brawl with Philadelphia and will appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Bobby Cox drew a two-game suspension, but won't appeal  
and will sit out games in Pittsburgh on Wednesday and Thursday. Pat 
Corrales will manage in his absence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to have to sit sometime, I might as well sit here,''  
Cox said. ``What are you going to do?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cox clearly was unhappy with the suspension, saying he returned  
to the field only to ``restore the peace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then, taking a verbal jab at Mets manager Bobby Valentine, said,  
``I don't think it's the same thing as coming back and sitting on 
the bench in disguise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cox, who was ejected for the eighth time this season, also was  
fined $5,000. Perez was fined $1,000. Braves pitcher John Smoltz, 
who also was ejected, was fined $2,500 but was not suspended. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez, 0-for-1 with two walks in a 7-1 loss Tuesday at  
Pittsburgh, was especially upset that no Phillies were suspended. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody (from the Phillies) gets fined or suspended,'' he said.  
``That's ridiculous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fight began after Phillies pitcher Paul Byrd hit Perez in  
third inning Friday night, the second time in less than a week that 
Byrd hit his former teammate with a pitch. Byrd leads the majors 
with 13 hit batters. 
</P>
<P>
	The following inning, the pair exchanged words when Byrd came to  
the plate and Perez threw a punch, setting off a brawl. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox had been ejected the previous inning for arguing a  
double-play call and was suspended for returning to the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz was ejected by plate umpire Jerry Meals in the fourth  
after hitting Alex Arias with a pitch. However, Smoltz was not 
suspended, apparently after arguing he should have been warned 
first by Meals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 20:06:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
