<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Pilots Return to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Pilots at the French airline AOM returned to work  
Tuesday, ending a four-day strike that left thousands of tourists 
stranded in France, the Caribbean and several Pacific locations. 
</P>
<P>
	Jean-Marc Jamaillac, managing director of AOM, or Air Outre Mer,  
said on French radio that the strike had been suspended but 
provided no details of the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	AOM pilots walked off the job Friday to support their demands  
for higher pay. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline canceled all but one of its long-distance flights  
and 30 percent of its medium-range flights Monday, including those 
on domestic and European routes. Some charter flights also were 
scrapped. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of flights bound for the Caribbean, the Pacific and  
southern Europe were canceled, disappointing thousands of tourists 
hoping to start their summer vacations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
