<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybeans Soar on Outlook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Corn and soybean futures soared early today on  
the Chicago Board of Trade after the government sharply lowered 
crop conditions in major growing states. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors ignored forecasts for beneficial showers to fall in  
the next 10 days over major growing areas as they digested the U.S. 
Agriculture Department's weekly crop update, which showed 
conditions worsened in Illinois and Indiana in the past week under 
hot, dry weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Crops in Ohio and eastern states also were suffering under  
severe drought conditions. The unexpected turn in weather during a 
growing season that has generally been beneficial to crop 
development now has analysts revising downward their fall 
production figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures retreated after the government reported an  
improvement in spring wheat conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 3/4 cents to $2.98 a bushel;  
December corn rose 7 1/2 cents to $2.34 a bushel; December oats rose 3/4 
cent to $1.19 a bushel; November soybeans rose 13 3/4 cents to $4.77 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while pork futures rose strongly. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell .20 cent to 64.50 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .20 cent to 76.62 cent s a pound; August lean 
hogs rose .10 cent to 50.05 cents a pound; August pork bellies rose 
4.50 cents to 59.62 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
