<DOCNO> APW19990803.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 07:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cops Questioned on DuBose's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Civil rights activists on Monday questioned  
whether the fatal police shooting of former NFL linebacker 
Demetrius DuBose was racially motivated, saying witness statements 
indicated the black athlete may have been shot in the back. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not think the gentleman did anything to provoke the  
shooting,'' said H.J. Sims of the National Association for the 
Advancement of Colored People in San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	Conflicting accounts of the July 24 killing have prompted the  
family of the 28-year-old DuBose, who played for the Tampa Bay 
Buccaneers, to request an autopsy independent of the police probe 
and to hire an attorney to conduct a private investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego police Chief David Bejarano said he welcomes outside  
input and expects an internal investigation to be completed within 
two weeks. Results, which will include toxicology results, will be 
turned over to the district attorney's office, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-2-inch DuBose was shot several times by police  
officers after he allegedly charged at officers with nunchakus, a 
martial arts weapon that he took away from an officer, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers, who were investigating a burglary call in  
predominantly white Mission Beach, claim DuBose resisted officers' 
attempts to question him and appeared to be under the influence of 
alcohol or other drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	But preliminary findings of the family's investigation show  
DuBose was initially calm and cooperated with officers until they 
began to ``intimidate and harass'' him, likely because he was 
black, Sims said. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the police first arrived the gentleman was patient for  
about five to 10 minutes,'' Sims said. ``It was only after they 
tried to place him in handcuffs that the unprofessionalism of 
police allowed the situation to escalate and prompted the gentleman 
to run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before the shooting, DuBose had played volleyball and drank  
beer, ``but beer and volleyball are kind of like peanut butter and 
jelly,'' Sims said. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego City Councilmen George Stevens and Byron Wear are also  
calling for a thorough investigation into the shooting to allay any 
concerns that it was unjustified. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens noted some people have said DuBose was bending over when  
the accident happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``Others have said he was turning away. I would hope the autopsy  
would show where the first shot entered,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two officers who shot DuBose have been removed from field  
work pending the investigation. Their names have not been released. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose had been arrested three times in the past year.  
</P>
<P>
	The latest was June 14, when California Highway Patrol officers  
found DuBose ``very dazed, very confused'' in his car parked on the 
side of a highway near Mammoth Lakes, said Mono County prosecutor 
Tim Kendall. 
</P>
<P>
	After conducting field sobriety tests and observing ``white  
powdery substance dripping from his nose,'' officers determined he 
was under the influence of PCP, Kendall said. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose became increasingly agitated as the investigation went  
on, but officers were able to get him handcuffed, Kendall said. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose also was reportedly under the influence of an unknown  
drug Feb. 3, when he allegedly forced his way into a Mammoth Lakes 
restaurant after being denied entrance several times, Kendall said. 
</P>
<P>
	In August 1998, DuBose, who played at Notre Dame, was arrested  
in South Bend, Ind., after he became belligerent at a nightclub. 
When an off-duty police officer ordered him to leave, DuBose 
allegedly grabbed a pipe from an overhead sprinkler system -- 
flooding the club with some 1,600 gallons of water. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 19:52:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  McGwire Tires of Stats, Milestones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Mark McGwire is tiring of stats and milestones,  
but a big one is coming up. He's just two homers from the 500 home 
run club. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fascination with numbers started when rotisserie baseball  
became big probably 10 years ago,'' McGwire said. ``There's stats 
coming out of the woodwork that nobody ever knew about that I think 
sometimes blow things way out of proportion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire has set a few of those lately, such as most homers over  
a four- and five-year period. Last month he broke Joe Adcock's NL 
record with 16 homers in July. 
</P>
<P>
	He's hit 221 homers since 1996 and 259 since 1995, both records,  
naturally. He's second on the career list for homers by a first 
baseman with 483, 10 behind Lou Gehrig. 
</P>
<P>
	He almost assuredly will break Babe Ruth's record of reaching  
500 in the fewest at-bats, since he's at 5,478 and Ruth needed 
5,801. 
</P>
<P>
	His reaction? Statistics are for geeks.  
</P>
<P>
	``The only stats you look at with power hitters are driving in  
runs and hitting home runs,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire entered Tuesday night's game in a sprint for 500, having  
hit 14 homers in 18 games, including No. 498 against San Diego on 
Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	But he acts as if there's no special incentive, even though only  
15 players have reached 500, and all are in the Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing to feel,'' he said. ``It's going to happen one  
day. I don't know when.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He feels the same way about Tony Gwynn's quest for 3,000 hits,  
which is being played out in front of him the next three days. 
Gwynn got his 2,995th hit, a two-run single in the ninth inning, in 
the Cardinals' 6-5 victory Monday, but McGwire said he and Gwynn 
didn't discuss their parallel chases at first base. 
</P>
<P>
	``How much is there to talk about?'' McGwire said. ``There's no  
reason to talk about 500 until you get there and there's no reason 
to talk about 3,000 until he gets to 3,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a level you reach. People have done it before, so  
it's just a milestone he's going to reach. What day, what hour, 
what minute, it's just a matter of time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The way McGwire is going, he'll get to 500 very soon. After a  
slow start, he was only four homers off his record 70-homer pace of 
last year and chances for him reaching his milestone before Gwynn 
appeared good. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Cardinals began a seven-game homestand Friday, McGwire  
needed six homers and Gwynn needed nine hits, and McGwire said he 
basically had no chance of getting there first. Evidence to the 
contrary, he's sticking to that prediction. 
</P>
<P>
	``Getting hits is a little bit easier than hitting home runs,  
believe me,'' McGwire said. ``But you guys write it like it's easy. 
I think people take me for granted because I hit them in such 
streaks. They don't realize how tough it is.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 19:52:04 </DATE_TIME>
