<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> KLM Profit Slides 64 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Profits at the Dutch flag carrier  
KLM tumbled 64 percent in its first fiscal quarter, excluding a 
one-time gain, a decline the company blamed on an overall slowdown 
in the global airline industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Without the one-time gain of $433.8 million on the sale of its  
stake in Galileo International, a global airline ticketing company, 
KLM earned $37.2 million compared to $102.4 million in the same 
period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales dropped slightly to $1.6 billion from $1.7 billion a year  
earlier. Earnings per share fell to 59 cents from $1.38. 
</P>
<P>
	``Competitive conditions and excess capacity within the airline  
industry rather than the global macro-economic environment are the 
drivers of the current situation,'' KLM said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Amsterdam-based airline, which has alliances with Northwest  
and Alitalia of Italy, said that the current airline market is 
``more difficult'' than it has been in a long time and added that 
excess capacity, especially on North Atlantic routes, was 
continually pressuring profit margins. 
</P>
<P>
	KLM's shares fell 2.6 percent on the Amsterdam stock exchange  
following the news. Traders already had offloaded KLM shares after 
an internal memo on an Internet website leaked part of the results 
last week. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
