<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston To Join Cardinals Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. (AP) -- Newly signed rookie receiver David  
Boston will join Arizona Cardinals training camp Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston held out for four days and inked a four year, $7 million  
deal with the club. His sister and agent, Dallas attorney Alicia 
Boston, said Monday that the Cardinals compromised on length -- four 
instead of five years -- while David compromised on the ``bells and 
whistles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boston received a $3.8 million signing bonus.  
</P>
<P>
	``I wish it would have happened earlier. It'll be a set of fresh  
legs to run seam routes down the middle. He's going to be a key 
part of the offense,'' Cardinals quarterback Jake Plummer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You ask Randy Moss what kind of impact (a rookie) can have,''  
wide receiver Frank Sanders said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	While nobody is realistically comparing Boston to Moss -- Cards  
coach Vince Tobin rolled his eyes when asked how Boston compared 
with the Vikings rookie of the year from 1998 -- all involved see 
the potential for Boston to be a game-breaking threat who can 
stretch the field for quarterback Plummer. 
</P>
<P>
	Offensive coordinator Mark Trestman said Boston will serve as a  
backup to Rob Moore, who is still holding out of camp and will 
function in a different role when the team introduces 
three-receiver sets. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest thing is to see how all three of us can function  
on the field together,'' Sanders said. ``For David, the sky is the 
limit. He has the potential to do it all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boston missed most of the team's June rookie camp in Tempe with  
a shoulder injury, so he already was behind the rest of the team in 
terms of learning the offense. He also has missed nine practices in 
an abbreviated training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited to have David in here, no question,'' Tobin said.  
``We expect him to make a big contribution. In order for him to do 
that, he's got to get to camp and learn the system and get reps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Trestman: ``He's basically starting from scratch. But he's  
a smart kid and a fast learner. I don't anticipate it will take him 
very long to get into the swing of things.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
