<DOCNO> APW19990803.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 13:50:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tips for Proper Use of Sunscreen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Cancer experts' advice on staying safe in the sun:  

</P>
<P>
	--Avoid sun between 10 a.m. and 2 p.m., its most intense hours.  
</P>
<P>
	--Wear sunscreen with a sun-protection factor of at least 15.  
</P>
<P>
	--Choose sunscreens that protect against both UVA and UVB  
radiation. Check the labels on sunscreens and pick the ones that 
contain at least one of these ingredients: benzophenone, 
oxybenzone, sulisobenzone, titanium dioxide, zinc oxide or 
avobenzone. 
</P>
<P>
	--Apply sunscreen generously at least 20 minutes before any  
outdoor physical activity. Sweating reduces the effectiveness of 
sunscreens so reapply often. Always reapply after swimming. 
</P>
<P>
	--At the beach or playground, try to stay in the shade. Sit under  
an umbrella or tree. 
</P>
<P>
	--Cover skin in tightly woven, loose-fitting, light-colored  
clothes. 
</P>
<P>
	--Wear sunglasses that protect from ultraviolet radiation. Such  
glasses carry a UVB or UVA sticker. 
</P>
<P>
	--Wear wide-brimmed hats to protect the face, ears and neck,  
which burn most often. 
</P>
<P>
	--Take special care protecting children, keeping children under  
the age of one out of the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	--Don't assume you can't be burned just because it is cloudy or  
overcast. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 08:36:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indonesian Elections Declared Legit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Frustrated by drawn out political  
infighting, Indonesia's president today declared the results of a 
historic June 7 parliamentary election legitimate after feuding 
electoral officials failed to release them. 
</P>
<P>
	President B.J. Habibie made the announcement at the State Palace  
where officials from 23 parties and senior Cabinet ministers had 
gathered for talks on constitutional and legislative reform. He 
will sign a formal decree Wednesday, said Information Minister 
Yunus Yosfiah. 
</P>
<P>
	By midday today Indonesia's General Election Commission had  
still not released the results. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Habibie's statement, commission chairman Rudini, a  
retired army general who uses only one name, told reporters his 
organization must endorse the figures before they can be declared 
official. 
</P>
<P>
	The final figures are expected to closely mirror previously  
released unofficial tallies that gave Megawati Sukarnoputri's 
Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle a clear lead with 34 
percent of the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling Golkar Party, which underpinned Suharto's reign and  
now backs his onetime protege, Habibie, came in second in the 
unofficial counts with 22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I declare the results of the June elections are legitimate,''  
Habibie said. 
</P>
<P>
	It has been nearly two months since Indonesians voted in the  
elections, regarded as crucial to the Southeast Asian nation's 
democratization and the selection of a new head of state after 
decades of authoritarian rule under ex-President Suharto. 
</P>
<P>
	Vote counting ended July 26 after weeks of bureaucratic bungling  
and painfully slow procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia's major parties and independent observers accepted the  
results as valid. However, they were blocked after a group of small 
parties claimed the election had been unfair and refused to sign 
off on the tally. 
</P>
<P>
	An election watchdog committee later threw out 100,000  
allegations of irregularities. 
</P>
<P>
	Habibie intervened in the dispute after pleading several times  
with electoral officials to bury their differences and release the 
results. 
</P>
<P>
	The president, who wants a second term, called on Indonesians to  
focus now on the selection of a head of state. 
</P>
<P>
	Newly elected lawmakers, military appointees and regional and  
interest group representatives are to form a special 700-member 
assembly to select a president in November. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 08:36:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
