<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Acts on Small Business Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House approved two bills Monday aimed at  
improving Small Business Administration loan programs for 
businesses unable to secure financing through normal channels. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the bills increases the maximum loans under the SBA's  
Loan Guaranty Program from $750,000 to $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would also increase the guarantee percentage on loans  
of $150,000 or less from 75 percent to 80 percent. The 80 percent 
guarantee currently applies only to loans of $100,000 or less. 
</P>
<P>
	The second bill expands the SBA's program helping small  
businesses with long-term loans for major fixed assets such as land 
or buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	It increases the maximum regular loan from $750,000 to $1  
million and public policy loans from $1 million to $1.3 million. It 
makes businesses owned by women eligible for the policy loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Both bills, passed by voice, require Senate consideration.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bills are H.R. 2614 and H.R. 2615.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
