<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sharpe Complains About Long Flight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- His eyes were bleary after a long  
flight to Australia, and Denver Broncos tight end Shannon Sharpe 
was clearly unhappy. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one should be made to have to fly 17 hours and play a  
football game,'' Sharpe said after the team arrived in Sydney for 
an exhibition game Friday against the San Diego Chargers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sorry, Mr. Tagliabue,'' he said, referring to commissioner  
Paul Tagliabue. ``You need to address this in our upcoming 
meetings. This is utterly ridiculous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Broncos left Denver late Sunday after a 45-minute delay when  
newly signed offensive lineman Scott Adams realized he had left his 
passport in his rental car at the Broncos training facility. 
</P>
<P>
	An Arapahoe County sheriff's official had to break into the car  
and rush the document back to the airport, but the team left 44 
minutes late on the 2 1/2-hour flight to Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Next came a 14 1/2-hour flight to Sydney. The team essentially  
missed Monday because of the time difference, arriving at their 
hotel this morning. Less than 90 minutes later, they were back on 
the bus and headed to a field for their first of four days of 
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough, it's tough,'' running back Terrell Davis said  
after a light workout later in the day. ``I feel like I just woke 
up. My body is not ready to come out here and run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he added, ``I think by tomorrow we'll be OK.''  
</P>
<P>
	Sharpe wasn't so sure.  
</P>
<P>
	He said the compressed schedule left no time for sightseeing and  
museum-going. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Broncos coach) Mike (Shanahan) was trying to make this as  
enjoyable as possible, but there is very little enjoyment you get 
out of a situation like this. Trust me, I've tried.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Today the Broncos had their first full practice in pads.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
