<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Canada Banks Plan Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- TD Bank has agreed to buy the holding company  
that owns Canada Trust in a $5 billion deal that links two of the 
leaders of Canada's financial industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger is part of an effort to restructure the Imasco  
consumer products and services company, which owns CT Financial 
Services, Canada trust's parent company. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger is conditional on the completion of a multi-stage  
transaction involving Imasco and British American Tobacco, the 
British tobacco company that owns 42 per cent of Imasco. Under an 
agreement that had been rumored since early June, BAT will make an 
offer for all the common shares of Imasco that it does not already 
own. 
</P>
<P>
	Imasco also owns Shopper's Drug Mart and Imperial Tobacco.  
</P>
<P>
	If Imasco shareholders accept BAT's offer, BAT has agreed to  
sell 100 per cent of CT Financial Services to the TD Bank Financial 
Group. 
</P>
<P>
	If the sale goes through, the retail banking operations of TD  
and Canada Trust would be merged under the name TD Canada Trust. 
</P>
<P>
	The transactions are conditional on various shareholder and  
regulatory approvals. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the reason for the shuffle of some of Canada's  
best-known corporate assets was BAT's desire to concentrate on its 
core business in tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	Market observers have predicted the British company would sell  
off Imasco's non-tobacco assets after taking it private and keep 
Imperial Tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	``BAT's 1997 decision to concentrate exclusively on the tobacco  
business means that their business focus is now considerably 
narrower than Imasco's,'' Imasco President Brian Levitt said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	British American Tobacco, the world's No. 2 cigarette company,  
just completed an $8.2 billion acquisition of a smaller rival, 
Rothmans International NV, in June. BAT aims to become the world's 
leading international tobacco company. 
</P>
<P>
	The Imasco deal would make BAT the biggest cigarette maker in  
Canada but won't affect its global sales volumes. BAT's results 
already include 100 percent of Imperial Tobacco's sales volumes but 
only 42 percent of Imperial's profit. By buying the additional 
shares in Imasco, BAT would benefit from an additional $160 million 
to its annual cash flow, said Denise Hart, a BAT spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	BAT makes brands including Kent and Lucky Strike. Its  
acquisition of Rothmans, the world's fourth-biggest cigarette 
producer, gives it a 16 percent share of the global cigarette 
market, just behind Philip Morris Cos., which has 17 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0353 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 07:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Talk Magazine Celebrates Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Madonna, Henry Kissinger and Paul Newman were  
among the headliners partying at the Statue of Liberty to celebrate 
editor Tina Brown's latest publishing venture, a new glossy 
magazine called Talk. 
</P>
<P>
	Noticeably absent Monday night were Hillary Rodham Clinton,  
featured on the debut cover, and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who made 
the revelers move their soiree from Brooklyn. 
</P>
<P>
	Actress Sarah Jessica Parker said she had received a glimpse of  
Talk and liked it: ``It's a smart, provocative and well-thought-out 
magazine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The gala was moved to Liberty Island after plans for a Brooklyn  
Navy Yard bash were nixed by Giuliani. The mayor said the 
city-owned Navy Yard isn't suitable for private parties, but his 
critics have said he was more miffed at Mrs. Clinton's appearance 
on the magazine's cover. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, possibly Giuliani's rival for the U.S. Senate seat  
being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, shares the 
cover with a skimpily clad Oscar-winner Gwyneth Paltrow and a 
grinning Texas Gov. George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Brown, reveling in the spotlight Monday, teasingly thanked  
the mayor for the publicity. She said Mrs. Clinton was unable to 
attend because of a prior commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	Talk had already grabbed international headlines for its  
interview with Mrs. Clinton, in which the first lady discusses her 
marriage and her husband's infidelity. The first issue hits 
newsstands today. 
</P>
<P>
	A disc jockey entertained the hundreds of celebrities,  
politicians, literary types and fashion trendsetters, who munched 
on chicken served in baskets at the foot of Lady Liberty. Fireworks 
lit the sky. 
</P>
<P>
	Guests included Salman Rushdie, Lauren Bacall, Demi Moore,  
Elizabeth Hurley, Hugh Grant, Matthew Broderick, Queen Latifah, 
Kevin Bacon, Kate Moss, Pierce Brosnan, Liam Neeson and Natasha 
Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Brown was editor of Vanity Fair and The New Yorker, both  
members of the Conde Nast magazine family. 
</P>
<P>
	Talk has the backing of the Miramax movie studio and a  
partnership with the Hearst magazine publishing empire. The 
magazine, which costs $2.95, will have an initial circulation of 
500,000 copies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990803.0354 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 07:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Talk Magazine Celebrates Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Madonna, Henry Kissinger and Paul Newman were  
among the headliners partying at the Statue of Liberty to celebrate 
editor Tina Brown's latest publishing venture, a new glossy 
