<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Tests N.Y. Local Phone Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T is quietly offering local telephone service  
to some consumers in New York, becoming the second major 
long-distance company to enter that Bell Atlantic market this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Opting for a more gradual approach than MCI WorldCom, AT&AMP;T is  
looking to sign up just 6,000 of its 5 million New York customers 
at first, and only in the New York City area and Albany. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T said Tuesday it began calling up its long-distance  
customers in those markets on Monday evening, offering a fixed-rate 
package for local and long-distance service. 
</P>
<P>
	For $24.90 a month, an AT&AMP;T customer in New York can get 75  
hours of local calling time and long-distance service for an 
additional 10 cents per minute. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom introduced local service in New York back in  
February, offering a package of 100 calls for $14.99 a month in the 
New York City area and $19.99 in less densely populated areas where 
Bell Atlantic charges more to lease its lines. In early June, MCI 
WorldCom reported having 75,000 local customers in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T's maneuver, its first local offering to most New York  
consumers in 15 years, comes amid a bitter, state-by-state battle 
between long-distance providers and regional ``Baby Bell'' 
monopolies created by the government in the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell Atlantic and the other Bells have been pushing hard for  
government clearance to sell long-distance to their residential 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	They insist that rivals can now easily lease the Bell wires  
connected to people's homes and sell local service -- the main goal 
of a 1996 law designed to spark competition and choice consumers 
now enjoy in long-distance calling. 
</P>
<P>
	But AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom and Sprint charge that the Bells are  
still too slow and unreliable in filling orders for customers 
wanting to switch their local service. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, despite the new initiative into New York and an  
existing one in Texas, the main thrust of AT&AMP;T's overall strategy 
is to provide telephone and Internet service through cable TV wires 
rather than the Bell networks. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T has committed more than $100 billion to that plan, having  
decided that ownership of the connections to people's homes is 
preferrable to leasing arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	Since last summer, AT&AMP;T has assembled a ``local'' network  
covering about 60 percent of the country, buying two of the 
nation's four biggest cable companies and partnering up with the 
other two. 
</P>
<P>
	But, since it's unlikely that regulators would allow AT&AMP;T to  
create a national cable monopoly, the company will need to lease 
some Bell lines to reach consumers. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
