<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Zapruder Heirs To Get $16M for Film  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Arbitrators declared today the government must  
pay the heirs of Abraham Zapruder $16 million for film that 
Zapruder took of the assassination of President Kennedy, the 
Justice Department said. The Zapruder family had asked for $30 
million. The government offered $1 million. The government has to 
compensate the Zapruder family because the Assassination Records 
Review Board in 1997 declared the film the permanent possession of 
the people of the United States. The decision cannot be appealed. 
Zapruder filmed the assassination while standing on a concrete 
abutment along the route of the president's motorcade through 
Dallas. 

</P>
<P>
	Rory Kennedy Weds in Athens  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Rory Kennedy, whose wedding was postponed  
after the death of her cousin John F. Kennedy Jr., was married in a 
private ceremony at the home of a Greek shipping magnate, the 
shipowner's office confirmed today. Ms. Kennedy married Mark Bailey 
last night on the grounds of the family compound of shipowner 
Vardis Vardinoyiannis. Kennedy Jr., along with his wife and 
sister-in-law, were killed July 16 when his plane crashed en route 
to Hyannis Port, Mass., for the wedding. Ms. Kennedy, 30, is the 
last of 11 children born to Ethel and the late Sen. Robert Kennedy. 

</P>
<P>
	India's Railway Minister Resigns  
</P>
<P>
	GAISAL, India (AP) -- India's railway minister resigned today, a  
day after a train collision left more than 250 people dead, saying 
the country hadn't spent enough money to upgrade the system. 
Railway Minister Nitish Kumar said one of the trains involved in 
yesterday's crash was on the wrong track for an unknown reason, and 
said the accident was caused by ``criminal negligence.'' At least 
257 bodies have been removed from the mangled wreckage. About 50 
more people were thought to be inside three smashed train cars, but 
authorities feared that none could have survived. 

</P>
<P>
	Butler Chides Annan on Arms Probes  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Former U.N. weapons chief Richard Butler  
says that the weapons inspection operation he headed was ``a thorn 
in the side'' of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and that Annan 
tried to destroy it. In an interview in the new Talk magazine, 
Butler said Annan repeatedly confused Iraqi President Saddam 
Hussein's ``superficial cooperation'' with U.N. weapons inspectors 
``with substantive compliance'' on Baghdad's disarmament 
obligations. Butler pulled U.N. inspectors out of Iraq in 
mid-December prior to U.S. airstrikes on Baghdad, and Iraqi 
officials have banned them from returning. 

</P>
<P>
	Twins Admit to Shooting Father  
</P>
<P>
	HENDERSON, N.C. (AP) -- Eleven-year-old twins have admitted that  
they fatally shot their father and wounded their mother and sister 
four months ago. Originally charged with first-degree murder, the 
boys entered pleas yesterday to lesser charges and avoided a public 
trial. Their identities were not released. The maximum sentence 
would be confinement in a juvenile facility until they are 18. 
Prosecutors say the shooting occurred when the boys' mother found a 
rifle under their bed and tried to take it. One twin wrestled with 
his mom for the rifle, while the other shot her with a .38 caliber 
pistol. 

</P>
<P>
	Leading Economic Indicators Rise  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The index of leading economic indicators rose  
0.3 from 107.4 to 107.7 in June, suggesting that the U.S. economy 
will keep on growing. The report from the Conference Board 
indicates the economy could be in its longest expansion ever. The 
growth should last through the early part of next year. The 
economic indicators have risen in eight of the last nine months. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 9  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before noon EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 9.50 to 10,655.46. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,598-1,070. The Nasdaq was down 27.96 to 
2,595.67. 

</P>
<P>
	Celtics, Nuggets Make 6-Player Swap  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Boston Celtics and Denver Nuggets completed a  
major six-player deal that will send Celtics guard Ron Mercer to 
Denver for power forward Danny Fortson. The Celtics traded Mercer, 
Popeye Jones and Dwayne Schintzius to Denver for Fortson, Eric 
Washington, and Eric Williams. The Celtics will also receive a 
first-round pick. Mercer and Fortson will be free agents after the 
upcoming season. Mercer, who averaged 17 points last season, said 
there was a ``huge difference'' between the Celtics' contract offer 
and what he was asking. Fortson was fourth in the league in 
rebounding with a 11.6 per game average last year. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
