<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Self Possessed a Favorite at Hambo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Self Possessed will be a heavy favorite in the $1 million  
Hambletonian in more ways than one. 
</P>
<P>
	Most experts contend the only way Self Possessed can lose  
trotting's most prestigious race is if the colt goes off stride 
Saturday at the Meadowlands Racetrack in East Rutherford, N.J. He 
has done that before. 
</P>
<P>
	That's where the weight comes in.  
</P>
<P>
	Ron Gurfein, the training guru who has combined with driver Mike  
Lachance to win two Hambletonians since 1994, isn't taking any 
chances with Self Possessed, one of the fastest trotters in a long 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Because he's so fast, the colt is more apt to break stride,  
which is what happened in the Budweiser Beacon Course Trot on July 
16. The result was a fourth-place finish behind winner CR Renegade. 
</P>
<P>
	Gurfein found a solution in last weekend's Hambletonian  
eliminations. He changed Self Possessed's shoes, making them a 
little heavier. He also changed the sulky, chucking a modern one 
for a steel one similar to the one used by Victory Dream -- Self 
Possessed's father -- in winning the '94 Hambo. 
</P>
<P>
	The result was a 6-length victory over CR Renegade.  
</P>
<P>
	``We made some changes to make it easier on his feet, his knees  
and his splints,'' Gurfein said. ``He was much more comfortable the 
following week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lachance said the difference in the Beacon Course final and the  
Hambletonian elimination was like night and day. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was much safer, more relaxed and much easier to drive,''  
Lachance, who also combined with Gurfein to win the '96 
Hambletonian with Continentalvictory. ``He probably has more speed 
than anybody in the race, but it's not going to be an easy race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Self Possessed, who has won three of five starts this year and  
twice matched the Meadowlands record for 3-year-old trotters 
(1.52.2), had a good day on Tuesday, getting the No. 4 post 
position in the draw at the racetrack. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Hambletonian, Self Possessed will be coupled with Angus  
Hall and Raffaello Ambrosio. Gurfein also trains Raffaello 
Ambrosio, while there is some common ownership between Angus Hall 
and Self Possessed. The entry is an overwhelming 3-5 morning line 
favorite. 
</P>
<P>
	Angus Hall, who will be driven by John Campbell from the No. 9  
post, won last weekend's other Hambletonian elimination in 1:54.3, 
more than a second slower than Self Possessed's time of 1:53. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is definitely the horse to beat going in, there is no  
question about that,'' Campbell said of Self Possessed. He has a 
lot of ability. I wish we had drawn better, but it's just a 
starting point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell drove to an unprecedented fifth Hambletonian victory  
last year with Muscles Yankee. 
</P>
<P>
	The entry of CR Renegade and CR Commando is the 7-2 second  
choice. 
</P>
<P>
	CR Renegade drew the No. 1 post position for driver Rod Allen,  
CR Commando got the No. 3 post for driver Carl Allen, Rod's father 
and the trainer of both colts. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting between them will be Cherry Hills, a 12-1 longshot  
driven by Dave Palone. 
</P>
<P>
	After Self Possessed in the No. 4 post, the rest of the field  
with colt, driver, and odds: 
</P>
<P>
	Comets Tail, Berndt Lindstedt, 15-1; Pearsall Hanover, Mickey  
McNichol, 15-1; Enjoy Lavec, Luc Ouellette, 9-2; Davanti, Doug 
Ackerman, 20-1; Angus Hall, Campbell, 3-5; Raffaello Ambrosio, Jack 
Moiseyev, 3-5. 
</P>
<P>
	Post time for scheduled for 3:43 p.m. EDT.  
</P>
<P>
	Oolong, an impressive 4-length winner in her elimination last  
week, was made the lukewarm 3-1 favorite for the $500,000 
Hambletonian Oaks, which is also on Saturday's card. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
