<HEADLINE> Malaysian Airlines Loses $168M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Malaysian Airlines, the country's  
national carrier, suffered a $168.2 million loss in the 1998-99 
financial year, Parliament was told Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Transport Minister Ling Liong Sik cited increases in fuel prices  
and reduced traffic flow as reasons for the loss, the Bernama news 
agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic flights alone recorded losses of $263,000 a day during  
the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ling said Malaysian Airlines did not plan to increase fares. He  
also said the airline was selling aircraft to recover some of the 
losses. 
  	   	
</P>
