<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. City Backs Death Penalty Halt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- The city council passed a resolution calling  
on President Clinton, Congress and state officials to halt all 
executions, and its supporters say Durham is the largest city in 
the nation to adopt such a measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The council voted 8-3 Monday night to encourage a moratorium on  
executions until laws ensure that death penalty cases are 
administered fairly and prevent the execution of mentally retarded 
people and people who were under 18 at the time of their crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This vote is going to be noticed by people all over the world  
and especially all over the United States,'' said Stephen Dear, 
executive director of People of Faith Against the Death Penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Council members in Durham, population 175,000, said they were  
most concerned about the number of minority and poor people 
executed since the Supreme Court allowed the death penalty to 
resume 23 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other North Carolina cities, Carrboro and Chapel Hill,  
approved similar resolutions in June. They came after a North 
Carolina judge overturned a man's murder conviction and death 
sentence, saying he was falsely accused and authorities withheld 
evidence of his innocence. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, Nebraska Gov. Mike Johanns vetoed a bill that would have  
made his state the first to place a moratorium on executions while 
officials studied whether the death penalty is being applied 
fairly. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers in other states, including North Carolina, have  
considered but not approved moratoriums, which also have been 
encouraged by the American Bar Association. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
