<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Blair Witch' Good for Indie Films </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- No big stars? Tiny budget? No problem. ``The  
Blair Witch Project'' is proving that a movie shot for $60,000 can 
still conjure up a monster hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Seemingly coming from nowhere, the horror film went into wide  
release over the weekend and took in $29.2 million -- second only to 
Julia Roberts and Richard Gere's ``Runaway Bride.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The movie's success has reminded a blockbuster-crazy movie  
industry that sometimes, the next best thing in the cinema doesn't 
follow the formulaic route. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no words to describe it,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, a  
movie-industry analyst for Reel Source Inc. ``I'm at a loss for 
words on what this film has done for the whole industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Playing in barely a third as many theaters as ``Runaway Bride,''  
``Blair Witch'' averaged $26,528 a screen, nearly 2.5 times that of 
the romantic comedy, according to Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc., 
which tracks ticket sales. 
</P>
<P>
	And while ``Runaway Bride'' took in $35.1 million, about half of  
its production costs, in just one weekend, ``Blair Witch'' has 
grossed $36.1 million -- 100 times what the filmmakers and their 
distributor spent to produce it. 
</P>
<P>
	``This helps the industry, because it shows you there's a  
business out there,'' said Tom Sherak, distribution head for 20th 
Century Fox. ``It kind of stops the complacency where everything 
has to have a big budget, and you have to get this person to 
star.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Filmmakers Eduardo Sanchez and Daniel Myrick shot ``Blair  
Witch'' for about $60,000, while distributor Artisan Entertainment 
poured in $300,000 more for other production costs, said Amir 
Malin, Artisan president. 
</P>
<P>
	A fictional movie, ``Blair Witch'' presents itself as a  
documentary pieced together from video shot by three filmmakers who 
disappeared in the woods while hunting for a witch. 
</P>
<P>
	The marketing has played on that ``mockumentary'' notion,  
leaving some moviegoers guessing about whether the horror story is 
real or imagined. Word-of-mouth reviews and the Internet helped 
fuel interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Artisan bought ``Blair Witch'' for $1 million after the  
distributor's executives saw it at the Sundance film festival, 
Malin said. He said the company has spent $10 million on 
distribution and promotion, still relatively cheap by Hollywood 
blockbuster standards. 
</P>
<P>
	And with the movie expanding from 1,100 theaters to about 2,000  
next weekend, ``Blair Witch'' was expected to easily gross more 
than $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Blair Witch'' could even become the most successful film ever  
in terms of return on initial investment, said Tom Borys, president 
of box-office tracker ACNielsen EDI Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every now and then, a small film does break through. But  
there's been nothing before of this magnitude,'' Borys said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollywood always searches for independent films that might have  
commercial appeal, but ``Blair Witch'' might make big studios 
``reexamine what they can do to find those gems,'' Borys said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Blair Witch'' could become a franchise film for Artisan, whose  
previous best box-office performer was Wes Craven's ``Wishmaster.'' 
That film made $18.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Artisan already has plan for a ``Blair Witch'' sequel, and the  
distributor is cleaning up on T-shirts, books and other merchandise 
related to the movie. 
</P>
<P>
	Big movie studios are taking heed.  
</P>
<P>
	``You don't need to make movies for $100 million, you don't need  
to spend $25 million in marketing and distribution,'' Malin said. 
``What audiences really want is something fresh that's not 
derivative in nature.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
